{ao:"Capstone",q:"What did the educator in the story build instead of a standard CV to demonstrate their expertise?",o:["A complete, functional blueprint of an inclusive classroom combining SEN profiling, curriculum adaptation, an IEP, and more","A two-page text summary with no practical detail","A single certificate with no other supporting material","A list of unrelated hobbies and interests"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"What is Universal Design for Learning (UDL)?",o:["A framework for planning curriculum accessibility for a wide range of learners from the start, rather than retrofitting adaptations later","A single fixed lesson plan used for every student without variation","A synonym for standardized testing","A behaviour management punishment system"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"Why does a complete, integrated inclusive framework have strong portfolio value, according to this unit?",o:["A concrete, demonstrable plan is more convincing and more useful in practice than a general description of good intentions","It removes the need for any further professional development","It guarantees a specific salary regardless of quality","It is required by law in every country"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"What four components did the educator's capstone project combine, according to the story?",o:["An SEN profile analysis, an adapted curriculum module, a data-driven IEP, and a behaviour/technology matrix","Only a single lesson plan with no other elements","Only a certificate of attendance","A list of unrelated academic theories with no application"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"What was the outcome for the educator who built this comprehensive capstone project?",o:["They won the Inclusion Director position with a strong compensation package","They were rejected for lacking sufficient documentation","They were asked to redo the entire project from scratch","The hiring committee found the project irrelevant"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"What does a behaviour management matrix or assistive technology map do, according to the Key Ideas?",o:["Makes a teacher's intentions concrete and specific, rather than a vague general statement","Replaces the need for any actual classroom implementation","Removes the need for an IEP entirely","Applies only to physical education classes"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"What was the international hiring committee's reaction to the educator's presentation, according to the story?",o:["They were genuinely impressed, since the graduate presented a functional blueprint rather than abstract claims","They were unimpressed and rejected the application immediately","They ignored the presentation entirely","They requested a completely different type of application"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"According to the unit, what should a complete inclusive framework bring together?",o:["Every skill covered in the course into one coherent plan for a specific learner or classroom","Only a single isolated topic with no integration","Unrelated administrative tasks","Only test scores with no instructional planning"],a:0},
{ao:"Capstone",q:"What principle, emphasized throughout this entire course, underlies the value of the final capstone project?",o:["A concrete, demonstrable plan is far more convincing and useful than a general description of good intentions","Certificates alone are always sufficient proof of expertise","Portfolio projects are optional and rarely matter","Vague intentions are just as valuable as concrete plans"],a:0}
