// ═══ STUDENT LEARNING JOURNEYS (Sociology Year 10) ═══
// Three term journeys, each ~3 months, teacher-style structure with practice
// checks (which never count toward the assessment) and a 100-question term
// assessment at 65% to pass, 60-minute timer. Students must APPLY per subject
// and be APPROVED by the admin before starting. Admins bypass the gate.
const SOC10T1_UNITS=[
 {id:"t1u1",n:1,title:"What is Sociology?",mins:180,icon:"Target",
  summary:"Meet the subject: what sociology studies, where it came from, and how sociologists think differently from everyday guessing.",
  keyWords:["sociology","society","institution","Auguste Comte","social facts","verstehen"],
  sections:[
   {art:"society",h:"Sociology, in plain words",p:[
    "Sociology is the study of society. It looks at how people behave in groups, how we relate to each other, and how big institutions like the family, school and the law shape our lives.",
    "The key idea is this: you are not only an individual. Society influences what you believe, how you speak, what you want, and even what you think is normal. Sociology studies that influence."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a sociological question",b:["Everyday question: \u201CWhy did Ada do well in her exams?\u201D \u2014 answer: she is clever.","Sociological question: \u201CWhy do students from some backgrounds do better in exams than others?\u201D \u2014 answer needs evidence about family, money and schools.","Sociology moves from one person to the pattern."]}},
   {art:"science",h:"Where sociology came from",p:[
    "Sociology began in the 19th century, a time of huge change: factories, cities and revolutions. Auguste Comte, often called the father of sociology, said society should be studied scientifically, just like nature.",
    "\u00C9mile Durkheim built key ideas such as social facts \u2014 things outside us (like laws and customs) that still control our behaviour \u2014 and the importance of social cohesion, meaning what holds society together."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a social fact",b:["Nobody forces you to wear clothes to school, yet everyone does.","The rule exists outside any one person, but it shapes everyone\u2019s behaviour \u2014 that is a social fact.","Durkheim said we should study these facts like a scientist studies objects."]}},
   {art:"interpret",h:"Marx and Weber: two more founders",p:[
    "Karl Marx saw society as a contest between classes: a rich class that owns businesses and a working class that sells its labour. For Marx, the big story of society is inequality and conflict.",
    "Max Weber said we must also understand life from the inside. He used the word verstehen \u2014 interpretive understanding \u2014 meaning we should learn what actions MEAN to the people doing them, not just count them from outside."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the same strike, two views",b:["Marx would ask: which class gains and which loses from this strike?","Weber would ask: what does the strike mean to the workers \u2014 anger, hope, pride?","Both questions are sociological; they simply look from different angles."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Thinking like a sociologist",p:[
    "Sociologists refuse to accept \u2018everyone knows\u2019 answers. They ask for evidence, look for patterns across many people, and question the obvious.",
    "They also ask useful habits of questions: Who benefits from this arrangement? Is this really natural, or was it taught? Would this look different in another culture or time?"],
    ex:{t:"Example — questioning the obvious",b:["\u2018Boys are just naturally better at maths\u2019 sounds obvious to some people.","A sociologist checks the evidence: results change across countries and across decades \u2014 so teaching and expectations matter, not just nature.","Evidence beats assumption. That is the whole spirit of this course."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write down three \u2018everyone knows\u2019 statements you have heard about people (for example, about teenagers). For each one, write the sociological question you would ask to test whether it is really true.",
  check:[
   {q:"Sociology is best described as the study of\u2026",o:["Rocks and minerals","Society and how it shapes people\u2019s behaviour","Ancient languages","One person\u2019s private thoughts"],a:1},
   {q:"Who is often called the father of sociology?",o:["\u00c9mile Durkheim","Max Weber","Auguste Comte","Karl Marx"],a:2},
   {q:"Weber\u2019s idea of verstehen means\u2026",o:["Studying only laws","Ignoring people\u2019s feelings","Counting behaviour from outside","Understanding what actions mean to the people doing them"],a:3},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u2",n:2,title:"The Positivist Approach",mins:180,icon:"FlaskConical",
  summary:"Positivists study society like a science: big patterns, hard numbers, and rules of cause and effect.",
  keyWords:["positivism","scientific method","macro","social facts","quantitative data","causation","correlation","objectivity","reliability"],
  sections:[
   {art:"science",h:"Society as a science",p:[
    "Positivists believe society can be studied with the scientific method \u2014 the same careful, step-by-step testing used in physics or biology. Observe, measure, test, repeat.",
    "They take a macro view: instead of studying one person, they study large-scale structures and patterns \u2014 whole institutions, social classes, and trends across millions of people."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a positivist study",b:["A positivist wants to understand crime.","They collect crime statistics from many cities and compare them with poverty figures.","They are looking for a pattern across society, not one criminal\u2019s life story."]}},
   {art:"data",h:"Social facts and hard numbers",p:[
    "Positivists focus on social facts: features of social life \u2014 laws, norms, customs \u2014 that exist outside individuals but shape their actions. Because these facts are \u2018out there\u2019, they can be measured.",
    "Their favourite evidence is quantitative data: numbers that can be counted, compared and turned into statistics. Numbers make it easy to spot patterns and trends over time."],
    ex:{t:"Example — measuring a social fact",b:["Marriage customs are a social fact.","A positivist measures them with numbers: marriage rates per year, average age at first marriage, divorce rates.","The numbers reveal how the custom is changing across the whole society."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"Causation vs correlation",p:[
    "A correlation means two things change together \u2014 when one rises, the other rises (or falls). Causation means one thing actually MAKES the other happen. They are not the same.",
    "This is one of the most important ideas in research. Ice-cream sales and drowning both rise in summer \u2014 they correlate \u2014 but ice-cream does not cause drowning. Hot weather causes both."],
    ex:{t:"Example — spot the difference",b:["Finding: cities with more poverty have more crime. That is a correlation.","Does poverty CAUSE crime? Maybe \u2014 but a good positivist tests other explanations first (policing levels, age of population).","Never jump from \u2018changes together\u2019 to \u2018causes\u2019."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Objectivity and reliability",p:[
    "Positivists aim for objectivity: keeping personal opinions out of the research so the findings are unbiased. The researcher\u2019s feelings should not change the results.",
    "They also prize reliability: if another researcher repeats the study the same way, they should get the same results. Numbers and fixed methods make this repeat-test possible."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a reliable method",b:["A questionnaire with fixed questions is given to 1,000 students this year.","Next year another researcher gives the same questionnaire to 1,000 similar students.","If results match, the method is reliable \u2014 a big win for positivists."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Find one statistic about your country (for example, the literacy rate). Write one correlation someone might claim using it, and then explain why that correlation might NOT be causation.",
  check:[
   {q:"Positivists prefer which kind of data?",o:["Qualitative (feelings)","Quantitative (numbers)","Only photographs","Only diaries"],a:1},
   {q:"Two things rising together, without one causing the other, is called\u2026",o:["A social fact","Verstehen","A correlation","Causation"],a:2},
   {q:"Reliability means\u2026",o:["The study repeats with the same results","The topic is interesting","The sample is small","The study is about real feelings"],a:0},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u3",n:3,title:"The Interpretivist Approach",mins:180,icon:"Users",
  summary:"Interpretivists zoom in: small groups, real meanings, and understanding life from the inside.",
  keyWords:["interpretivism","micro","meanings","motivations","qualitative data","subjectivity","validity","verstehen"],
  sections:[
   {art:"interpret",h:"The micro view",p:[
    "Interpretivists study society close-up. Instead of big statistics, they take a micro view: individuals and small groups, everyday conversations, and personal experiences.",
    "Their central belief: people are not billiard balls pushed by outside forces. People act because of meanings and motivations \u2014 and to explain behaviour you must understand those meanings."],
    ex:{t:"Example — an interpretivist study",b:["Question: why do teenagers spend hours on social media?","An interpretivist sits with teenagers and asks long, open questions about what social media MEANS to them \u2014 friendship, status, escape.","Numbers alone could never reveal those meanings."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Qualitative data: rich and deep",p:[
    "Interpretivists collect qualitative data: words, stories, observations and detailed descriptions. This data is in-depth \u2014 it captures feelings and reasons that numbers miss.",
    "Common tools are unstructured interviews (open conversations) and observation (watching people in real settings). The goal is a true, detailed picture of a small slice of life."],
    ex:{t:"Example — depth over breadth",b:["A survey can tell you 40% of students feel stressed.","Ten long interviews can tell you WHY: exam pressure, family expectations, comparing themselves online.","Interpretivists trade the big number for the deep reason."]}},
   {art:"read",h:"Subjectivity and validity",p:[
    "Interpretivists accept subjectivity: everyone \u2014 including the researcher \u2014 sees the world from a personal viewpoint. Instead of pretending to be perfectly neutral, they try to understand viewpoints honestly.",
    "Their prize is validity: research that gives a true, genuine picture of what it claims to study. A study is valid when it captures real life, not an artificial version of it."],
    ex:{t:"Example — validity in action",b:["Students may tick \u2018I never skip homework\u2019 on a form (looks good, may be false).","Weeks of friendly observation in the school shows what really happens.","The observation is more valid \u2014 closer to the truth \u2014 even though it is harder to repeat."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"Positivism vs interpretivism: the see-saw",p:[
    "The two approaches trade strengths. Positivist methods are strong on reliability (repeatable) and patterns; weak on depth. Interpretivist methods are strong on validity (true meanings); weak on repeatability and size.",
    "You do not have to pick a winner. The exam rewards students who can explain WHY each approach would choose certain methods \u2014 and what each gains and gives up."],
    ex:{t:"Example — one topic, two designs",b:["Topic: bullying in schools.","Positivist: a survey across 20 schools counts how often bullying happens \u2014 patterns, comparison.","Interpretivist: a term inside one school, watching and talking \u2014 meaning, depth. Both designs teach us something different."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose a topic you care about (music, sport, gaming). Write one positivist research question about it (needing numbers) and one interpretivist question (needing meanings).",
  check:[
   {q:"Interpretivists take which view of society?",o:["Only legal","Micro \u2014 individuals and small groups","Only historical","Macro \u2014 whole structures"],a:1},
   {q:"Qualitative data is mainly\u2026",o:["Temperatures","Words, meanings and detailed descriptions","Numbers and percentages","Prices"],a:1},
   {q:"Which pairing is correct?",o:["Positivists\u2013validity; Interpretivists\u2013reliability","Positivists\u2013reliability; Interpretivists\u2013validity","Both only care about cost","Neither uses evidence"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u4",n:4,title:"Mixing Methods & Judging Research",mins:180,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"Triangulation, longitudinal studies, and the judging words every answer needs: bias, validity, reliability, representativeness and generalisability.",
  keyWords:["triangulation","longitudinal study","bias","interviewer effect","Hawthorne effect","representativeness","generalisability"],
  sections:[
   {art:"match",h:"Triangulation: cross-checking the truth",p:[
    "Triangulation means using more than one method in the same study \u2014 for example a survey PLUS interviews PLUS observation \u2014 and comparing the results.",
    "Each method has weaknesses; combining them lets one method cover another\u2019s blind spots. If all the methods point the same way, the findings are much stronger."],
    ex:{t:"Example — triangulating a study",b:["A study on career progress uses a survey (patterns), interviews (reasons) and company records (facts).","If the survey says people feel stuck AND the records show few promotions, the finding is trustworthy.","One method alone could be wrong; three agreeing is powerful."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Longitudinal studies: watching change over time",p:[
    "A longitudinal study follows the same people over a long period \u2014 years or even decades \u2014 returning again and again to see what changes.",
    "This is the best way to watch trends develop: how careers grow, how attitudes shift, how childhood affects adult life. The cost is time, money, and people dropping out along the way."],
    ex:{t:"Example — following the same class",b:["Researchers survey a Year 10 class today, then re-survey the same people at ages 20, 30 and 40.","They can see how school experiences connect to later jobs and happiness.","A one-off survey could only ever guess at that story."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Things that distort research",p:[
    "Bias is anything that unfairly tilts the results \u2014 including the researcher\u2019s own opinions leaking into the questions or the interpretation.",
    "The interviewer effect happens when the interviewer\u2019s presence, tone or identity changes people\u2019s answers. The Hawthorne (observer) effect happens when people behave differently simply because they know they are being watched."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the watched classroom",b:["A researcher sits at the back of a class to observe behaviour.","Suddenly everyone sits up straight and works quietly \u2014 not because that is normal, but because they are being watched.","That is the Hawthorne effect: the watching changed the thing being watched."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"The judging words",p:[
    "Four words let you judge any study. Validity: does it show the truth it claims to show? Reliability: would repeating it give the same results?",
    "Representativeness: does the sample fairly reflect the wider group? Generalisability: can the findings stretch beyond the study to other people and places? Strong exam answers ATTACH these words to real features of a study."],
    ex:{t:"Example — attaching the words",b:["Weak: \u201CThe study is not representative.\u201D","Strong: \u201CBecause the study only sampled boys from one school, it does not represent all teenagers \u2014 so its findings cannot be generalised to girls or other schools.\u201D","Name the word, then point at the feature that proves it."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Invent a small study about phone use in your school. Write one sentence for each judging word (validity, reliability, representativeness, generalisability) attaching it to a real feature of your design.",
  check:[
   {q:"Using several methods in one study and comparing results is called\u2026",o:["Sampling","Deception","Triangulation","Correlation"],a:2},
   {q:"People behaving differently because they know they are watched is the\u2026",o:["Pilot study","Poverty trap","Hawthorne effect","Interviewer schedule"],a:2},
   {q:"\u2018Can these findings stretch to other people and places?\u2019 asks about\u2026",o:["Operationalisation","Legality","Generalisability","Funding"],a:2},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u5",n:5,title:"Data & Evidence",mins:180,icon:"BookOpen",
  summary:"Primary vs secondary, numbers vs words, and the main kinds of secondary evidence \u2014 with their strengths and limits.",
  keyWords:["primary data","secondary data","official statistics","documents","digital sources","media content"],
  sections:[
   {art:"data",h:"Primary vs secondary data",p:[
    "Primary data is collected first-hand by the researcher for their own study \u2014 through surveys, interviews or observations. It is fresh and fits the research question exactly, but it costs time and money to gather.",
    "Secondary data already exists, collected by someone else \u2014 official statistics, old letters, other studies. It is fast and cheap to use, but it was made for a different purpose, so it may not fit your question perfectly."],
    ex:{t:"Example — choosing your source",b:["Studying crime, a researcher could interview victims (primary) or use police statistics (secondary).","The interviews fit the exact question but take months.","The statistics are instant \u2014 but they only count crimes people reported."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Quantitative vs qualitative: strengths and limits",p:[
    "Quantitative data (numbers) gives a broad view: easy to compare, chart and test for patterns. Its weakness is missing the story behind the numbers.",
    "Qualitative data (words, meanings) gives depth and detail. Its weakness is that it is harder to compare across people, and the researcher\u2019s judgement enters the analysis."],
    ex:{t:"Example — both together",b:["Crime statistics show WHERE burglary is highest (numbers).","Interviews with residents show HOW it changes daily life \u2014 fear, locked doors, moving away (words).","A full picture usually needs both kinds."]}},
   {art:"read",h:"Kinds of secondary evidence",p:[
    "Official statistics are collected by governments and agencies \u2014 census data, crime rates, exam results. They are large-scale and regular, but they only count what officials chose to count.",
    "Historical and personal documents (letters, diaries, records) open windows into the past and private life. Digital sources and media content (websites, social media, news) show current opinions \u2014 but can be biased, exaggerated or fake."],
    ex:{t:"Example — judging a source",b:["A newspaper article on teenagers and crime is quick evidence \u2014 but the paper may exaggerate to sell copies.","A government crime statistic is more careful \u2014 but misses unreported crime.","Every source must be judged, not just used."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Reading data like a sociologist",p:[
    "Sociologists present findings in summaries, tables, charts and graphs. Learning to READ these is an exam skill: check the title, the labels, the units, and the dates before drawing any conclusion.",
    "When you compare studies, summarise each one\u2019s key finding in one sentence. Comparing summaries side by side reveals agreement, disagreement and gaps."],
    ex:{t:"Example — reading a chart carefully",b:["A bar chart shows \u2018reported thefts\u2019 doubling in five years.","Careless reading: \u2018theft has doubled.\u2019","Careful reading: REPORTED theft has doubled \u2014 maybe people now report more. The label changes the conclusion."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Find any chart or table (textbook, news, internet). Write its title, what is measured, and one careless conclusion someone might jump to \u2014 then correct it with a careful reading.",
  check:[
   {q:"Data collected first-hand by the researcher is called\u2026",o:["Official statistics","Media content","Primary data","Secondary data"],a:2},
   {q:"A weakness of official statistics is that they\u2026",o:["Are always secret","Contain no numbers","Cannot be compared over time","Only count what officials chose to count"],a:3},
   {q:"Before using a chart you should first check\u2026",o:["The page number","The title, labels, units and dates","The font","The colour scheme"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u6",n:6,title:"Designing Research",mins:180,icon:"PenLine",
  summary:"The stages every study follows: topic, aims, hypothesis, target population, operationalisation and the pilot study.",
  keyWords:["aim","hypothesis","target population","operationalisation","pilot study"],
  sections:[
   {art:"write",h:"Topic, aims and hypothesis",p:[
    "Research starts with selecting a topic \u2014 something relevant and possible to study. The aims say what the research wants to find out or achieve.",
    "A hypothesis is a testable statement or prediction. It must be possible to prove it wrong with evidence \u2014 that is what makes it scientific."],
    ex:{t:"Example — building a hypothesis",b:["Topic: education and family income.","Hypothesis: \u2018Students from higher-income families achieve better grades than students from lower-income families.\u2019","Another: \u2018A freelancer working at his own pace is more likely to be satisfied with his job than a 9\u20135 salary earner.\u2019 Both can be tested \u2014 and could be proved wrong."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Target population",p:[
    "The target population is the whole group your research is about \u2014 for example, all Year 10 students in Lagos, or all nurses in a country.",
    "You almost never study everyone. Instead you study a sample drawn from the target population \u2014 which is why next unit\u2019s sampling skills matter so much."],
    ex:{t:"Example — naming the population",b:["Question: \u2018Do part-time jobs affect students\u2019 grades?\u2019","Target population: students aged 14\u201318 in the region being studied.","Everything about the sample must connect back to this group."]}},
   {art:"science",h:"Operationalisation: making ideas measurable",p:[
    "Operationalisation means turning an abstract idea into something you can actually measure. \u2018Social class\u2019, \u2018happiness\u2019 and \u2018achievement\u2019 are ideas \u2014 you cannot count them until you define them in measurable terms.",
    "For example, a researcher might operationalise social class through income brackets or occupation type, and achievement through exam grades."],
    ex:{t:"Example — measuring \u2018happiness\u2019",b:["You cannot weigh happiness.","Operationalised: a 1\u201310 life-satisfaction score, plus how often the person smiled or laughed yesterday.","Now the fuzzy idea can be measured, compared and charted."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Pilot studies: the practice run",p:[
    "A pilot study is a small trial run of the research before the real thing. It tests whether the questions make sense, how long everything takes, and whether the method actually works.",
    "Pilots catch problems cheaply: a confusing question, a survey that is too long, an interview plan that misses the point. Fixing problems before the main study saves the whole project."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a pilot that saved a study",b:["A researcher pilots a questionnaire on 10 students.","Half of them misunderstand question 3, and everyone skips the last page because it is too long.","The researcher rewrites question 3 and shortens the form \u2014 the main study now works."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Design a mini-study on lateness at your school: write the aim, a testable hypothesis, the target population, and how you would operationalise \u2018lateness\u2019. Then say what your pilot would test.",
  check:[
   {q:"A hypothesis must be\u2026",o:["Testable \u2014 possible to prove wrong with evidence","Secret","Always about money","A question with no answer"],a:0},
   {q:"Turning an abstract idea like \u2018social class\u2019 into measurable terms is called\u2026",o:["Triangulation","Operationalisation","Generalisation","Ethics"],a:1},
   {q:"The main purpose of a pilot study is to\u2026",o:["Win funding","Test and fix the research tools before the main study","Replace the main study","Publish early results"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u7",n:7,title:"Sampling",mins:180,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"How researchers choose who to study: the sampling frame and the five techniques, with the strengths and limits of each.",
  keyWords:["sample","sampling frame","random","systematic","stratified","snowball","quota"],
  sections:[
   {art:"sample",h:"Why sample, and the sampling frame",p:[
    "Studying everyone in a target population is usually impossible, so researchers study a sample \u2014 a smaller group chosen to stand for the whole.",
    "A sampling frame is the list of everyone in the target population from which the sample is drawn \u2014 for example, a school register or an electoral roll. No frame, no fair selection."],
    ex:{t:"Example — frame first",b:["Target population: all students in your school.","Sampling frame: the school\u2019s full student register.","Only with that list can every student have a known chance of being chosen."]}},
   {art:"sample",h:"Random and systematic sampling",p:[
    "Random sampling gives every person in the frame an equal chance of selection \u2014 like drawing names from a hat. It is the fairest way to avoid selection bias, though pure randomness is not always practical.",
    "Systematic sampling selects every nth person from the list \u2014 every 10th name, say. It is easier to run than random sampling, but if the list has a hidden pattern, bias can sneak in."],
    ex:{t:"Example — every 10th student",b:["A researcher surveys every 10th student on the school roster.","Quick and evenly spread \u2014 systematic sampling.","Danger: if the roster lists students by class sets, every 10th name might over-pick one set."]}},
   {art:"sample",h:"Stratified and quota sampling",p:[
    "Stratified sampling divides the population into subgroups (strata) \u2014 by age, gender, class \u2014 then randomly samples from each group in fair proportion. This boosts representativeness but takes time to organise.",
    "Quota sampling also fills set numbers from each category, but the researcher picks people conveniently rather than randomly \u2014 faster, but the non-random choosing can introduce bias."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the workplace survey",b:["A company has 5 departments. A stratified sample randomly selects employees from EACH department.","A quota version tells the interviewer: \u2018find 10 people from each department\u2019 \u2014 and they grab whoever is nearby.","Both ensure spread; only the stratified one is random."]}},
   {art:"sample",h:"Snowball sampling",p:[
    "Snowball sampling asks each participant to introduce others they know \u2014 the sample grows like a rolling snowball. It is the classic tool for hard-to-reach or hidden groups with no sampling frame.",
    "Its weakness: everyone comes from the same social circle, so the sample is unlikely to represent the wider group. Findings from snowball samples are hard to generalise."],
    ex:{t:"Example — reaching a hidden group",b:["A researcher studies an underground music scene with no member list.","One member introduces two friends, who introduce more.","The study happens at all thanks to snowballing \u2014 but it only reaches one connected network."]}},
  ],
  activity:"You must sample 50 students from a school of 1,000 to study attitudes to homework. Choose a technique, explain the steps, and give one strength and one limitation of your choice.",
  check:[
   {q:"The list of everyone in the target population is the\u2026",o:["Hypothesis","Pilot study","Quota","Sampling frame"],a:3},
   {q:"Choosing every 10th name from a list is\u2026",o:["Snowball sampling","Stratified sampling","Random sampling","Systematic sampling"],a:3},
   {q:"The best technique for a hidden group with no list is\u2026",o:["Stratified sampling","Census","Systematic sampling","Snowball sampling"],a:3},
  ]},

 {id:"t1u8",n:8,title:"Methods, Questions & Ethics",mins:180,icon:"Lightbulb",
  summary:"The main primary methods, the four question types, the practical pressures on research, and the five ethical rules.",
  keyWords:["survey","questionnaire","structured interview","participant observation","covert","informed consent","confidentiality"],
  sections:[
   {art:"talk",h:"Surveys, questionnaires and interviews",p:[
    "Surveys collect data from large groups through structured questions; questionnaires are the written form. They are cheap and reach many people, but answers can be shallow, and people may tick what looks good.",
    "Interviews trade size for depth. Structured interviews use fixed questions in a fixed order (consistent, but limited depth). Semi-structured mixes fixed and flexible. Unstructured is an open conversation (deep, but hard to repeat). Group interviews spark discussion among several people at once."],
    ex:{t:"Example — matching the tool to the job",b:["\u2018How many students have part-time jobs?\u2019 \u2192 questionnaire to 500 students.","\u2018How does a part-time job FEEL alongside school?\u2019 \u2192 ten unstructured interviews.","Numbers need reach; meanings need depth."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Observation: four flavours",p:[
    "Participant observation means joining the group being studied (a researcher working undercover in a factory); non-participant means watching from outside without joining in.",
    "Overt observation means the group KNOWS they are watched \u2014 ethical, but behaviour may change (Hawthorne effect). Covert means they do NOT know \u2014 natural behaviour, but a serious ethics problem: no consent."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the back of the class",b:["Aim: how do students really behave at the back of the classroom?","A questionnaire invites polite lies; overt watching changes the behaviour.","Covert non-participant observation shows the truth \u2014 but the students never agreed to be studied. Truth and ethics pull in opposite directions."]}},
   {art:"write",h:"Question types and practical pressures",p:[
    "Open questions let people answer freely (\u2018How do you feel about remote work?\u2019) \u2014 rich, but hard to count. Closed questions fix the choices (\u2018Yes/No\u2019) \u2014 easy to count, but thin. Multiple choice offers set options; scaled questions rate feelings on a scale (1\u20135).",
    "Real research also faces practical pressures: the researcher\u2019s perspective (positivist or interpretivist) shapes method choice; access to the sample can be hard; low response rates weaken surveys; funding and time limit everything."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a scaled question",b:["\u2018Rate your satisfaction with online learning from 1 to 5.\u2019","Scaled answers can be averaged and charted \u2014 numbers from feelings.","But a \u20183\u2019 hides WHY \u2014 open questions would catch the reason."]}},
   {art:"ethics",h:"The five ethical rules",p:[
    "Informed consent: participants agree to take part, knowing what the research is. Privacy and confidentiality: personal information stays protected and is used only for the research.",
    "Deception: do not mislead participants about the study unless truly unavoidable. Prevention of harm: no physical or psychological damage. Legality: the research must obey the law. Studies of children need extra care \u2014 consent from guardians too."],
    ex:{t:"Example — consent with teenagers",b:["A researcher studying teenagers\u2019 mental health must explain the study clearly and get consent from BOTH the teenagers and their guardians.","Names are replaced with codes so no one can be identified.","Consent + confidentiality + no harm: the study is now ethical."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Plan a one-page study on students and sleep. State: your method, one open and one closed question you would ask, the biggest practical problem you expect, and how you will meet all five ethical rules.",
  check:[
   {q:"An interview with fixed questions in a fixed order is\u2026",o:["Longitudinal","Unstructured","Structured","Covert"],a:2},
   {q:"Watching a group that does not know it is being watched is\u2026",o:["A pilot study","Overt observation","Covert observation","A census"],a:2},
   {q:"Participants agreeing to take part with full understanding is\u2026",o:["Deception","Informed consent","Quota sampling","Correlation"],a:1},
  ]},,
 {id:"t1u9",n:9,title:"Exam Skills: Answering IGCSE Command Questions",mins:180,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"How to read each command word and structure top-scoring answers — with real structural analysis of the highest-mark Explain, Discuss and Evaluate questions from the Cambridge 0495 specimen papers.",
  keyWords:["command word","Identify","Define","Explain","Discuss","Evaluate","PEEL","mark scheme"],
  sections:[
   {art:"command",h:"The seven command words and what they demand",p:[
    "Every IGCSE Sociology (0495) question opens with a command word that tells you exactly what to do. Marks are lost when students know the content but answer the wrong command. The seven words rise in difficulty: Identify, Define, Give (short, exact), Describe, Explain (developed points), and Discuss, Evaluate (two-sided argument plus a judgement).",
    "The number in brackets is your instruction for length. A [2] wants one or two exact items. A [4] wants two points, each with a reason. A [6] wants three developed points. A [8] Discuss wants three well-developed points. A [10], [12] or [14] wants a full structured essay. Always let the marks decide how much you write.",
    "Cambridge assesses three skills: AO1 (knowledge of terms, theories and studies), AO2 (applying that knowledge to the question), and AO3 (analysing and evaluating). Low-mark questions are mostly AO1/AO2; the big essays add AO3. Knowing which skill a question wants tells you how to shape the answer."],
    ex:{t:"Example \u2014 one topic, three commands (from the 0495 papers)",b:["\u2018Identify two types of question used by sociologists.\u2019 [2] \u2192 just name two, e.g. open and multiple-choice.","\u2018Explain three reasons why people may join deviant sub-cultures.\u2019 [6] \u2192 three developed paragraphs.","\u2018Evaluate the view that gender is the main influence on identity.\u2019 [14] \u2192 three arguments for, three against, and a conclusion.","Same subject knowledge \u2014 the command word decides the shape of the answer."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Identify, Define, Give and Describe (the short-answer marks)",p:[
    "Identify and Give want you to state something correctly \u2014 usually [2]. Do not explain or add detail; the examiner reports that extra detail earns no marks and wastes time. In the specimen paper, \u2018Identify two types of question\u2019 scored full marks with just \u2018Open questions and multiple-choice questions.\u2019",
    "Define wants the precise meaning of a term, [2]. A full definition has TWO elements; a bare example is only a \u2018partial\u2019 definition and scores one mark. The specimen answer defined feminism as a sociological theory (element one) that focuses on gender inequality and patriarchy (element two) \u2014 two elements, full marks.",
    "Describe wants a detailed account with signal words. \u2018Describe three types of marriage\u2019 [6] gives one mark for naming each type and one for describing it. The specimen lost a mark because it named polygamy but never described it \u2014 proving you must develop every point you raise, and always signal them: \u2018One type\u2026 A second type\u2026\u2019."],
    ex:{t:"Example \u2014 why marks are lost on easy questions",b:["\u2018Give two negative sanctions used in the family\u2019 [2]: one specimen answer said \u2018being told off\u2019 (correct) and \u2018being sent to prison\u2019 \u2014 prison is not a family sanction, so it scored 1/2.","Lesson: read the exact context (\u2018in the family\u2019) before answering.","On these questions, accuracy and staying on-context matter more than length."]}},
   {art:"build",h:"EXPLAIN questions: the PEEL structure that scores full marks",p:[
    "Explain questions ([4] or [6]) ask HOW or WHY. The examiner\u2019s golden tip appears again and again in the mark schemes: use the word \u2018because\u2019 \u2014 it forces you to explain rather than merely describe. Each point needs a clear structure: POINT (state it), EXPLAIN (the \u2018because\u2026\u2019 reason), EXAMPLE (a concrete illustration), and where useful a LINK back to the question.",
    "Structure matters as much as content. In the specimen \u2018Explain three reasons why people join deviant sub-cultures\u2019 [6], the top answer scored 6/6 with three separate paragraphs, each signalled (\u2018One reason\u2026 A second reason\u2026 A third reason\u2026\u2019), each naming a reason then developing it with a study or example (status frustration and Cohen; relative deprivation; the thrill factor).",
    "One mark per point is for the correct point; the second mark is for developing it. The specimen \u2018Explain three ways identity can be chosen\u2019 [6] scored only 5/6 because the third point (joining interest-based networks) was named but not developed \u2014 \u2018more explanation was needed\u2019. The pattern is clear: never leave a point undeveloped."],
    ex:{t:"Structural analysis \u2014 \u2018Explain three reasons why poverty might lead to crime.\u2019 [6] (scored 6/6)",b:["POINT 1 \u2014 the underclass (New Right, Murray): named, then explained via poor socialisation and benefit dependency. [2 marks]","POINT 2 \u2014 material deprivation (Marxists): named, then explained as lacking money/food, leading to shoplifting. [2 marks]","POINT 3 \u2014 status frustration (Cohen): named, then explained via anger at unfairness and lack of status. [2 marks]","Structure = 3 signalled paragraphs \u00D7 (point + because-reason + study/example). That repeatable shape is full marks."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"DISCUSS questions [8]: three developed points with evidence",p:[
    "A \u2018Discuss\u2026 include at least three developed points with evidence\u2019 [8] is a mini-essay. It needs three points, each developed MORE deeply than in a [6] Explain, because it is a higher-tariff question. The examiner explicitly notes part (e) answers need \u2018a greater level of development (evidence and analysis)\u2019 than part (d).",
    "Structure each point as its own paragraph: state the point, develop it with sociological concepts, and support it with evidence, a study or a real example. Signal each clearly. The specimen \u2018Discuss how family functions have changed\u2019 [8] scored full marks by discussing three functions (reproduction \u2014 with \u2018DINK families\u2019 evidence; socialisation \u2014 nurseries and media; emotional care \u2014 care homes), each a developed paragraph.",
    "A key examiner warning for [8] Discuss: do NOT waste time on long introductions or conclusions, and do not criticise the view if the question does not ask for evaluation \u2014 no marks are given for that. Spend every sentence developing your three points. Depth, not breadth: three deep points beat five shallow ones."],
    ex:{t:"Structural analysis \u2014 \u2018Discuss the view that crime and deviance are relative.\u2019 [8]",b:["Best practice: open by showing you understand \u2018relative\u2019 (definitions can change) with a theory link (interactionism) \u2014 but keep it brief.","POINT 1 \u2014 situation: the same act (a punch) is acceptable in a boxing ring, deviant in the street. Develop WHY.","POINT 2 \u2014 time/era: smoking was once a norm, now restricted and deviant in many places.","POINT 3 \u2014 culture: acts like adultery are treated very differently across societies.","Examiner note: this specimen lost marks where points were named but under-developed \u2014 depth is everything at [8]."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"EVALUATE questions [10\u201314]: the full for/against/judgement essay",p:[
    "Evaluate is the highest-tariff question ([10], [12] or [14]) and follows a strict rubric printed on the paper: \u2018at least [two or three] arguments for the view and [two or three] against, and a conclusion\u2019. Meeting every element of that rubric is how you reach the top level (Level 3 or 4). Miss the conclusion, or give only one side, and you cannot reach the top band.",
    "The structure is: (1) a brief definition/context \u2014 no long introduction; (2) developed arguments FOR, each its own paragraph with evidence; (3) developed arguments AGAINST, signalled with \u2018On the other hand\u2026\u2019 or \u2018However\u2026\u2019; (4) a CONCLUSION that makes a reasoned judgement, not just a summary. Use sociological perspectives (functionalist, Marxist, feminist, interactionist) as ready-made sides.",
    "What lifts an Evaluate answer into the top level: naming studies and sociologists (Oakley, Cohen, Murray, Becker), using precise concepts (canalisation, status frustration, patriarchy, vertical/horizontal segregation), linking every argument back to the exact wording of the question, and ending with a genuine judgement. The specimen answers that scored 12\u201313 out of 14 did all of these; where they dropped marks, it was usually a weaker link to the question or a judgement that did not fully weigh the evidence."],
    ex:{t:"Structural analysis \u2014 \u2018Evaluate the view that gender is the main influence on identity.\u2019 [14] (scored 12/14)",b:["FOR (3 developed paragraphs): primary socialisation (Oakley \u2014 canalisation, manipulation); secondary socialisation (school, peer pressure); the gendered division of labour (vertical/horizontal segregation).","AGAINST (3 developed paragraphs): other influences \u2014 class, age and stereotyping of the elderly \u2014 each shown to shape identity too.","CONCLUSION: a judgement \u2014 identity is now more chosen, and class and age are \u2018now as important as gender\u2019.","Why 12 not 14: one \u2018against\u2019 paragraph was less developed and its link to \u2018identity\u2019 was left implicit. Lesson: develop EVERY paragraph equally and link each one explicitly to the question.","Rubric met = top band: three for, three against, evidence throughout, and a reasoned conclusion."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick any [8] Discuss or [10–14] Evaluate question from your course. Plan it on paper: write your three FOR points, three AGAINST points (each with a study or example), and a one-sentence judgement. Check every paragraph links back to the exact question.",
  check:[
   {q:"A [14] Evaluate question always requires…",o:["Only one strong side","Arguments for, arguments against, and a conclusion","Just definitions","A long introduction"],a:1},
   {q:"The examiner’s tip for turning description into explanation is to use the word…",o:["however","finally","because","therefore"],a:2},
   {q:"In a [6] Explain question, the second mark for each point is earned by…",o:["Writing a conclusion","Listing more points","Developing the point with a reason or example","Naming the point only"],a:2},
  ]}

];
