const SOC10T3_UNITS=[
 {id:"t3u1",n:1,title:"Layers of Society",mins:180,icon:"Target",
  summary:"How societies are divided into layers, the difference between open and closed systems, and the key words of stratification.",
  keyWords:["social stratification","open society","closed society","achieved status","ascribed status","caste system","meritocracy","social mobility"],
  sections:[
   {art:"layers",h:"What is social stratification?",p:[
    "Social stratification is the way society is divided into different layers, called strata, based on things like wealth, power and status. Picture a layered cake: people sit on different levels, and the level shapes their life.",
    "Every known society has some form of stratification. What changes is how the layers are decided, how far apart they are, and whether people can move between them."],
    ex:{t:"Example — layers you can see",b:["Think of a large company: cleaners, junior staff, managers and the chief executive.","Each layer has different pay, power and respect.","That is stratification inside one organisation \u2014 society works the same way on a bigger scale."]}},
   {art:"layers",h:"Open and closed societies",p:[
    "In an open society, people can move between the layers based on their own effort or ability \u2014 modern Britain is often used as an example. Movement is possible, even if not always easy.",
    "In a closed society, movement is restricted, usually fixed by birth. India\u2019s traditional caste system is the classic example: the layer you are born into is the layer you stay in for life."],
    ex:{t:"Example — open versus closed",b:["In an open society a market trader\u2019s child could, in theory, become a doctor.","In a strict caste system that same move would be blocked by birth.","The door between layers is open in one and locked in the other."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Achieved and ascribed status again",p:[
    "Two familiar words explain how people get their layer. Achieved status is a position earned through hard work or talent \u2014 becoming a doctor, a business owner, a champion.",
    "Ascribed status is a position given at birth, not earned \u2014 being born into royalty, or into a particular caste. Open societies lean on achieved status; closed societies lean on ascribed status."],
    ex:{t:"Example — earned or given",b:["A surgeon\u2019s status is achieved \u2014 years of study earned it.","A prince\u2019s status is ascribed \u2014 born into it.","Both are high status, but reached in opposite ways."]}},
   {art:"chance",h:"Mobility, meritocracy and modern slavery",p:[
    "Social mobility is the ability to move up or down the social ladder. A meritocracy is a system where success is meant to depend on talent and effort, not on your background \u2014 the ideal of an open society.",
    "But inequality has a dark extreme: modern slavery, where people are exploited and controlled, often through forced labour. It is a reminder that stratification is not just about comfort \u2014 for some, the bottom layer means being owned."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the ladder in action",b:["Upward mobility: a factory worker\u2019s daughter becomes an engineer.","A true meritocracy would let this happen through talent alone.","Critics ask whether any real society is fully meritocratic \u2014 or whether birth still tilts the ladder."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Decide whether your society is more open or more closed, and give two reasons. Then list one example of achieved status and one of ascribed status from your own community.",
  check:[
   {q:"Dividing society into layers based on wealth, power and status is called\u2026",o:["Social stratification","Photosynthesis","Sampling","Socialisation"],a:0},
   {q:"A society where movement between layers is fixed by birth is\u2026",o:["A meritocracy","A closed society","A digital society","An open society"],a:1},
   {q:"A system where success is meant to depend on talent and effort is a\u2026",o:["Closed society","Meritocracy","Reserve army","Caste system"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u2",n:2,title:"Life Chances",mins:180,icon:"BarChart2",
  summary:"How the layer you are born into shapes your real opportunities in education, work, health, housing and length of life.",
  keyWords:["life chances","poverty","wealth","power","education","health","life expectancy"],
  sections:[
   {art:"chance",h:"What are life chances?",p:[
    "Life chances are the opportunities a person has to improve the quality of their life \u2014 to get a good education, a decent job, safe housing, good health and a long life.",
    "The key sociological point: life chances are not shared equally. They are strongly affected by age, gender, ethnicity and social class. The layer you are born into travels with you."],
    ex:{t:"Example — two babies",b:["Two babies are born on the same day, one into wealth and one into poverty.","Before they can walk, their likely paths in school, health and housing already differ.","That gap is a difference in life chances."]}},
   {art:"school",h:"Education and employment",p:[
    "In education, wealthier students often attend better-resourced schools, and some ethnic groups face discrimination that lowers their chances. Money and treatment shape results before ability is even tested.",
    "In employment, higher social classes tend to have better job opportunities, while women and ethnic minorities sometimes earn less for similar work. The layer opens some doors and quietly closes others."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the school gap",b:["A wealthy family can pay for tutoring, books and a quiet study space.","A poorer family may have none of these, through no fault of the child.","Same ability, different chances \u2014 that is the life-chances argument."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Health, housing and life expectancy",p:[
    "Poorer people often have worse health and less access to good healthcare. Richer families usually live in better, safer housing, while poorer people may face overcrowded or unsafe homes.",
    "These gaps add up to the starkest measure of all: life expectancy. Wealthier people, on average, live longer; poverty and poor health shorten lives. Inequality is written into how long people live."],
    ex:{t:"Example — inequality measured in years",b:["In many countries, people in the richest areas live several years longer than those in the poorest.","Nobody chose the neighbourhood they were born into.","Yet it can change how many years they get \u2014 the ultimate life chance."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Age and gender in life chances",p:[
    "Age shapes chances too: the young and the very old are often treated differently in work and healthcare. Gender still matters: in many places women face unequal pay and fewer chances to reach the top.",
    "Remember that these factors combine. A person is never only their class, or only their gender \u2014 the next unit shows how these layers overlap."],
    ex:{t:"Example — gender at work",b:["A woman and a man do similar jobs with similar skill.","In many workplaces she is still, on average, paid less and promoted less often.","Gender has shaped a life chance that ability alone did not."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick one life chance (education, health, housing or life expectancy). Write two ways it might differ between a rich and a poor family in your society, using no illustrations \u2014 just clear reasons.",
  check:[
   {q:"Life chances are\u2026",o:["Games of luck","Only about health","The opportunities people have to improve their lives","Only about age"],a:2},
   {q:"Which factor does NOT strongly affect life chances (per the syllabus)?",o:["Gender","Favourite colour","Ethnicity","Social class"],a:1},
   {q:"The starkest single measure of unequal life chances is\u2026",o:["Hair length","Life expectancy","Handwriting","Shoe size"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u3",n:3,title:"Explaining Inequality",mins:180,icon:"Lightbulb",
  summary:"How different disadvantages overlap (intersectionality) and two big theories of inequality: labelling and Marxism.",
  keyWords:["intersectionality","labelling theory","master status","self-fulfilling prophecy","Marxism","exploitation","reserve army of labour"],
  sections:[
   {art:"gap",h:"Intersectionality: disadvantages that overlap",p:[
    "Intersectionality is the idea that different forms of inequality \u2014 age, gender, ethnicity and class \u2014 can combine and overlap to create unique disadvantages. They are not just added together; they interact.",
    "A person is never only one label. The same individual may face several disadvantages at once, and together they hit harder than any single one alone."],
    ex:{t:"Example — overlapping disadvantage",b:["A young, working-class, ethnic-minority woman may face bias for her age, her class, her ethnicity AND her gender.","Each layer alone is a barrier; together they can deepen the impact on her education and job chances.","That overlap is what intersectionality describes."]}},
   {art:"identity",h:"Labelling theory",p:[
    "Labelling theory (from the interactionist perspective) explains how labels and stereotypes given by others \u2014 teachers, employers, the media \u2014 can shape a person\u2019s self-image and behaviour.",
    "Three key ideas: a stereotype is an oversimplified generalisation (\u2018boys are troublemakers\u2019); a master status is one label that overshadows everything else about a person (\u2018dropout\u2019); and a self-fulfilling prophecy is when a person accepts a label and starts to act like it."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the label that came true",b:["A student is repeatedly labelled \u2018lazy\u2019.","They stop trying, because what is the point \u2014 the label has become their master status.","Eventually they underachieve: the self-fulfilling prophecy has completed."]}},
   {art:"theory",h:"Marxism and inequality",p:[
    "Marxists see society split between the bourgeoisie (the ruling class who own businesses) and the proletariat (the working class). For Marxists, inequality is the result of capitalist exploitation.",
    "Exploitation means workers are paid less than the value of what they produce, while owners keep the profit. Ideological control means schools and media spread beliefs that make inequality seem normal and fair."],
    ex:{t:"Example — where the profit goes",b:["A worker produces goods worth far more than their wage.","The gap becomes the owner\u2019s profit \u2014 Marxists call this exploitation.","Meanwhile the message \u2018work hard and you\u2019ll rise\u2019 hides how the system is built."]}},
   {art:"gap",h:"The poverty trap and the reserve army",p:[
    "Marxists describe a poverty trap: a cycle where poor people stay poor because of low wages, debt and lack of opportunity \u2014 escape is blocked from every side.",
    "They also describe the reserve army of labour: a pool of unemployed or underemployed people who can be hired cheaply when needed and dropped when not. Their existence helps keep everyone\u2019s wages low."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the trap and the army",b:["Low wages leave no savings; no savings means no training; no training means low wages again \u2014 the poverty trap.","When business booms, the unemployed \u2018reserve army\u2019 is hired cheaply; when it slows, they are let go first.","Both ideas show inequality built into the system, not just bad luck."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Take one made-up person facing two overlapping disadvantages. Explain in a short paragraph how intersectionality applies, then how a labelling theorist would see their situation differently from a Marxist.",
  check:[
   {q:"The idea that age, gender, class and ethnicity can overlap to deepen disadvantage is\u2026",o:["Meritocracy","Triangulation","A pilot study","Intersectionality"],a:3},
   {q:"One label that overshadows all others about a person is a\u2026",o:["Sampling frame","Master status","Positive sanction","Reserve army"],a:1},
   {q:"Marxists say workers are paid less than the value they produce \u2014 this is\u2026",o:["Consent","Exploitation","Mobility","Meritocracy"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u4",n:4,title:"Laws Against Inequality",mins:180,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"How governments use law to reduce inequality: progressive taxation, redistribution, minimum wage and equal opportunities laws.",
  keyWords:["progressive taxation","redistribution of wealth","benefits","minimum wage","equal opportunities laws"],
  sections:[
   {art:"law",h:"Progressive taxation",p:[
    "Progressive taxation is a system where the more you earn, the higher the rate of tax you pay. Its aim is to reduce the gap between rich and poor.",
    "The money collected can fund public services \u2014 education, healthcare, roads \u2014 that everyone uses, including those who could never pay for them privately. Tax becomes a tool for fairness."],
    ex:{t:"Example — different rates",b:["A high earner might pay 40% in tax while a low earner pays 10%.","The richer person contributes a larger share.","That extra revenue can fund schools and hospitals for all."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Redistribution through benefits",p:[
    "Redistribution of wealth means moving resources from richer to poorer through the tax-and-benefit system. Governments provide financial support \u2014 unemployment benefits, child support, housing benefit, pensions.",
    "The purpose is to ensure everyone can meet basic needs like food, shelter and healthcare, even when they cannot earn enough themselves."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a safety net",b:["A parent loses their job.","Unemployment and child benefits help the family afford food and rent while they look for work.","Redistribution has caught them before they fall too far."]}},
   {art:"law",h:"Minimum wage",p:[
    "A minimum wage is a legal lowest hourly rate that employers must pay. It prevents the worst exploitation and helps workers afford a basic standard of living.",
    "No employer may legally pay below it. Supporters say it protects the vulnerable; critics worry it could raise costs for businesses \u2014 a debate this course returns to."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the legal floor",b:["If the minimum wage is set at a fixed hourly amount, no employer can legally pay less.","A worker on that wage is protected from being paid a tiny sum for long hours.","The law puts a floor under wages."]}},
   {art:"law",h:"Equal opportunities laws and other measures",p:[
    "Equal opportunities laws make it illegal to discriminate based on gender, race, age, disability or religion in employment, education and services. They aim to create a level playing field.",
    "Other government measures include free or subsidised education and healthcare, affirmative action to support under-represented groups, and training programmes to help the unemployed gain skills and jobs."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a level field",b:["A company must treat male and female job candidates equally during recruitment.","An equal opportunities law makes discrimination against the rules.","The aim is that ability, not background or gender, decides who gets the job."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose two of the four measures (progressive tax, benefits, minimum wage, equal opportunities laws). For each, write one sentence on how it reduces inequality and one possible criticism.",
  check:[
   {q:"A tax system where higher earners pay a higher rate is\u2026",o:["Redistribution only","Progressive taxation","A minimum wage","A benefit"],a:1},
   {q:"A legal lowest hourly pay rate is the\u2026",o:["Poverty trap","Reserve army","Caste","Minimum wage"],a:3},
   {q:"Laws banning discrimination in jobs and education are\u2026",o:["Equal opportunities laws","Pensions","Sanctions","Progressive taxes"],a:0},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u5",n:5,title:"The Welfare State",mins:180,icon:"Heart",
  summary:"How a welfare state supports citizens and improves life chances, from free education and healthcare to pensions and universal basic income.",
  keyWords:["welfare state","universal education","unemployment benefits","pensions","free healthcare","universal basic income"],
  sections:[
   {art:"help",h:"What is a welfare state?",p:[
    "A welfare state is a system where the government takes responsibility for the well-being of its citizens, especially those in need. It provides services and financial support to reduce inequality and improve life chances.",
    "The idea is simple but powerful: no one should be left to sink because of poverty, illness, unemployment or old age. The state builds a safety net beneath everyone."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the net beneath you",b:["A person falls ill and cannot work.","In a welfare state, free healthcare treats them and benefits support them.","They recover without losing everything \u2014 the safety net held."]}},
   {art:"school",h:"Education, benefits and pensions",p:[
    "Free or universal education gives everyone, regardless of background, access to schooling \u2014 improving job prospects and social mobility. Unemployment benefits support people financially while they search for work.",
    "Pensions are regular payments to the elderly after retirement, so older citizens can live with dignity rather than fall into poverty when they can no longer earn."],
    ex:{t:"Example — support across a lifetime",b:["Free schooling helps a poor child gain qualifications.","Unemployment benefit supports them through a gap between jobs.","A pension supports them in old age \u2014 the welfare state spans a whole life."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Housing, healthcare and UBI",p:[
    "Low-cost housing (government or council homes with affordable rent) reduces homelessness and housing inequality. Free healthcare, provided at little or no cost, improves health outcomes \u2014 especially for the poor.",
    "Universal basic income (UBI) is a newer idea: a fixed income given to every citizen regardless of whether they work, aiming to reduce poverty and support everyone equally. It is debated, not yet widespread."],
    ex:{t:"Example — free healthcare's effect",b:["A low-income family can see a doctor without a bill.","Illness is treated early instead of becoming a crisis.","Better health means better life chances \u2014 the welfare state\u2019s core aim."]}},
   {art:"chance",h:"The welfare state and life chances",p:[
    "By widening access to education, healthcare and stable living conditions, welfare states can reduce the harshest effects of poverty. Life chances that birth would otherwise decide are partly reopened.",
    "Whether the welfare state truly succeeds \u2014 or creates new problems \u2014 is fiercely argued. That debate is the subject of a later unit."],
    ex:{t:"Example — reopening a door",b:["Without free education, a poor but talented child might never gain qualifications.","With it, that child can reach university and a professional job.","The welfare state reopened a door that poverty had shut."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List the six main features of a welfare state from this unit. Next to each, write one word describing the group it helps most (for example: pensions \u2192 elderly).",
  check:[
   {q:"A welfare state is a system where\u2026",o:["Citizens pay no tax","Only the rich are helped","There are no services","The government takes responsibility for citizens' well-being"],a:3},
   {q:"Regular payments to the elderly after retirement are\u2026",o:["Minimum wages","Fines","Pensions","Quotas"],a:2},
   {q:"A fixed income given to all citizens regardless of work is\u2026",o:["A caste","Universal basic income","A pension only","Progressive tax"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u6",n:6,title:"NGOs and the Critics",mins:180,icon:"Users",
  summary:"The global work of NGOs to reduce inequality, and the main criticisms of welfare and NGOs from the New Right, Marxists and feminists.",
  keyWords:["NGO","dependency culture","culture of poverty","underclass","New Right","Marxist criticism","feminist criticism"],
  sections:[
   {art:"help",h:"What NGOs do",p:[
    "Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) are independent, non-profit groups that work locally and globally to improve lives, often in developing countries or crisis situations \u2014 stepping in where governments cannot reach.",
    "Their main areas of work are reducing poverty (food, clean water, shelter), providing medical assistance (clinics, vaccinations), promoting business (microloans, training) and improving education (schools, teachers, materials)."],
    ex:{t:"Example — an NGO at work",b:["After a disaster, an NGO delivers clean water, medical care and temporary shelter.","Later it funds a new school and trains local teachers.","It filled gaps the local government could not reach alone."]}},
   {art:"theory",h:"The New Right criticism",p:[
    "The New Right believes in minimal government and personal responsibility. It is critical of relying on welfare, arguing that generous benefits can create a dependency culture \u2014 people relying on state help instead of becoming self-reliant.",
    "It blames an underclass (the long-term unemployed, some lone parents) for social problems, and links the culture of poverty to habits passed down through generations."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the dependency argument",b:["The New Right claims that if benefits are too easy, some people may choose them over low-paid work.","They warn this can become a habit passed to children \u2014 a dependency culture.","Critics reply that this blames the poor for a system that traps them."]}},
   {art:"theory",h:"Marxist and feminist criticisms",p:[
    "Marxists argue the welfare state does not remove class inequality \u2014 it only manages it, keeping workers healthy enough to keep working for the capitalist class. The system, they say, maintains inequality rather than solving it.",
    "Feminists argue that equality legislation alone does not change attitudes: the gender pay gap and workplace discrimination still exist, because patriarchal norms are deeply rooted in institutions and culture."],
    ex:{t:"Example — laws are not enough",b:["An equal-pay law exists, yet women in many workplaces still earn less on average.","Feminists argue the law changed the rulebook but not the culture.","The deeper attitudes need changing too."]}},
   {art:"global",h:"Criticisms of NGOs",p:[
    "NGOs face criticism too. They may promote Western values over local traditions, and can create dependence on aid rather than building self-sufficiency. Some are accused of lacking accountability or misunderstanding local needs.",
    "None of this means NGOs are useless \u2014 it means their work must be judged carefully, like every attempt to reduce inequality. Good intentions do not guarantee good outcomes."],
    ex:{t:"Example — help that creates dependence",b:["An NGO gives free food for years without building local farming.","When it leaves, the community has no way to feed itself.","Critics say aid must build self-sufficiency, not replace it."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick one criticism (New Right, Marxist, feminist, or of NGOs). Write two sentences explaining it fairly, then one sentence giving the other side's reply.",
  check:[
   {q:"NGOs are\u2026",o:["Government tax offices","Independent, non-profit groups that work to improve lives","Court systems","Private banks"],a:1},
   {q:"The New Right argues generous welfare can create\u2026",o:["A reserve army","Progressive tax","A dependency culture","A caste system"],a:2},
   {q:"Marxists argue the welfare state mainly\u2026",o:["Ends capitalism","Helps only the rich","Manages inequality rather than removing it","Abolishes class"],a:2},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u7",n:7,title:"Globalisation and Migration",mins:180,icon:"BookOpen",
  summary:"How globalisation widens gaps between societies, and how migration \u2014 with its push and pull factors \u2014 reshapes them.",
  keyWords:["globalisation","Global North","Global South","immigration","emigration","push factors","pull factors","cultural diversity"],
  sections:[
   {art:"global",h:"Globalisation and widening gaps",p:[
    "Globalisation is the increasing connection of countries through trade, communication, migration and cultural exchange. It brings the world closer \u2014 but it does not affect everyone equally.",
    "Richer countries (the Global North) often gain most: better access to technology, investment and global markets. Poorer countries (the Global South) can become dependent on multinational companies and foreign aid, and their cheap labour and resources may be exploited."],
    ex:{t:"Example — an unequal connection",b:["A global company makes clothes cheaply in a poorer country and sells them for high profit in richer ones.","The workers gain little; the company and richer economies gain a lot.","Globalisation connected them \u2014 but unequally."]}},
   {art:"migrate",h:"Migration: immigration and emigration",p:[
    "Migration is a major consequence of globalisation. Immigration means people entering a country to live or work; emigration means people leaving their home country, often for better opportunities.",
    "Migration can be internal (within a country, such as rural to urban) or international (between countries). Either way, it reshapes the societies people leave and the ones they join."],
    ex:{t:"Example — two sides of one move",b:["A nurse leaves her home country (emigration) to work abroad (immigration there).","Her new country gains a skilled worker; her old country loses one.","One move, two effects on two societies."]}},
   {art:"migrate",h:"Push and pull factors",p:[
    "Push factors are conditions that force people to leave their home country \u2014 war, poverty, persecution, disaster. Pull factors are conditions that attract people to a new country \u2014 jobs, safety, education, a better life.",
    "Most migration is explained by a combination: something pushing people away and something pulling them toward a new place."],
    ex:{t:"Example — push meets pull",b:["War and poverty push a family to leave (push factors).","Jobs and safety in another country attract them (pull factors).","Together these factors explain their journey."]}},
   {art:"migrate",h:"The effects of migration",p:[
    "Migration increases cultural diversity, creating multicultural societies that can promote tolerance and innovation \u2014 though they can also cause tensions. Economically, migrants often fill skill gaps, pay taxes and support growth.",
    "But migrants also face negative perceptions: media and political narratives sometimes stereotype them as threats or criminals, which can lead to discrimination, racism and exclusion \u2014 an inequality of its own."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the double story of migration",b:["Migrants fill nursing and building jobs a country badly needs (a benefit).","Yet some media portray them as a threat, fuelling prejudice (a harm).","Both stories are real; a sociologist weighs them fairly."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose one real or imagined migration. List two push factors and two pull factors behind it, then name one benefit and one challenge it might bring to the receiving society.",
  check:[
   {q:"Globalisation is\u2026",o:["Countries closing all borders","A type of tax","A caste system","The increasing connection of countries through trade, migration and exchange"],a:3},
   {q:"War, poverty and persecution that force people to leave are\u2026",o:["Pensions","Push factors","Pull factors","Sanctions"],a:1},
   {q:"Jobs, safety and education that attract migrants to a country are\u2026",o:["Push factors","Quotas","Benefits only","Pull factors"],a:3},
  ]},

 {id:"t3u8",n:8,title:"A Planet Under Pressure",mins:180,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"Global ecological issues \u2014 transnational companies, climate change, pollution, urbanisation \u2014 and sociological explanations for global inequality.",
  keyWords:["transnational companies","climate change","pollution","urbanisation","capitalist exploitation","colonialism","patriarchy"],
  sections:[
   {art:"planet",h:"Transnational companies",p:[
    "Transnational companies (TNCs) are large corporations that operate in several countries at once. They can bring investment and jobs \u2014 but they often exploit cheap labour and natural resources in less developed countries.",
    "TNCs can cause environmental damage such as deforestation and water pollution, and while they increase wealth in some places, they often worsen inequality between countries."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the cost of cheap production",b:["A TNC extracts oil in a poorer country.","Spills damage local land, water and communities, while most profit leaves the country.","Wealth flowed out; harm stayed behind \u2014 a global inequality."]}},
   {art:"planet",h:"Climate change and pollution",p:[
    "Climate change means long-term shifts in temperature and weather caused by human activity. It hits poorer nations hardest \u2014 harming farming, water and housing, and creating climate refugees forced to migrate by environmental change.",
    "Pollution of air, water and land, often from industry and poor waste management, causes health problems and lowers quality of life. Poorer countries frequently lack the resources to tackle it effectively."],
    ex:{t:"Example — unequal harm",b:["Rising sea levels threaten low-lying island nations that did little to cause the problem.","Wealthier, higher-polluting nations are often better protected.","Those who caused least can suffer most \u2014 a global injustice."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Urbanisation",p:[
    "Urbanisation is the growth of cities as more people move from rural areas. It can bring economic opportunity and access to services \u2014 but the benefits are often unevenly shared.",
    "Rapid urbanisation can create overcrowded slums, poor sanitation and pollution, and strain housing, transport, schools and health services."],
    ex:{t:"Example — two sides of the city",b:["A growing city offers jobs and schools that villages lack.","But newcomers may crowd into slums with poor sanitation.","Urbanisation brought opportunity and hardship at once."]}},
   {art:"theory",h:"Explaining global inequality",p:[
    "Three sociological explanations stand out. Marxists point to capitalist exploitation: rich countries and corporations profit by exploiting poorer ones through low wages, debt and unequal trade.",
    "Others point to colonialism: past empires controlled and drained colonies, leaving long-term poverty and weak institutions whose effects remain. Feminists point to patriarchy: worldwide, women often have less access to education, work and healthcare, keeping gender inequality built into global poverty."],
    ex:{t:"Example — three lenses on one gap",b:["Marxist: cheap production in poorer nations enriches Western economies, not local workers.","Colonialism: much of that poverty traces back to centuries of imperial control.","Feminist: within poor nations, women face the sharpest disadvantage of all. Three lenses, one inequality."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose one global issue (TNCs, climate change, pollution or urbanisation). Explain in a short paragraph how a Marxist and a feminist might each interpret its impact differently.",
  check:[
   {q:"Large corporations operating in several countries are\u2026",o:["Transnational companies","Pensions","Trade unions","NGOs"],a:0},
   {q:"People forced to migrate by environmental change are\u2026",o:["A caste","Reserve army","The underclass","Climate refugees"],a:3},
   {q:"Marxists explain global inequality mainly through\u2026",o:["Capitalist exploitation","Patriarchy only","Meritocracy","Urbanisation only"],a:0},
  ]},
];
