const SOC11T1_UNITS=[
 {id:"y1u1",n:1,title:"What Is a Family?",mins:180,icon:"Users",
  summary:"The main family structures sociologists study, and the strengths and limits of each.",
  keyWords:["nuclear family","extended family","reconstituted family","lone parent","polygamous","beanpole"],
  sections:[
   {art:"family",h:"The nuclear and extended family",p:[
    "A nuclear family is two parents and their children living together \u2014 long treated as the \u2018typical\u2019 family. Its strength is often seen as stability for raising children; its limit is having little support beyond the two parents.",
    "An extended family includes relatives beyond the nuclear core \u2014 grandparents, aunts, uncles, cousins. It can be vertical (beanpole: several generations), horizontal (relatives of the same generation), or modified (living apart but keeping close ties)."],
    ex:{t:"Example — two households",b:["A mother, father and two children living together is a nuclear family.","Add grandparents under the same roof and it becomes a vertical (beanpole) extended family.","The extended form offers more support but risks more conflict between lifestyles."]}},
   {art:"family",h:"Reconstituted, lone-parent and same-sex families",p:[
    "A reconstituted (blended) family forms when parents remarry and bring children from previous relationships together. It can increase family size but may bring adjustment challenges for children.",
    "A lone-parent family is one parent raising the child or children \u2014 often with close bonds, though economic strain can be higher. A same-sex family has two parents of the same gender, showing family diversity while sometimes facing social stigma."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a blended household",b:["Two adults remarry; each brings a child from a previous marriage.","The new reconstituted family is larger and offers more relationships.","Children may need time to adjust to new siblings and a step-parent."]}},
   {art:"family",h:"Other family forms",p:[
    "A polygamous family is one where a person has more than one spouse, accepted in some cultures. An empty-nest family is a couple whose children have grown up and left home.",
    "A childless family is a couple without children, by choice or circumstance \u2014 offering freedom and flexibility, though possibly less family support in old age. Together these forms show how varied \u2018family\u2019 really is."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the empty nest",b:["A couple\u2019s two children finish education and move out.","The parents now form an empty-nest household.","Their roles shift from daily parenting to support and advice from a distance."]}},
   {art:"culture",h:"Diversity and variation",p:[
    "Family structures vary by culture, social class and ethnicity. Cross-cultural differences mean, for example, that polygamy is accepted in some societies and not others.",
    "Social class shapes family roles and resources, and ethnicity often influences family values and structure. There is no single \u2018correct\u2019 family \u2014 sociologists study the range and ask why it varies."],
    ex:{t:"Example — variation at work",b:["A wealthy family may afford childcare and larger homes, shaping who does which role.","In some cultures, extended family living is the norm; in others, nuclear living dominates.","Class, culture and ethnicity all shape the shape of the family."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List four family structures from this unit. For each, write one strength and one limitation in your own words \u2014 no examples needed, just clear reasons.",
  check:[
   {q:"A nuclear family is\u2026",o:["Only grandparents","Two parents and their children","A single person","A group of friends"],a:1},
   {q:"A beanpole family is a type of\u2026",o:["Reconstituted family","Childless family","Extended family (several generations)","Nuclear family"],a:2},
   {q:"A family formed when parents remarry and combine children is\u2026",o:["Polygamous","Empty nest","Reconstituted (blended)","Nuclear"],a:2},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u2",n:2,title:"Views on Family Diversity",mins:180,icon:"Lightbulb",
  summary:"How the New Right and postmodernists disagree about family diversity, plus alternatives to the family and types of marriage.",
  keyWords:["New Right","postmodernism","family diversity","single-person household","arranged marriage","serial monogamy"],
  sections:[
   {art:"theory",h:"The New Right view",p:[
    "The New Right believes the nuclear family is the ideal and sees other family types as less functional \u2014 even dysfunctional. It worries that different family forms can weaken discipline and stability.",
    "For example, the New Right argues that some lone-parent families may lack the structure children need, which they link to wider social problems. Critics say this unfairly blames certain families."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the New Right concern",b:["The New Right points to the nuclear family as the model for raising children.","It views a rise in lone-parent families with concern.","Critics reply that many lone-parent families raise children very successfully."]}},
   {art:"identity",h:"The postmodernist view",p:[
    "Postmodernists welcome family diversity, emphasising freedom of choice and adaptability. They see many valid ways to form a family, none automatically better than another.",
    "For example, postmodernists view same-sex families as positive, valid alternatives to traditional forms. Diversity, for them, is a strength of modern society, not a threat."],
    ex:{t:"Example — diversity as strength",b:["A postmodernist sees nuclear, lone-parent, same-sex and blended families as equally valid.","Each meets its members\u2019 needs in its own way.","Choice and adaptability are seen as gains, not problems."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Alternatives to the family",p:[
    "Not everyone lives in a family. Single-person households are individuals living alone \u2014 by choice, career or circumstance. Shared households are unrelated people sharing living space, such as roommates.",
    "\u2018Friends as family\u2019 describes close friendships that provide the emotional and practical support a family usually gives. These alternatives are increasingly common, especially in cities."],
    ex:{t:"Example — friends as family",b:["A group of friends share a flat and support each other through good and hard times.","They celebrate together, help with money, and provide emotional care.","For them, friends function much like a family."]}},
   {art:"marriage",h:"Variations in marriage",p:[
    "Marriage takes many forms. Arranged marriage is based on family or cultural tradition; a love marriage is based on mutual choice. Monogamy is one partner at a time; polygamy is more than one spouse.",
    "An empty-shell marriage is a couple staying together without emotional connection. Serial monogamy is a series of monogamous marriages one after another. Same-sex marriage is between partners of the same gender."],
    ex:{t:"Example — types side by side",b:["A love marriage rests on the couple\u2019s own choice.","An arranged marriage rests on family or cultural tradition.","Serial monogamy means several marriages over a lifetime, one at a time."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick the New Right OR the postmodernist view. Write two sentences explaining it fairly, then one sentence giving the opposing view.",
  check:[
   {q:"The New Right sees which family as ideal?",o:["The lone-parent family","The nuclear family","The childless couple","The shared household"],a:1},
   {q:"Postmodernists mainly view family diversity as\u2026",o:["Impossible","Illegal","A positive strength","A serious threat"],a:2},
   {q:"A marriage where the couple stays together with no emotional connection is\u2026",o:["An empty-shell marriage","Polygamy","Serial monogamy","A love marriage"],a:0},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u3",n:3,title:"The Functionalist Family",mins:180,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"How functionalists explain the family's positive role: functions, the loss-of-functions debate, and the warm bath theory.",
  keyWords:["functionalism","functions of the family","value transmission","warm bath theory","loss of functions","Parsons"],
  sections:[
   {art:"family",h:"The family as a pillar of society",p:[
    "Functionalists believe the family is essential for social order and stability. It provides emotional support, nurtures children and socialises individuals into society\u2019s norms and values.",
    "For example, the family teaches children respect, discipline and cooperation \u2014 the shared values that let society run smoothly. For functionalists, a healthy family means a healthy society."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the family as first teacher",b:["Before school, children learn right from wrong at home.","They learn to share, to greet elders, to follow rules.","Functionalists say this early socialisation holds society together."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"The functions of the family",p:[
    "Functionalists list several functions: socialisation of children, economic support, emotional stability and the reproduction of society. Each function helps both the members and the wider society.",
    "The loss-of-functions debate asks whether the family still does all of this. Over time, schools, hospitals and workplaces have taken over some roles \u2014 like education and healthcare \u2014 that families once handled alone."],
    ex:{t:"Example — functions shared out",b:["A century ago, families taught most skills at home.","Today, schools handle much education and hospitals handle much healthcare.","The family has lost some functions but kept socialisation and emotional support."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"The warm bath theory",p:[
    "The \u2018warm bath\u2019 theory, from Talcott Parsons, says the family offers a comforting environment where individuals relax and relieve the stress of daily life \u2014 like sinking into a warm bath.",
    "After a hard day, a person returns to the family to recover. For functionalists, this stabilisation of adult personalities is one of the family\u2019s most important jobs."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the warm bath in action",b:["After a stressful day at work, a parent comes home to family.","Time with loved ones eases the tension of the day.","Parsons called this the family acting as a \u2018warm bath\u2019."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"Strengths and limits of the functionalist view",p:[
    "The strength of the functionalist view is that it highlights the stabilising role of the family and its contribution to social order. It explains why almost every society has some form of family.",
    "Its limitation is that it can overlook inequalities inside families \u2014 gender divisions, conflict, even abuse. Later units add the Marxist and feminist views that focus on exactly those problems."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the missing side",b:["Functionalists praise the family\u2019s warmth and support.","But not every family is warm \u2014 some contain conflict or unfair burdens.","This blind spot is what feminists and Marxists step in to expose."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Explain the warm bath theory in two sentences of your own. Then give one strength and one limitation of the functionalist view of the family.",
  check:[
   {q:"Functionalists see the family as essential for\u2026",o:["Creating conflict","Social order and stability","Ending society","Only making money"],a:1},
   {q:"The 'warm bath' theory was proposed by\u2026",o:["A feminist writer","Talcott Parsons","Karl Marx","No one"],a:1},
   {q:"A limitation of the functionalist view is that it\u2026",o:["Ignores society","Overlooks inequalities inside families","Uses no ideas","Is illegal"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u4",n:4,title:"Marxist & Feminist Views of the Family",mins:180,icon:"BarChart2",
  summary:"How Marxists and feminists challenge the rosy picture: class reproduction, consumption, the domestic division of labour and the dual burden.",
  keyWords:["Marxism","reproduction of class","unit of consumption","feminism","domestic division of labour","dual burden","triple shift"],
  sections:[
   {art:"gap",h:"The Marxist view: family and capitalism",p:[
    "Marxists argue the family mainly serves capitalism. It reproduces the workforce (raising the next generation of workers) and passes wealth and status from one generation to the next, keeping class inequalities alive.",
    "For example, wealthy families pass down resources and advantages, maintaining class distinctions. The family, in this view, helps the rich stay rich."],
    ex:{t:"Example — inheritance and class",b:["A wealthy family funds tutoring, connections and property for its children.","Those advantages pass down the generations.","Marxists call this the reproduction of class inequalities."]}},
   {art:"data",h:"Family as a unit of consumption and ideological control",p:[
    "Marxists also see the family as a unit of consumption: families are encouraged to keep buying products, which benefits capitalist businesses. Advertising targets family life for exactly this reason.",
    "Through ideological control, the family socialises children to accept inequality as normal \u2014 teaching values that support the capitalist system rather than questioning it."],
    ex:{t:"Example — buying as a family",b:["Adverts push the newest phones, cars and holidays at families.","Each purchase feeds business profits.","Marxists say the family is turned into a unit of consumption."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"The feminist view: the domestic division of labour",p:[
    "Feminists argue that traditional family life reinforces patriarchy \u2014 male power over women. A key idea is the domestic division of labour: women are often expected to do most of the unpaid housework and childcare.",
    "This can limit women\u2019s opportunities outside the home. Feminists distinguish joint conjugal roles (partners share tasks) from segregated conjugal roles (partners have separate, unequal tasks)."],
    ex:{t:"Example — who does the housework",b:["In many homes, a mother manages childcare and housework while the father works outside.","Even when both work, she often does more at home.","Feminists call this the unequal domestic division of labour."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Dual burden, triple shift and evaluation",p:[
    "Many women carry a dual burden: paid work plus unpaid domestic work. Some carry a triple shift, adding emotional labour \u2014 caring for the family\u2019s feelings \u2014 on top.",
    "Each view has strengths and limits. Marxism highlights economics but can ignore care and love; feminism highlights gender inequality but can overlook happy, equal families. Sociologists debate whether family life is, overall, positive or negative."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the triple shift",b:["A woman works a full day, then does the housework, then comforts an upset child.","That is paid work, domestic work and emotional work in one day.","Feminists call this the triple shift."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Explain the dual burden and the triple shift in your own words. Then say which view \u2014 Marxist or feminist \u2014 you find more convincing, and why.",
  check:[
   {q:"Marxists argue the family helps to\u2026",o:["Remove all wealth","Abolish work","Reproduce class inequalities","End capitalism"],a:2},
   {q:"The unequal sharing of housework and childcare is the\u2026",o:["Caste system","Loss of functions","Domestic division of labour","Warm bath theory"],a:2},
   {q:"A woman doing paid work, housework AND emotional care carries the\u2026",o:["Warm bath","No shift","Triple shift","Single shift"],a:2},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u5",n:5,title:"A Changing Population",mins:180,icon:"BookOpen",
  summary:"How demographic change \u2014 family size, birth rates, life expectancy and ageing \u2014 reshapes family life, alongside industrialisation and urbanisation.",
  keyWords:["demography","family size","birth rate","life expectancy","ageing population","industrialisation","urbanisation"],
  sections:[
   {art:"chart",h:"Smaller families and falling birth rates",p:[
    "Families have generally become smaller, with fewer children per household. Causes include economic pressures, family planning and career-focused lifestyles.",
    "Birth rates have declined in many societies, influenced by contraception, careers and the choice to prioritise personal goals. Smaller families change how homes and daily life are organised."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the smaller family",b:["A century ago large families were common.","Today, one or two children per household is more typical in many cities.","Family planning and cost help explain the change."]}},
   {art:"planet",h:"Living longer and an ageing population",p:[
    "Life expectancy has risen: people live longer, so grandparents and even great-grandparents are more common in family networks. This lengthens the generations a family spans.",
    "An ageing population means more elderly members needing care, which changes family roles \u2014 middle-aged adults increasingly care for parents as well as children."],
    ex:{t:"Example — four generations",b:["Longer lives mean a child may know great-grandparents.","But more elderly relatives may also need care.","Family roles stretch to include caring for the old as well as the young."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Having children later",p:[
    "Many people now have children later in life, often because of education, career development or personal choice. This tends to mean smaller families and different relationships between the generations.",
    "Later parenthood can bring more financial stability but also new challenges, such as caring for young children and ageing parents at the same time."],
    ex:{t:"Example — parenthood delayed",b:["A couple focuses on careers through their twenties.","They have their first child in their thirties.","The family is smaller and the generation gap may be wider."]}},
   {art:"school",h:"Industrialisation and urbanisation",p:[
    "As societies moved from farming to industry (industrialisation), extended families \u2014 common in farming communities \u2014 gave way to nuclear families better suited to factory work and moving for jobs.",
    "Urbanisation, the move to cities, made families smaller, more mobile and more nuclear-focused, often with dual-income households and more shared responsibilities."],
    ex:{t:"Example — from farm to city",b:["On a farm, a large extended family shared the work.","Moving to a city for factory jobs favoured a smaller, mobile nuclear family.","Industrialisation and urbanisation reshaped the family."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose two demographic changes (smaller families, falling birth rates, longer life, ageing population, later children). Explain how each one changes everyday family life.",
  check:[
   {q:"Rising life expectancy tends to produce\u2026",o:["No grandparents","Smaller lifespans","More generations and an ageing population","Larger birth rates"],a:2},
   {q:"Industrialisation encouraged a shift toward\u2026",o:["Larger extended families","No families","Polygamy","Nuclear families"],a:3},
   {q:"A cause of smaller families is\u2026",o:["Fewer cities","Family planning and economic pressure","More farms","Longer weekends"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u6",n:6,title:"Marriage, Divorce & Cohabitation",mins:180,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"Why patterns of marriage, divorce and cohabitation have changed \u2014 and the growing alternatives to marriage.",
  keyWords:["cohabitation","divorce","secularisation","female empowerment","civil partnership","singlehood"],
  sections:[
   {art:"marriage",h:"Why patterns have changed",p:[
    "Several forces have changed marriage and divorce. Legislation has made marriage and divorce more flexible, and expanded recognition of civil partnerships and same-sex marriage.",
    "Changing societal attitudes now accept cohabitation, singlehood and non-traditional families far more than before. Social norms, not just laws, have shifted."],
    ex:{t:"Example — law and attitude together",b:["Easier divorce laws let people leave unhappy marriages.","Changing attitudes made divorce less shameful.","Both together explain why patterns changed."]}},
   {art:"global",h:"The internet, secularisation and culture",p:[
    "The internet has changed how people meet, through online dating and social media, widening the pool of potential partners beyond traditional settings.",
    "Secularisation \u2014 the declining influence of religion in some societies \u2014 has reduced traditional expectations around marriage. Evolving cultural expectations now allow more diverse, egalitarian relationships."],
    ex:{t:"Example — meeting online",b:["Couples once met mainly through family, work or community.","Now many meet through apps and social media.","The internet reshaped how relationships begin."]}},
   {art:"identity",h:"Female empowerment",p:[
    "As women gain independence, education and equal rights, they have more freedom to make their own choices about marriage, career and family. This is often called female empowerment.",
    "Greater female empowerment means women are less dependent on marriage for security, which changes when \u2014 and whether \u2014 people marry."],
    ex:{t:"Example — choice through independence",b:["A woman with her own career and income can choose whether and when to marry.","Marriage becomes a choice, not a necessity.","Female empowerment reshapes family decisions."]}},
   {art:"marriage",h:"Alternatives to marriage",p:[
    "Marriage is no longer the only path. Cohabitation means living together without marrying. Singlehood is choosing to remain single. Lone parenthood and civil partnerships are increasingly common and accepted.",
    "Newer forms include long-distance relationships and \u2018living apart together\u2019 (LAT), where committed partners choose to keep separate homes. Family life has many valid shapes."],
    ex:{t:"Example — cohabiting couples",b:["A couple shares a home, finances and responsibilities without marrying.","They enjoy partnership with more flexibility.","Cohabitation is now a common alternative to marriage."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List three reasons marriage and divorce patterns have changed. Then name two alternatives to marriage and describe each in one sentence.",
  check:[
   {q:"The declining influence of religion on marriage is called\u2026",o:["Secularisation","Urbanisation","Colonialism","Canalisation"],a:0},
   {q:"Living together without getting married is\u2026",o:["Serial monogamy","Cohabitation","An arranged marriage","An empty shell"],a:1},
   {q:"Greater female empowerment tends to\u2026",o:["Lower education","Give women more choice about marriage and family","End all families","Force earlier marriage"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u7",n:7,title:"Changing Roles in the Home",mins:180,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"How conjugal roles and the roles of children have changed: symmetrical families, the sandwich generation, child-centredness and boomerang children.",
  keyWords:["conjugal roles","symmetrical family","dual-worker family","sandwich generation","child-centredness","boomerang children"],
  sections:[
   {art:"home",h:"From segregated to joint roles",p:[
    "Conjugal roles are the roles of partners within a couple. Families have shifted from segregated roles (separate, unequal male and female tasks) toward joint conjugal roles, where both partners share the work.",
    "The symmetrical family describes a home where partners contribute fairly equally to childcare and housework \u2014 common in dual-worker families where both partners have jobs."],
    ex:{t:"Example — sharing the load",b:["In the past, one partner earned money and the other ran the home.","In a symmetrical family, both work and both share housework and childcare.","Roles have become more joint and equal."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Dual-worker and sandwich generation",p:[
    "In a dual-worker family, both partners work, sharing financial responsibility and, increasingly, domestic tasks. This changes the daily rhythm of family life.",
    "The pivot or \u2018sandwich generation\u2019 describes middle-aged adults who care for both their children and their ageing parents at once \u2014 squeezed between two sets of needs."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the sandwich generation",b:["A middle-aged woman helps her teenagers with school and her elderly mother with care.","She is caught between two generations\u2019 needs.","Sociologists call this the sandwich generation."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Changing roles of children",p:[
    "Raising children has become more expensive \u2014 children are now more of an economic cost than an economic help. At the same time, families have become more child-centred, focusing on children\u2019s needs and development.",
    "Child-centred parenting means more resources aimed at education, activities and individual care, treating childhood as a special, protected stage."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the child at the centre",b:["Parents invest heavily in tutoring, activities and a child\u2019s wellbeing.","Childhood is treated as precious and protected.","Sociologists call this child-centredness."]}},
   {art:"home",h:"Boomerang children",p:[
    "Young adults increasingly return to live with their parents after education \u2014 so-called boomerang children \u2014 often because of housing costs or money worries.",
    "This extends dependency into adulthood and changes family roles again: parents continue supporting adult children longer than in the past."],
    ex:{t:"Example — coming back home",b:["A graduate cannot yet afford their own place.","They move back in with their parents for a few years.","Boomerang children extend family dependency into adulthood."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Explain the symmetrical family and the sandwich generation in your own words. Then give one reason children\u2019s roles in families have changed.",
  check:[
   {q:"A home where partners share tasks fairly equally is a\u2026",o:["Empty-shell marriage","Segregated family","Polygamous family","Symmetrical family"],a:3},
   {q:"Adults caring for both children and ageing parents are the\u2026",o:["Underclass","Boomerang children","Reserve army","Sandwich generation"],a:3},
   {q:"Young adults returning home after education are\u2026",o:["Empty nesters","Child-centred","Lone parents","Boomerang children"],a:3},
  ]},

 {id:"y1u8",n:8,title:"The Role of Grandparents",mins:180,icon:"Heart",
  summary:"How grandparents support modern families through childcare, money, wisdom \u2014 and how they can also become dependent.",
  keyWords:["grandparents","childcare","economic support","wisdom","dependence","extended support"],
  sections:[
   {art:"help",h:"Grandparents as childcare",p:[
    "Many grandparents actively help with childcare, watching grandchildren while parents work. This support is especially valuable in dual-worker families where both parents have jobs.",
    "Grandparent childcare can save families money and strengthen bonds across the generations \u2014 a practical and emotional contribution to family life."],
    ex:{t:"Example — grandparents helping out",b:["Both parents work full time.","A grandmother collects the children from school and cares for them until evening.","Her childcare keeps the family running."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Economic support",p:[
    "Grandparents sometimes provide financial help to their adult children or grandchildren, especially in hard times \u2014 helping with rent, education or emergencies.",
    "This economic support can ease pressure on younger family members and is another way grandparents shape modern family life."],
    ex:{t:"Example — a helping hand",b:["A young family struggles with rising costs.","Grandparents contribute toward school fees or bills.","Their economic support cushions the family."]}},
   {art:"interpret",h:"Wisdom and advice",p:[
    "Grandparents often act as family mentors, sharing cultural values, life lessons and family history. They pass on identity and experience to younger generations.",
    "This role connects the family to its past and helps younger members learn from those who came before them."],
    ex:{t:"Example — passing on wisdom",b:["A grandfather tells stories of the family\u2019s history and values.","Grandchildren learn where they come from.","Grandparents pass on identity and advice."]}},
   {art:"family",h:"When grandparents need care",p:[
    "With longer lives, some grandparents become dependent on their children or grandchildren for care and support. This can add financial and emotional strain on families.",
    "So the grandparent role runs both ways: grandparents give support for years, then may need support in turn \u2014 a key theme in a family life that now spans more generations."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the role reverses",b:["For years a grandmother helped with childcare.","In old age she needs care herself.","The family now supports her, showing how roles can reverse."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List the four roles grandparents can play in modern families. Then explain, in two sentences, how the grandparent role can reverse over time.",
  check:[
   {q:"A common practical role of grandparents is\u2026",o:["Owning all businesses","Running the government","Childcare while parents work","Setting school exams"],a:2},
   {q:"Grandparents sharing family history and values provide\u2026",o:["Legal punishment","Only money","Wisdom and advice","Nothing"],a:2},
   {q:"With longer lives, some grandparents may become\u2026",o:["Younger","Dependent on their family for care","Childless","Employers"],a:1},
  ]},,
 {id:"y1u9",n:9,title:"Exam Skills: Answering IGCSE Command Questions",mins:180,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"How to read each command word and structure top-scoring answers — with real structural analysis of the highest-mark Explain, Discuss and Evaluate questions from the Cambridge 0495 specimen papers.",
  keyWords:["command word","Identify","Define","Explain","Discuss","Evaluate","PEEL","mark scheme"],
  sections:[
   {art:"command",h:"The seven command words and what they demand",p:[
    "Every IGCSE Sociology (0495) question opens with a command word that tells you exactly what to do. Marks are lost when students know the content but answer the wrong command. The seven words rise in difficulty: Identify, Define, Give (short, exact), Describe, Explain (developed points), and Discuss, Evaluate (two-sided argument plus a judgement).",
    "The number in brackets is your instruction for length. A [2] wants one or two exact items. A [4] wants two points, each with a reason. A [6] wants three developed points. A [8] Discuss wants three well-developed points. A [10], [12] or [14] wants a full structured essay. Always let the marks decide how much you write.",
    "Cambridge assesses three skills: AO1 (knowledge of terms, theories and studies), AO2 (applying that knowledge to the question), and AO3 (analysing and evaluating). Low-mark questions are mostly AO1/AO2; the big essays add AO3. Knowing which skill a question wants tells you how to shape the answer."],
    ex:{t:"Example \u2014 one topic, three commands (from the 0495 papers)",b:["\u2018Identify two types of question used by sociologists.\u2019 [2] \u2192 just name two, e.g. open and multiple-choice.","\u2018Explain three reasons why people may join deviant sub-cultures.\u2019 [6] \u2192 three developed paragraphs.","\u2018Evaluate the view that gender is the main influence on identity.\u2019 [14] \u2192 three arguments for, three against, and a conclusion.","Same subject knowledge \u2014 the command word decides the shape of the answer."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Identify, Define, Give and Describe (the short-answer marks)",p:[
    "Identify and Give want you to state something correctly \u2014 usually [2]. Do not explain or add detail; the examiner reports that extra detail earns no marks and wastes time. In the specimen paper, \u2018Identify two types of question\u2019 scored full marks with just \u2018Open questions and multiple-choice questions.\u2019",
    "Define wants the precise meaning of a term, [2]. A full definition has TWO elements; a bare example is only a \u2018partial\u2019 definition and scores one mark. The specimen answer defined feminism as a sociological theory (element one) that focuses on gender inequality and patriarchy (element two) \u2014 two elements, full marks.",
    "Describe wants a detailed account with signal words. \u2018Describe three types of marriage\u2019 [6] gives one mark for naming each type and one for describing it. The specimen lost a mark because it named polygamy but never described it \u2014 proving you must develop every point you raise, and always signal them: \u2018One type\u2026 A second type\u2026\u2019."],
    ex:{t:"Example \u2014 why marks are lost on easy questions",b:["\u2018Give two negative sanctions used in the family\u2019 [2]: one specimen answer said \u2018being told off\u2019 (correct) and \u2018being sent to prison\u2019 \u2014 prison is not a family sanction, so it scored 1/2.","Lesson: read the exact context (\u2018in the family\u2019) before answering.","On these questions, accuracy and staying on-context matter more than length."]}},
   {art:"build",h:"EXPLAIN questions: the PEEL structure that scores full marks",p:[
    "Explain questions ([4] or [6]) ask HOW or WHY. The examiner\u2019s golden tip appears again and again in the mark schemes: use the word \u2018because\u2019 \u2014 it forces you to explain rather than merely describe. Each point needs a clear structure: POINT (state it), EXPLAIN (the \u2018because\u2026\u2019 reason), EXAMPLE (a concrete illustration), and where useful a LINK back to the question.",
    "Structure matters as much as content. In the specimen \u2018Explain three reasons why people join deviant sub-cultures\u2019 [6], the top answer scored 6/6 with three separate paragraphs, each signalled (\u2018One reason\u2026 A second reason\u2026 A third reason\u2026\u2019), each naming a reason then developing it with a study or example (status frustration and Cohen; relative deprivation; the thrill factor).",
    "One mark per point is for the correct point; the second mark is for developing it. The specimen \u2018Explain three ways identity can be chosen\u2019 [6] scored only 5/6 because the third point (joining interest-based networks) was named but not developed \u2014 \u2018more explanation was needed\u2019. The pattern is clear: never leave a point undeveloped."],
    ex:{t:"Structural analysis \u2014 \u2018Explain three reasons why poverty might lead to crime.\u2019 [6] (scored 6/6)",b:["POINT 1 \u2014 the underclass (New Right, Murray): named, then explained via poor socialisation and benefit dependency. [2 marks]","POINT 2 \u2014 material deprivation (Marxists): named, then explained as lacking money/food, leading to shoplifting. [2 marks]","POINT 3 \u2014 status frustration (Cohen): named, then explained via anger at unfairness and lack of status. [2 marks]","Structure = 3 signalled paragraphs \u00D7 (point + because-reason + study/example). That repeatable shape is full marks."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"DISCUSS questions [8]: three developed points with evidence",p:[
    "A \u2018Discuss\u2026 include at least three developed points with evidence\u2019 [8] is a mini-essay. It needs three points, each developed MORE deeply than in a [6] Explain, because it is a higher-tariff question. The examiner explicitly notes part (e) answers need \u2018a greater level of development (evidence and analysis)\u2019 than part (d).",
    "Structure each point as its own paragraph: state the point, develop it with sociological concepts, and support it with evidence, a study or a real example. Signal each clearly. The specimen \u2018Discuss how family functions have changed\u2019 [8] scored full marks by discussing three functions (reproduction \u2014 with \u2018DINK families\u2019 evidence; socialisation \u2014 nurseries and media; emotional care \u2014 care homes), each a developed paragraph.",
    "A key examiner warning for [8] Discuss: do NOT waste time on long introductions or conclusions, and do not criticise the view if the question does not ask for evaluation \u2014 no marks are given for that. Spend every sentence developing your three points. Depth, not breadth: three deep points beat five shallow ones."],
    ex:{t:"Structural analysis \u2014 \u2018Discuss the view that crime and deviance are relative.\u2019 [8]",b:["Best practice: open by showing you understand \u2018relative\u2019 (definitions can change) with a theory link (interactionism) \u2014 but keep it brief.","POINT 1 \u2014 situation: the same act (a punch) is acceptable in a boxing ring, deviant in the street. Develop WHY.","POINT 2 \u2014 time/era: smoking was once a norm, now restricted and deviant in many places.","POINT 3 \u2014 culture: acts like adultery are treated very differently across societies.","Examiner note: this specimen lost marks where points were named but under-developed \u2014 depth is everything at [8]."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"EVALUATE questions [10\u201314]: the full for/against/judgement essay",p:[
    "Evaluate is the highest-tariff question ([10], [12] or [14]) and follows a strict rubric printed on the paper: \u2018at least [two or three] arguments for the view and [two or three] against, and a conclusion\u2019. Meeting every element of that rubric is how you reach the top level (Level 3 or 4). Miss the conclusion, or give only one side, and you cannot reach the top band.",
    "The structure is: (1) a brief definition/context \u2014 no long introduction; (2) developed arguments FOR, each its own paragraph with evidence; (3) developed arguments AGAINST, signalled with \u2018On the other hand\u2026\u2019 or \u2018However\u2026\u2019; (4) a CONCLUSION that makes a reasoned judgement, not just a summary. Use sociological perspectives (functionalist, Marxist, feminist, interactionist) as ready-made sides.",
    "What lifts an Evaluate answer into the top level: naming studies and sociologists (Oakley, Cohen, Murray, Becker), using precise concepts (canalisation, status frustration, patriarchy, vertical/horizontal segregation), linking every argument back to the exact wording of the question, and ending with a genuine judgement. The specimen answers that scored 12\u201313 out of 14 did all of these; where they dropped marks, it was usually a weaker link to the question or a judgement that did not fully weigh the evidence."],
    ex:{t:"Structural analysis \u2014 \u2018Evaluate the view that gender is the main influence on identity.\u2019 [14] (scored 12/14)",b:["FOR (3 developed paragraphs): primary socialisation (Oakley \u2014 canalisation, manipulation); secondary socialisation (school, peer pressure); the gendered division of labour (vertical/horizontal segregation).","AGAINST (3 developed paragraphs): other influences \u2014 class, age and stereotyping of the elderly \u2014 each shown to shape identity too.","CONCLUSION: a judgement \u2014 identity is now more chosen, and class and age are \u2018now as important as gender\u2019.","Why 12 not 14: one \u2018against\u2019 paragraph was less developed and its link to \u2018identity\u2019 was left implicit. Lesson: develop EVERY paragraph equally and link each one explicitly to the question.","Rubric met = top band: three for, three against, evidence throughout, and a reasoned conclusion."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick any [8] Discuss or [10–14] Evaluate question from your course. Plan it on paper: write your three FOR points, three AGAINST points (each with a study or example), and a one-sentence judgement. Check every paragraph links back to the exact question.",
  check:[
   {q:"A [14] Evaluate question always requires…",o:["Only one strong side","Arguments for, arguments against, and a conclusion","Just definitions","A long introduction"],a:1},
   {q:"The examiner’s tip for turning description into explanation is to use the word…",o:["finally","however","because","therefore"],a:2},
   {q:"In a [6] Explain question, the second mark for each point is earned by…",o:["Developing the point with a reason or example","Listing more points","Writing a conclusion","Naming the point only"],a:0},
  ]}

];
