const SOC11T3_UNITS=[
 {id:"y3u1",n:1,title:"Crime, Deviance & Formal Control",mins:180,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"The difference between crime and deviance, the idea of relativity, and the formal agencies that keep order.",
  keyWords:["crime","deviance","relativity","social control","formal control","penal system"],
  sections:[
   {art:"crime",h:"Crime versus deviance",p:[
    "Crime is any action that breaks the formal written laws of a society and is punishable by the legal system \u2014 theft, assault, fraud. Deviance is behaviour that breaks a society\u2019s norms and values, but is not always illegal.",
    "So the two overlap but are not the same: some deviance (like talking loudly in a library) is not a crime, and the line between them shifts."],
    ex:{t:"Example — breaking rules two ways",b:["Theft breaks the law \u2014 it is a crime.","Wearing pyjamas to a formal event breaks norms \u2014 it is deviant but not illegal.","Crime breaks laws; deviance breaks norms."]}},
   {art:"culture",h:"The relativity of crime and deviance",p:[
    "Relativity means what counts as crime or deviance can change. It varies between cultures (alcohol is legal in some countries, banned in others), across time (some acts once illegal are now accepted), and by situation (shouting is fine at a match, not in a courtroom).",
    "This shows crime and deviance are not fixed facts of nature \u2014 they are socially constructed by each society."],
    ex:{t:"Example — shifting lines",b:["Drinking alcohol is legal in some societies and forbidden in others.","An act once treated as a crime may later be accepted.","Crime and deviance are relative \u2014 they depend on time, place and situation."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"What is social control?",p:[
    "Social control is the set of ways society encourages conformity to norms and laws and discourages deviance and crime. It uses both formal and informal mechanisms.",
    "Formal social control uses official institutions to enforce laws and rules; informal control (studied next unit) uses everyday social pressure. Together they keep behaviour within limits."],
    ex:{t:"Example — two kinds of control",b:["A court punishing a thief is formal control.","Friends disapproving of cheating is informal control.","Both encourage conformity."]}},
   {art:"law",h:"Formal agencies of control",p:[
    "The formal agencies are the police (enforce laws, investigate, arrest), the courts (decide guilt and punishment), the government (makes laws and oversees the system), the armed forces (protect the country and keep order in emergencies), and the penal system (prisons and rehabilitation).",
    "They prevent crime and deviance through law enforcement (awareness of consequences), punishment and deterrence, and rehabilitation aimed at reforming offenders."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the system in action",b:["Police arrest a suspected thief.","A court decides guilt and sets a punishment.","The penal system carries out the sentence and tries to rehabilitate."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Explain the difference between crime and deviance in your own words. Then give one example each of how they can be relative (change by culture, time or situation).",
  check:[
   {q:"Crime is behaviour that\u2026",o:["Breaks formal written laws","Breaks only norms","Is always accepted","Never has punishment"],a:0},
   {q:"Deviance is behaviour that\u2026",o:["Is always a crime","Breaks norms, not always illegal","Never breaks rules","Always breaks the law"],a:1},
   {q:"Crime and deviance being 'relative' means they\u2026",o:["Are fixed by nature","Change by culture, time and situation","Are the same everywhere","Never change"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u2",n:2,title:"Informal Social Control",mins:180,icon:"Users",
  summary:"How informal agencies shape behaviour without formal punishment, and how effective this control is.",
  keyWords:["informal control","family","peer group","media","religion","conformity"],
  sections:[
   {art:"social",h:"What is informal social control?",p:[
    "Informal social control is the way people are encouraged to follow rules, norms and values WITHOUT formal punishment like laws or police. It works through everyday interactions and expectations.",
    "Instead of fines or prison, it uses approval and disapproval \u2014 praise, respect, teasing, shame \u2014 to guide behaviour. It is quieter than formal control but often more constant."],
    ex:{t:"Example — no police needed",b:["A teenager avoids stealing not from fear of police\u2026","\u2026but because they don\u2019t want to disappoint their parents or lose friends\u2019 respect.","That is informal social control."]}},
   {art:"family",h:"Informal agencies: family and education",p:[
    "The family teaches children right from wrong, using praise, discipline and disappointment to shape behaviour \u2014 usually the first and most powerful informal agency.",
    "Education (schools) encourages punctuality, obedience and hard work through the hidden curriculum, rewarding good behaviour and punishing misbehaviour."],
    ex:{t:"Example — early lessons",b:["A parent praises honesty and shows disappointment at lying.","A school rewards punctuality and good conduct.","Both shape behaviour informally."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"Informal agencies: workplace, peers, media, religion",p:[
    "The workplace sets rules on dress, behaviour and communication, with promotion or dismissal encouraging conformity. The peer group influences behaviour through peer pressure \u2014 acceptance depends on following group norms.",
    "Traditional and digital media promote certain lifestyles and values, shaming some behaviours and praising others. Religion teaches moral values like honesty and kindness that guide daily actions."],
    ex:{t:"Example — peer pressure",b:["A friendship group expects certain behaviour.","Members conform to stay accepted.","The peer group exerts informal control."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"How effective is informal control?",p:[
    "Strengths: informal control works early in life (especially through family), encourages internal discipline (doing right because it feels right), and supports long-term stability.",
    "Limitations: not everyone responds to it; peer pressure or media can promote negative behaviour; and it may be weak where formal controls like law enforcement are also weak. It works best alongside formal control."],
    ex:{t:"Example — strengths and limits together",b:["A child raised to value honesty may never need the police to behave well.","But peer pressure could also push someone toward bad behaviour.","Informal control has both strengths and limits."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List the informal agencies of social control. For two of them, explain how they encourage good behaviour without any formal punishment.",
  check:[
   {q:"Informal social control works\u2026",o:["Only through prisons","Only through fines","Without formal punishment like laws or police","Only through courts"],a:2},
   {q:"Which is an informal agency of social control?",o:["The courts","The peer group","The armed forces","The penal system"],a:1},
   {q:"A strength of informal control is that it\u2026",o:["Only uses fines","Encourages internal discipline early in life","Needs no people","Requires prisons"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u3",n:3,title:"Types of Crime",mins:180,icon:"ClipboardCheck",
  summary:"The main categories of crime sociologists distinguish, from violent and property crime to cyber, green and corporate crime.",
  keyWords:["violent crime","property crime","white-collar crime","cyber crime","green crime","hate crime"],
  sections:[
   {art:"crime",h:"Violent, property and corporate crime",p:[
    "Violent crime involves physical harm or the threat of it \u2014 murder, assault. Property crime involves stealing or damaging property \u2014 theft, burglary.",
    "White-collar or corporate crime is committed by people in high-status jobs or companies for financial gain \u2014 fraud, embezzlement. It often causes huge harm but is less visible than street crime."],
    ex:{t:"Example — three categories",b:["An assault is a violent crime.","A burglary is a property crime.","Company fraud is a white-collar (corporate) crime."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Expressive, instrumental and gang crime",p:[
    "Expressive crime is committed out of emotion or feeling \u2014 a crime of passion. Instrumental crime is committed to achieve a goal, often money \u2014 robbery, drug dealing.",
    "Gang crime is committed by organised groups, such as drug trafficking or violent assaults carried out by a gang."],
    ex:{t:"Example — motive matters",b:["A crime of passion is expressive \u2014 driven by emotion.","A robbery for money is instrumental \u2014 driven by a goal.","The motive helps classify the crime."]}},
   {art:"planet",h:"Green, global, cyber, hate and domestic crime",p:[
    "Green crime harms the environment \u2014 illegal logging, pollution. Global crime crosses borders \u2014 human trafficking, organised crime networks. Cyber crime uses digital technology \u2014 hacking, online scams.",
    "Hate crime is motivated by prejudice \u2014 racist or homophobic attacks. Domestic crime happens within the home or family \u2014 domestic violence, child abuse."],
    ex:{t:"Example — modern crime types",b:["Hacking a bank account is cyber crime.","Illegal pollution is green crime.","An attack motivated by prejudice is a hate crime."]}},
   {art:"measure",h:"Why classify crime?",p:[
    "Classifying crime helps sociologists study patterns and causes. Different crimes have different motives, victims and social meanings, so lumping them together would hide important differences.",
    "It also reveals which crimes society treats seriously and which it overlooks \u2014 for example, corporate crime often causes vast harm yet receives less attention than street crime."],
    ex:{t:"Example — hidden harm",b:["A street theft is highly visible and often punished.","Large-scale corporate fraud may harm thousands but attract less attention.","Classifying crime exposes these differences."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List six types of crime from this unit. For three of them, write one sentence describing what makes each type distinct.",
  check:[
   {q:"White-collar crime is committed by\u2026",o:["Only teenagers","Only strangers","No one","People in high-status jobs for financial gain"],a:3},
   {q:"Crime that harms the environment is\u2026",o:["Hate crime","Green crime","Cyber crime","Property crime"],a:1},
   {q:"Crime committed to achieve a goal, often money, is\u2026",o:["Domestic crime","Instrumental crime","Green crime","Expressive crime"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u4",n:4,title:"Measuring Crime",mins:180,icon:"BarChart2",
  summary:"The three main ways of measuring crime, their strengths and limits, and the problem of hidden crime.",
  keyWords:["official statistics","self-report studies","victim surveys","dark figure of crime","unreported crime"],
  sections:[
   {art:"measure",h:"Official statistics",p:[
    "Official statistics are collected by the police and government agencies, showing reported and recorded crimes. Their strengths are that they are easy to access and useful for tracking trends over time.",
    "Their limitations are serious: many crimes go unreported or unrecorded, and the figures can reflect police priorities more than actual crime rates."],
    ex:{t:"Example — reading the numbers",b:["Police statistics show recorded thefts rising.","But some thefts are never reported.","So the statistics may understate the true amount."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Self-report studies",p:[
    "Self-report studies ask people, usually anonymously, whether they have committed crimes. Their strength is that they can reveal unreported crimes and help us understand criminal behaviour.",
    "Their limitation is that people may lie or forget, and the sample may not represent the wider population."],
    ex:{t:"Example — asking directly",b:["An anonymous survey asks people about crimes they have committed.","It can uncover offences the police never knew about.","But respondents may not always tell the truth."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Victim surveys",p:[
    "Victim surveys ask people whether they have been victims of crime, at local or national level. Their strength is highlighting crimes that go unreported and showing the impact of crime on people.",
    "Their limitation is that memory may be unreliable, and some crimes \u2014 such as domestic abuse \u2014 may still stay hidden."],
    ex:{t:"Example — asking victims",b:["A national survey asks people if they were victims of crime last year.","It reveals crimes never reported to police.","But some sensitive crimes may still go unmentioned."]}},
   {art:"measure",h:"The dark figure of crime",p:[
    "The gap between crimes that happen and crimes that are officially recorded is called the \u2018dark figure of crime\u2019. Many crimes are never reported \u2014 due to fear of retaliation, shame, or lack of trust in authorities.",
    "Some reported crimes are also not recorded by the police, which affects accuracy. Because of this, no single measure gives a complete picture \u2014 which is why sociologists use several together."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the hidden crimes",b:["A victim is too ashamed or afraid to report a crime.","It never appears in any statistic.","These hidden crimes form the dark figure of crime."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Compare the three ways of measuring crime. For each, give one strength and one limitation. Then explain what the 'dark figure of crime' means.",
  check:[
   {q:"Official statistics are collected by\u2026",o:["No one","The police and government agencies","Only victims","Only offenders"],a:1},
   {q:"Self-report studies ask people whether they\u2026",o:["Enjoy school","Like sport","Vote","Have committed crimes"],a:3},
   {q:"The 'dark figure of crime' refers to\u2026",o:["Crimes that are not reported or recorded","Solved crimes","Recorded crimes only","Crimes in the dark only"],a:0},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u5",n:5,title:"Patterns & Explanations: Age",mins:180,icon:"Target",
  summary:"The patterns in who commits and suffers crime, and the explanations for youth crime.",
  keyWords:["patterns of crime","age","stereotyping","gang culture","status frustration","self-fulfilling prophecy"],
  sections:[
   {art:"chance",h:"Patterns of crime and victimisation",p:[
    "Sociologists study patterns to see who is more likely to commit or suffer crime. Key patterns: young people are more likely to offend and be victims; working-class individuals appear more often, partly due to inequality.",
    "Males commit more recorded crimes than females (though female offending is rising), and ethnic minorities are often over-represented in statistics and face higher victimisation."],
    ex:{t:"Example — reading the patterns",b:["Young people appear often in crime statistics.","So do working-class individuals.","These patterns are what explanations try to account for."]}},
   {art:"identity",h:"Police targeting and self-fulfilling prophecy",p:[
    "Young people are more likely to be stopped and searched by police, especially if they fit certain stereotypes \u2014 which can inflate youth crime figures.",
    "If youths are labelled \u2018troublemakers\u2019, they may begin to act in ways that match the label \u2014 a self-fulfilling prophecy \u2014 turning a stereotype into reality."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the label comes true",b:["Youths are repeatedly treated as troublemakers.","Some begin to behave that way.","A self-fulfilling prophecy has taken hold."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Stereotyping and gang culture",p:[
    "Stereotyping means young people \u2014 especially those from certain groups or wearing certain styles \u2014 may be unfairly judged as criminal, affecting how they are treated.",
    "Gang culture can draw some youths in for protection, belonging or income, which raises criminal involvement. The gang offers something mainstream society has not."],
    ex:{t:"Example — joining a gang",b:["A young person lacks money, belonging and protection.","A gang seems to offer all three.","Gang culture pulls them toward crime."]}},
   {art:"theory",h:"Socialisation, opportunity and status frustration",p:[
    "Weak socialisation and social control \u2014 from family, school or community \u2014 can lead to deviance. A lack of opportunity (jobs, education, recreation) may push young people toward crime.",
    "Status frustration is key: when youths cannot gain respect or success in mainstream ways, they may seek it through deviance instead."],
    ex:{t:"Example — status frustration",b:["A young person cannot succeed at school or find work.","They feel blocked from respect and success.","They may seek status through deviance \u2014 status frustration."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List three explanations for youth crime. Explain how status frustration and the self-fulfilling prophecy can each lead a young person toward deviance.",
  check:[
   {q:"Which group is more likely to appear in crime statistics?",o:["Only the elderly","Only children under 5","No one","Young people"],a:3},
   {q:"Seeking respect through deviance when blocked from mainstream success is\u2026",o:["Meritocracy","Cultural capital","Status frustration","Secularisation"],a:2},
   {q:"Youths labelled 'troublemakers' who then behave that way show\u2026",o:["Deterrence","A self-fulfilling prophecy","A victim survey","Rehabilitation"],a:1},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u6",n:6,title:"Explanations: Ethnicity, Gender & Class",mins:180,icon:"Lightbulb",
  summary:"How sociologists explain patterns of crime by ethnicity, gender and social class.",
  keyWords:["institutional racism","chivalry thesis","culture of masculinity","material deprivation","power inequalities","social exclusion"],
  sections:[
   {art:"law",h:"Ethnicity and crime",p:[
    "Several reasons are given for ethnic minorities appearing more often in crime statistics: institutional racism (discrimination built into institutions like the police), and prejudice and discrimination from authorities.",
    "Police targeting through stop and search, material and relative deprivation, stereotyping, gang culture and status frustration all add to the picture \u2014 much of it about how minorities are TREATED, not just how they behave."],
    ex:{t:"Example — treatment, not just behaviour",b:["Ethnic minorities are more likely to be stopped and searched.","This can inflate their appearance in statistics.","Explanations focus on treatment as well as behaviour."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Gender and crime",p:[
    "Crime rates differ by gender. The chivalry thesis suggests women are treated more leniently by the justice system. A culture of masculinity may push some men to prove toughness through crime.",
    "Girls are often more strictly socialised and controlled, reducing risk-taking. Misogyny can drive gender-based crimes; stereotyping means women are seen as less likely to offend; lack of opportunity may push some women toward crimes like theft."],
    ex:{t:"Example — the chivalry thesis",b:["A court may treat a female offender more leniently.","This could lower recorded female crime.","The chivalry thesis offers one explanation."]}},
   {art:"gap",h:"Social class and crime",p:[
    "Working-class people appear more often in crime statistics for several reasons: social exclusion (being pushed to the margins), material and relative deprivation (poverty increasing pressure), and inadequate socialisation.",
    "Add a lack of opportunity, status frustration, power inequalities (the powerful shape laws to benefit themselves), and police targeting of working-class areas."],
    ex:{t:"Example — power and the law",b:["Laws and policing often focus on street crime.","Powerful groups may shape which acts are criminalised.","Power inequalities affect who appears in the statistics."]}},
   {art:"measure",h:"Reading these explanations carefully",p:[
    "A key sociological point runs through all three: statistics may reflect how groups are policed and judged as much as how they behave. Institutional racism, chivalry and power inequalities are all about treatment.",
    "So sociologists never take crime statistics at face value \u2014 they ask who is being watched, stopped and recorded, and why."],
    ex:{t:"Example — behind the numbers",b:["Two groups may offend at similar rates.","But if one is policed more heavily, it appears more in statistics.","Sociologists look behind the numbers."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose ethnicity, gender OR class. List three explanations for its crime pattern and explain how one of them is about treatment rather than behaviour.",
  check:[
   {q:"Discrimination built into institutions like the police is\u2026",o:["The chivalry thesis","Institutional racism","Rehabilitation","Meritocracy"],a:1},
   {q:"The chivalry thesis suggests women are\u2026",o:["More heavily policed","Never victims","Treated more leniently by the justice system","Always guilty"],a:2},
   {q:"The idea that the powerful shape laws to benefit themselves is\u2026",o:["The chivalry thesis","A victim survey","Power inequalities","Deterrence"],a:2},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u7",n:7,title:"Theories of Crime",mins:180,icon:"BookOpen",
  summary:"The main sociological theories of crime and deviance: postmodernism, interactionism, functionalism, Marxism and feminism.",
  keyWords:["postmodernism","interactionism","labelling","moral panic","functionalism","strain theory","Marxism","feminism"],
  sections:[
   {art:"theory",h:"Postmodernism and interactionism",p:[
    "Postmodernists argue crime today is more individualistic and unpredictable \u2014 a personal choice, with traditional definitions breaking down and media and technology shaping behaviour (for example, cybercrime and identity theft).",
    "Interactionism focuses on labelling: being labelled \u2018deviant\u2019 can lead to further deviance (a self-fulfilling prophecy). Moral panic describes media exaggeration that creates fear and stereotyping \u2014 for example, youths labelled as gang members."],
    ex:{t:"Example — moral panic",b:["Media exaggerate a youth crime story.","Public fear and stereotyping grow.","Interactionists call this a moral panic."]}},
   {art:"theory",h:"Functionalism",p:[
    "Functionalists see crime as having both positive and negative functions. Durkheim argued crime is inevitable and can reinforce social norms by reminding everyone of the rules.",
    "Merton\u2019s strain theory says crime results from a gap between society\u2019s goals and the means to achieve them. Subcultural theory says some groups form their own norms encouraging deviance; the New Right links crime to weak socialisation and declining values."],
    ex:{t:"Example — strain theory",b:["Society tells everyone to succeed and get rich.","Some people lack legal means to do so.","Merton said this strain can push them toward crime."]}},
   {art:"gap",h:"Marxism and feminism",p:[
    "Marxists see crime as a result of class conflict and capitalism: the law serves ruling-class interests, white-collar crimes are often ignored, and poverty drives much working-class crime (corporate fraud is punished less than street crime).",
    "Feminists focus on how crime and control affect men and women differently: patriarchy shapes which crimes are reported or punished, women are often victims of gendered violence, and male-dominated institutions may downplay female victimisation (domestic abuse is often underreported)."],
    ex:{t:"Example — whose crime is punished",b:["Corporate fraud can harm thousands.","Yet it is often punished less than a street theft.","Marxists say the law reflects ruling-class interests."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"Strengths and limitations",p:[
    "Each theory has strengths and limits. Postmodernism explains new crimes like cybercrime but is vague on solutions. Interactionism highlights labelling and media but can downplay the harm of crime.",
    "Functionalism explains why crime exists everywhere but ignores structural causes like poverty. Marxism links crime to inequality but over-focuses on class. Feminism raises awareness of gendered crime but may understate women\u2019s offending or male victimisation."],
    ex:{t:"Example — no single answer",b:["Each theory captures part of the picture.","None explains every crime alone.","Sociologists weigh their strengths and limits together."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose two theories of crime. Explain each in your own words, then give one strength and one limitation of each.",
  check:[
   {q:"Labelling theory belongs to which approach?",o:["Functionalism","Marxism","Postmodernism","Interactionism"],a:3},
   {q:"Merton's strain theory says crime results from\u2026",o:["No poverty","A gap between goals and the means to achieve them","Too many police","Perfect equality"],a:1},
   {q:"Marxists argue the law mainly serves\u2026",o:["The poorest only","Only women","No one","Ruling-class interests"],a:3},
  ]},

 {id:"y3u8",n:8,title:"Punishment & Policing",mins:180,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"The aims of punishment, the effectiveness of different punishments, and the strengths and limits of policing strategies.",
  keyWords:["deterrence","retribution","rehabilitation","incapacitation","surveillance","community policing"],
  sections:[
   {art:"punish",h:"The aims of punishment",p:[
    "Punishment serves different aims. Protection keeps society safe from offenders. Deterrence discourages people from committing crimes. Retribution ensures the offender is punished fairly \u2014 a form of justice.",
    "Incapacitation removes offenders from society, for example through prison. Rehabilitation helps offenders change and rejoin society. Different societies emphasise different aims."],
    ex:{t:"Example — four aims in one sentence",b:["A prison sentence protects society and incapacitates the offender.","It may deter others and deliver retribution.","Ideally it also rehabilitates \u2014 several aims at once."]}},
   {art:"punish",h:"Types of punishment",p:[
    "Punishments range widely. Community sentencing means unpaid work for the community; financial penalties are fines for minor crimes; prison removes dangerous individuals; rehabilitation programmes use counselling, education and treatment.",
    "Others include capital punishment (the death penalty, used in some countries), corporal punishment (physical, widely seen as a rights abuse), exile or ostracism, electronic tagging, probation, police cautions, and even social media or vigilante shaming."],
    ex:{t:"Example — matching punishment to crime",b:["A fine may suit a minor traffic offence.","Prison may suit a serious violent crime.","Different crimes call for different punishments."]}},
   {art:"scale",h:"How effective is punishment?",p:[
    "Effectiveness varies. Community sentencing can reform but is not always taken seriously. Fines work for some but hit the poor hardest. Prison removes danger but can lead to reoffending and is costly.",
    "Rehabilitation programmes aim for long-term change. Corporal punishment is widely seen as a human-rights abuse. Online shaming can be unfair and lacks legal process. No punishment works perfectly for every case."],
    ex:{t:"Example — fines and fairness",b:["A fine is easy for a rich person to pay.","The same fine is a heavy burden for a poor person.","So fines can be effective for some but not others."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Effectiveness of policing",p:[
    "Policing strategies also vary. Targeting and stop-and-search focus on certain areas or groups \u2014 but may lead to discrimination. Surveillance (CCTV, digital tracking) helps detect crime but raises privacy concerns.",
    "Crime prevention designs out crime (better lighting, secure buildings). Community policing builds trust and cooperation. Military-style policing may reduce crime but can increase fear. The best approach balances safety with fairness."],
    ex:{t:"Example — trust versus fear",b:["Community policing builds local trust and cooperation.","Heavy military-style policing may cut crime but raise fear.","Effectiveness means balancing safety with fairness."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List the five aims of punishment. Then choose one type of punishment and one policing strategy, and explain one strength and one limitation of each.",
  check:[
   {q:"Punishment that removes offenders from society is\u2026",o:["Incapacitation","Rehabilitation","Deterrence","Retribution"],a:0},
   {q:"Helping offenders change and rejoin society is\u2026",o:["Exile","Retribution","Incapacitation","Rehabilitation"],a:3},
   {q:"A limitation of stop-and-search is that it\u2026",o:["May lead to discrimination","Builds total trust","Is always fair","Removes all crime"],a:0},
  ]},
];
