// === Soft Skills for Students (25-week course) ===
const SOFT_UNITS=[
 {id:"ss1",n:1,title:"Understanding Soft Skills",mins:150,icon:"Sparkles",
  summary:"What soft skills are, how they differ from hard skills, why employers value them so highly, and how a growth mindset lets anyone build them.",
  keyWords:["soft skills","hard skills","employability","growth mindset","the future of work"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Julia Rozovsky",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2012\u20132016 \u00b7 Mountain View, California, USA \u00b7 Julia Rozovsky and the Google Team",
    "A few years ago, a big company called Google wanted to build the perfect team. They started a special project called Project Aristotle, led by a researcher named Julia Rozovsky. Google had always hired the \"smartest\" people in the world. These were students who got perfect A+ grades, won coding contests, and knew how to build amazing computer programs. Google thought that putting these super-smart people together would make the best team ever. But when the project finished, the scientists discovered something that surprised everyone! The most successful teams weren't the ones with the highest grades or the best computer skills. Instead, the winning teams were the ones who were kind to each other. They listened to everyone\u2019s ideas, smiled, and didn't make fun of anyone who made a mistake. Google proved that having a growth mindset and learning how to get along with others is much more important than just being the smartest person in the room!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Grades can open a door; soft skills keep you in the room.","Employers worldwide say graduates struggle for lack of soft skills, not knowledge.","Your attitude is often more valuable than your aptitude.","This course builds the \u2018how to work with people\u2019 that exams never test."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"What are soft skills?",p:[
    "Soft skills are the personal and people skills that shape how you work and relate to others: communicating, listening, teamwork, managing your time and emotions, solving problems and leading. They are sometimes called \u2018human skills\u2019 or \u2018life skills\u2019.",
    "Unlike a fact you either know or don\u2019t, soft skills are shown through behaviour \u2014 how you act in a group, under pressure, or when things go wrong. That is why they must be practised, not just read about."],
    ex:{t:"Everyday soft skills",b:["Explaining an idea so a friend instantly understands it.","Staying calm and fair when a teammate lets you down.","Managing your week so nothing is left to the last night.","Encouraging a quiet classmate to share their idea."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Hard skills vs soft skills",p:[
    "Hard skills are specific, teachable abilities you can measure \u2014 solving equations, coding, speaking French, using a spreadsheet. Soft skills are how you apply those abilities alongside other people.",
    "You need both. Hard skills may get you the interview or the task; soft skills decide how well you actually do it with, and for, other people. A brilliant coder who cannot listen or explain will struggle on any real team."],
    ex:{t:"Two sides of one worker",b:["Hard skill: can build a website.","Soft skill: can understand what the client actually needs.","Hard skill: knows the biology.","Soft skill: can teach it clearly to a nervous classmate."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Why soft skills matter and the future of work",p:[
    "As technology and even AI take over more routine, technical tasks, the human skills machines cannot copy \u2014 empathy, creativity, judgement, leadership \u2014 become more valuable, not less. Employers consistently rank communication, teamwork and problem-solving among the skills they most want.",
    "The world of work is also changing fast: people switch roles and fields more than past generations did. Soft skills travel with you across every job, because they are about you, not one task."],
    ex:{t:"Skills employers ask for most",b:["Communication and teamwork.","Problem-solving and critical thinking.","Adaptability and a positive attitude.","Leadership and reliability."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"A growth mindset: soft skills can be learned",p:[
    "No one is born a great communicator or leader. These skills grow with effort and practice, like a muscle. A \u2018growth mindset\u2019 is believing your abilities can improve \u2014 which is exactly what this course is built on.",
    "The opposite, a \u2018fixed mindset\u2019, says \u2018I\u2019m just not a people person\u2019 and stops trying. Swap that for \u2018I haven\u2019t built that skill yet\u2019, and every setback becomes practice rather than proof you cannot do it."],
    ex:{t:"Fixed vs growth",b:["Fixed: \u2018I\u2019m bad at speaking.\u2019 Growth: \u2018I haven\u2019t practised speaking yet.\u2019","Fixed: avoids the hard task. Growth: runs toward it to learn.","Effort is the path to mastery, not a sign of weakness.","Every module here is a chance to practise, not just to read."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write down one hard skill and one soft skill you already have, and one soft skill from this module you most want to build over the next 25 weeks. Keep it \u2014 you\u2019ll review it at the end.",
  check:[
   {q:"Soft skills are best described as\u2026",o:["Facts you memorise","Personal and people skills shown through behaviour","The same as certificates","Only for adults"],a:1},
   {q:"Employers say graduates most often struggle because they lack\u2026",o:["Talent","Money","Soft skills, not knowledge","Certificates"],a:2},
   {q:"A growth mindset means believing\u2026",o:["Only some can learn","Effort is pointless","Your abilities can improve with effort","You are born fixed"],a:2},
  ]},
 {id:"ss2",n:2,title:"Knowing Yourself",mins:150,icon:"User",
  summary:"Self-awareness, understanding your personality and values, spotting your strengths, and setting a personal vision \u2014 the foundation all other skills rest on.",
  keyWords:["self-awareness","personality","values","strengths","personal vision"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Isabel Briggs Myers",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1957 \u00b7 Princeton, New Jersey, USA \u00b7 Isabel Briggs Myers and Mary McCaulley",
    "In 1957, a teacher and researcher named Isabel Briggs Myers noticed that a lot of university students were unhappy. Schools were teaching children facts from heavy textbooks, but no one was teaching them about themselves! Students were picking jobs blindly, like picking a toy with their eyes closed. Many grew up to be sad because they chose jobs that did not fit who they really were. Isabel and her helper, Mary McCaulley, decided to change this. They spent years helping thousands of young students map out their own personalities. They helped them discover what they were naturally good at, what they valued most, and what their personal goals were. They discovered that when students took the time to truly know themselves, they became much happier, did better in school, and could handle tough days without giving up. It showed that before you can do big things in the world, you must first learn who you are inside!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Self-knowledge grows from reflection and observation.","Isabel Briggs Myers helped students discover who they really are.","Knowing your own values steadies you in hard times.","You cannot manage what you do not understand \u2014 starting with yourself."]}},
   {art:"interpret",h:"Self-awareness",p:[
    "Self-awareness is understanding your own emotions, strengths, weaknesses, habits and how you affect others. It is the foundation of emotional intelligence and of almost every other soft skill \u2014 you cannot improve what you cannot see.",
    "You build it by pausing to reflect: What am I feeling right now, and why? How did I come across in that meeting? Honest reflection, and asking trusted people for feedback, slowly sharpens the picture."],
    ex:{t:"Building self-awareness",b:["Notice and name your emotions as they happen.","Ask: how did I come across just then?","Invite honest feedback from people you trust.","Keep a short reflection note after key moments."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Personality, behaviour and values",p:[
    "Your personality is your typical pattern of thinking, feeling and behaving \u2014 for example, whether you recharge alone or with people, or prefer planning or spontaneity. There is no \u2018best\u2019 personality; each has strengths.",
    "Your values are what matters most to you \u2014 honesty, family, achievement, kindness, fairness. When your actions match your values you feel steady and confident; when they clash, you feel uneasy. Knowing your values helps you make hard choices well."],
    ex:{t:"Personality and values in action",b:["Introvert or extrovert \u2014 both can lead, differently.","Values act like an inner compass for decisions.","Acting against your values causes stress and regret.","Naming your top three values makes choices clearer."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Discovering your strengths",p:[
    "Everyone has strengths \u2014 things they do naturally well or with energy. Some people organise, some create, some encourage, some analyse. Building on your strengths is usually more powerful than only fixing weaknesses.",
    "Spot yours by noticing what you enjoy, what others come to you for, and what makes time fly. In teamwork, matching tasks to each person\u2019s strengths lifts the whole group \u2014 a theme you\u2019ll meet again in the teamwork module."],
    ex:{t:"Finding your strengths",b:["What do people ask for your help with?","Which tasks make time fly for you?","When do you feel most energised and capable?","Play to strengths; manage weaknesses."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Personal vision and goals",p:[
    "A personal vision is a picture of the person you want to become and the life you want to build. It gives direction, so your daily choices add up to something rather than drifting.",
    "You don\u2019t need the whole map at 15 \u2014 just a direction. From a vision you can set goals: the concrete steps that move you toward it. Later modules turn vision into SMART goals and a full success plan."],
    ex:{t:"From vision to action",b:["Vision: the kind of person you want to be.","Goals: the steps that take you there.","A direction beats drifting, even if it changes.","Your vision guides which opportunities to say yes to."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write three of your core values and two strengths others would say you have. Then write one sentence describing the kind of person you want to become.",
  check:[
   {q:"Self-awareness is\u2026",o:["Ignoring your feelings","Understanding your emotions, strengths and effect on others","Only for adults","Copying others"],a:1},
   {q:"Your values act as\u2026",o:["A fixed grade","Someone else\u2019s rules","An inner compass for decisions","A weakness"],a:2},
   {q:"Building on strengths is\u2026",o:["Usually more powerful than only fixing weaknesses","Selfish","Impossible","A waste of time"],a:0},
  ]},
 {id:"ss3",n:3,title:"Building Self-Confidence",mins:150,icon:"Flame",
  summary:"Growing healthy self-esteem, overcoming fear, handling criticism, building resilience and self-discipline \u2014 becoming your best self.",
  keyWords:["self-esteem","courage","criticism","resilience","self-discipline"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: J.K. Rowling",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1995\u20131997 \u00b7 Edinburgh, Scotland \u00b7 J.K. Rowling (Joanne Rowling)",
    "Once upon a time, a mother named Joanne Rowling sat in a small cafe, typing a story on an old machine. She was very poor, did not have a job, and was struggling to take care of her baby daughter. But she had a dream. She had written a magic story about a young wizard named Harry Potter. Joanne needed a lot of self-discipline and courage just to send her book to publishers. Sadly, twelve different book companies read it and said, \"No, thank you.\" Some even told her to stop writing because they thought children wouldn't like it. Imagine how sad that would feel! But Joanne chose to be brave and resilient. She didn't let the criticism stop her. Finally, in 1997, a small company gave her a chance. Today, millions of children around the world have read her books. Her life proves that self-confidence isn't something you are just born with\u2014it is a superpower you build by trying again and again, even when things are scary."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Confidence is acting on your beliefs, not the absence of fear.","J.K. Rowling kept going through twelve rejections.","Courage is a choice repeated, not a one-off.","Self-confidence is built by trying again, even when it is scary."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Developing positive self-esteem",p:[
    "Self-esteem is how much you value yourself. Healthy self-esteem is not thinking you are better than others \u2014 it is quietly believing you have worth and can grow, even when you fail.",
    "It grows from small kept promises to yourself, from focusing on effort and progress rather than only results, and from how you talk to yourself. Speak to yourself as you would to a good friend."],
    ex:{t:"Feeding healthy self-esteem",b:["Keep small promises to yourself \u2014 they build self-trust.","Judge effort and progress, not just outcomes.","Replace harsh self-talk with fair self-talk.","Worth is not the same as being the best."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Overcoming fear",p:[
    "Fear is normal \u2014 everyone feels it before hard or new things. The goal is not to remove fear but to act despite it. Courage is a decision, and it grows each time you make it.",
    "Shrink fear by preparing well, by starting small, and by reframing nerves as energy. The very thing you are avoiding is often the thing that would grow you most."],
    ex:{t:"Facing fear",b:["Prepare \u2014 competence lowers fear.","Start with a small version of the scary thing.","Reframe nerves as excitement and energy.","Do the thing you fear; confidence follows action."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Handling criticism",p:[
    "Criticism stings, but it can be a free upgrade for your work \u2014 if you separate your self-worth from your output. A comment on your essay is about the essay, not about you as a person.",
    "Listen fully before defending, thank the person, then decide calmly which parts are useful. Not all criticism is fair \u2014 but even unfair criticism can show you how you are being seen."],
    ex:{t:"Turning critique into fuel",b:["Separate your worth from your work.","Listen fully before reacting.","Thank them, then choose what to apply.","Even unfair feedback shows how you come across."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Resilience, self-discipline and becoming your best self",p:[
    "Resilience is bouncing back from setbacks; self-discipline is doing what matters even when you don\u2019t feel like it. Together they turn confidence from a mood into a habit.",
    "Build resilience by treating failure as data, not identity, and self-discipline by making good actions small and routine. Confidence, in the end, is the quiet result of repeatedly keeping faith with yourself."],
    ex:{t:"Confidence as a habit",b:["Resilience: setbacks are data, not identity.","Self-discipline: act on your goals, not just your moods.","Small daily wins compound into steady confidence.","Become your best self one kept promise at a time."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Recall one thing you are afraid to try (speaking up, joining a club, a hard subject). Write the smallest first step you could take this week to face it.",
  check:[
   {q:"Confidence, as J.K. Rowling shows, is\u2026",o:["Being the loudest","Built by trying again despite rejection and fear","Avoiding all risk","Never feeling afraid"],a:1},
   {q:"Healthy self-esteem means\u2026",o:["Never failing","Believing you have worth and can grow","Thinking you\u2019re better than everyone","Ignoring others"],a:1},
   {q:"The best way to handle useful criticism is to\u2026",o:["Reject it all","Separate your worth from your work and apply what helps","Take it as a personal attack","Never ask for it"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss4",n:4,title:"Effective Communication",mins:150,icon:"MessageSquare",
  summary:"Speaking clearly, non-verbal and written communication, digital etiquette, and professional communication that builds your reputation.",
  keyWords:["verbal","non-verbal","written","digital etiquette","clarity"],
  sections:[
   {art:"talk",h:"A true story: Gene Kranz",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1970 \u00b7 Houston, Texas, USA (NASA Mission Control) \u00b7 Gene Kranz, John Aaron, and the Apollo 13 Astronauts",
    "In April 1970, three brave astronauts were flying high in space on a ship called Apollo 13. Suddenly, a loud BANG shook the rocket. An oxygen tank had exploded! The ship was losing electricity and clean air, and the astronauts were freezing. Their lives depended entirely on how they talked to the clever team back on Earth at NASA Mission Control. The boss on Earth, Gene Kranz, told everyone to stay calm and use very clear and simple words. In space, there was no time for messy chating or guessing games. A space expert named John Aaron figured out a secret puzzle to save the ship. He had to tell the astronauts exactly which butions to press over a very noisy radio. Because the team used perfect, clear words and checked everything they wrote down, the astronauts followed the rules perfectly and landed safely in the ocean. This true space adventure shows that good communication can literally save lives!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Simple, vivid language moves people more than jargon.","Repetition and a clear picture make a message stick.","Conviction is heard, not just words.","Clarity is power."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Verbal articulation",p:[
    "Speaking clearly is not about big words; it is about making ideas easy to understand. A useful rule: explain your point as if to a smart 12-year-old \u2014 swap jargon for everyday analogies.",
    "How you say it matters too. Slow down; fast talking signals nerves. Use a short, deliberate pause before and after a key point to give it weight, and vary your pitch so you never drone in a monotone."],
    ex:{t:"Speaking with clarity",b:["Explain it as if to a smart 12-year-old.","Slow down; pauses give your words weight.","Vary pitch \u2014 up for excitement, down for seriousness.","Trade jargon for everyday analogies."]}},
   {art:"listen",h:"Non-verbal communication",p:[
    "Much of a message is carried without words \u2014 by face, posture, gesture and tone. Crossed arms can signal defensiveness; fidgeting, stress; a slight lean forward, engagement. Your own body speaks before you do.",
    "Match your body to your message: open posture, steady but natural eye contact (around 60% of the time), and occasional nods that show you\u2019re engaged. When words and body disagree, people believe the body."],
    ex:{t:"Reading and using the body",b:["Crossed arms \u2192 possible defensiveness.","Forward lean \u2192 engagement.","Aim for eye contact about 60% of the time.","When words and body clash, the body wins."]}},
   {art:"write",h:"Written and digital etiquette",p:[
    "In a digital world your writing is your reputation. Keep outreach concise: a simple pattern is purpose in sentence one, context in sentence two, and a clear request in sentence three. Use specific, searchable subject lines \u2014 \u2018Group 4 project: question on slide 5\u2019, not just \u2018Question\u2019.",
    "Match the channel to the message: quick chat apps for fast updates, email for formal requests and official records. Never send long walls of text on instant messaging."],
    ex:{t:"Writing that earns trust",b:["Emails: purpose, context, clear request \u2014 kept short.","Subject lines: specific and searchable.","Chat apps for quick updates; email for formal records.","Polite, clear writing builds fast credibility."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Professional communication",p:[
    "Professional communication means being clear, respectful and reliable in how you speak and write with teachers, teammates and, one day, colleagues. It is courtesy plus clarity.",
    "Small habits build a strong reputation: reply promptly, keep promises about what you\u2019ll send and when, admit mistakes plainly, and adapt your tone to your audience. People trust those who communicate well."],
    ex:{t:"Professional habits",b:["Reply promptly and keep your word on deadlines.","Admit mistakes clearly, without drama.","Adapt tone to the audience and setting.","Reliability in communication builds reputation."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Take an idea from a subject you enjoy and write two versions of one explanation: one full of jargon, one for a smart 12-year-old. Notice which is clearer.",
  check:[
   {q:"Clear speaking mainly means\u2026",o:["Using jargon","Speaking in monotone","Making ideas easy to understand, not using big words","Talking fast"],a:2},
   {q:"When words and body language disagree, people tend to believe\u2026",o:["Whoever is louder","Neither","The body language","The words"],a:2},
   {q:"A good rule for emails is\u2026",o:["Written like a chat message","No subject line","Purpose, context, clear request \u2014 kept concise","As long as possible"],a:2},
  ]},
 {id:"ss5",n:5,title:"Active Listening",mins:150,icon:"Ear",
  summary:"The difference between hearing and listening, empathy, asking better questions, and giving and receiving feedback well.",
  keyWords:["active listening","empathy","questions","feedback","understanding"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Dr. Rita Charon",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1991 \u00b7 New York City, New York, USA \u00b7 Dr. Rita Charon",
    "In 1991, a kind doctor named Dr. Rita Charon noticed a big problem with new medical students. They were amazing at reading charts and using medical tools, but they were terrible at listening to the people who were sick! In fact, the data showed that doctors would interrupt a patient after just 18 seconds of speaking. Because they were rushing and only \"hearing sounds\" instead of truly listening, they were missing important clues about how to help. Dr. Rita decided to teach them a new skill called \"Narrative Medicine.\" She told the students to put down their pens, look at the patients, and practice empathy\u2014which means trying to feel what the other person is feeling. The students learned to ask friendly questions and listen to the whole story without interrupting. Amazingly, the students started making fewer mistakes, and the patients felt much happier and safer. Dr. Rita proved that listening with your heart is the fastest way to build trust!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Understanding people is the root of leading them.","Listening to opponents is a strength, not a weakness.","Gandhi listened for years before he led.","To influence people, first truly hear them."]}},
   {art:"listen",h:"Listening vs hearing",p:[
    "Hearing is passive \u2014 sound reaches your ears. Listening is active \u2014 you focus, understand and remember. Most people listen only to reply, planning their answer while the other person is still speaking. Active listening turns hearing into a tool for real collaboration.",
    "A simple technique is to \u2018loop back\u2019: before adding your view, summarise theirs \u2014 \u2018So what you\u2019re saying is X, and we need to solve Y \u2014 is that right?\u2019 It proves you understood and prevents misunderstandings."],
    ex:{t:"Listening actively",b:["Listen to understand, not just to reply.","Loop back: summarise their point before adding yours.","Put your own answer on hold while they speak.","Give full attention \u2014 devices down."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Empathy in communication",p:[
    "Empathy is understanding and sharing another person\u2019s feelings \u2014 seeing the situation from their side. It is the heart of active listening and of every strong relationship.",
    "When a teammate is upset or late, empathy asks \u2018what might be going on for them?\u2019 before judging. You don\u2019t have to agree to understand \u2014 and people open up far more to those who try to understand them."],
    ex:{t:"Listening with empathy",b:["Ask: how might this look from their side?","Understanding is not the same as agreeing.","Assume a reason before assuming the worst.","People open up to those who try to understand."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Asking better questions",p:[
    "Good questions unlock understanding. Open questions \u2014 starting with what, how or why \u2014 invite people to explain, while closed questions get only yes or no. \u2018Help me understand how you reached that\u2019 opens a conversation; \u2018Are you sure?\u2019 closes it.",
    "Curious, genuine questions show respect and gather the information you need before deciding. Asking well is as important as speaking well."],
    ex:{t:"Questions that open people up",b:["Open (what/how/why) invites explanation.","\u2018Help me understand\u2026\u2019 lowers defensiveness.","Ask before you assume or judge.","Curiosity signals respect."]}},
   {art:"mark",h:"Giving and receiving feedback",p:[
    "Giving good feedback means being specific, kind and focused on the work, not the person: praise clearly, and frame improvements as \u2018next time, try\u2026\u2019. Receiving feedback well means listening without defending, thanking the giver, and choosing what to apply.",
    "A healthy team runs on honest, respectful feedback flowing both ways. It is how good work becomes great work."],
    ex:{t:"Feedback both ways",b:["Give: specific, kind, about the work not the person.","Receive: listen, thank, then choose what to use.","Praise publicly; correct privately and gently.","Feedback is how good work becomes great."]}},
  ],
  activity:"In your next real conversation, try the \u2018loop back\u2019 technique once: summarise the other person\u2019s point before giving yours. Note how they react.",
  check:[
   {q:"The difference between hearing and listening is that listening is\u2026",o:["Louder","Faster","Active \u2014 focusing to understand and remember","Passive"],a:2},
   {q:"The \u2018loop back\u2019 technique means\u2026",o:["Repeating yourself","Ignoring them","Interrupting","Summarising their point before adding yours"],a:3},
   {q:"Empathy means\u2026",o:["Giving advice","Understanding another\u2019s feelings, even without agreeing","Feeling sorry","Always agreeing"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss6",n:6,title:"Presentation Skills",mins:150,icon:"Presentation",
  summary:"Preparing and delivering presentations: hooks, storytelling, minimalist slides, managing stage fright and speaking with confidence.",
  keyWords:["presentation","hook","storytelling","slides","stage fright"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Sir Ken Robinson",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2006 \u00b7 Monterey, California, USA \u00b7 Sir Ken Robinson",
    "In 2006, a friendly speaker named Sir Ken Robinson walked onto a big stage at a famous meeting called a TED Conference. He had to give a speech about schools and creativity to a room full of important adults. He didn't use a giant screen with lots of boring words or complicated pictures. He just stood on the stage by himself. Even though he felt nervous before starting, Ken knew how to share an amazing story. Instead of giving a dry, boring school lecture, he used funny jokes, smiled a lot, and told sweet stories about real children. He spoke with lots of confidence, and the audience fell in love with his words. Today, his speech is the most-watched TED video in history, with over 75 million views! Ken showed students everywhere that great presentation skills aren't about using fancy computer slides; they are about standing tall, being proud, and sharing a story that comes straight from your heart. Now that these kid-friendly true stories are ready, how should we build the next part for Mindklass.com? We can: 1. Create funny cartoon scripts or puppets scenarios based directly on these stories. 2. Draft simple reflection questions that children can easily answer after reading. 3. Design a 5-minute interactive game or role-play for Module 4 (Clear Communication) or Module 5 (Active Listening). Let me know what we should tackle next! Here are the true, real-life stories for Parts Three, Four, and Five, written in the same simple, friendly, and easy-to-understand language for young students at Mindklass.com."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Open with a story or hook, not a spec sheet.","Slides support the speaker \u2014 they are not the speech.","Simplicity and rehearsal beat cramming everything in.","You deliver the message; the slide just points to it."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Preparing presentations",p:[
    "Great presentations are built before you speak. Know your one core message, your audience, and the three or four points that support it. Structure beats improvisation: a clear beginning, middle and end.",
    "Then rehearse \u2014 out loud, ideally to someone. Preparation is what turns nervous energy into calm command; the confident speakers you admire almost always practised more than you think."],
    ex:{t:"Preparing well",b:["Decide your single core message first.","Support it with three or four clear points.","Give it a beginning, middle and end.","Rehearse out loud \u2014 preparation calms nerves."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"The hook and storytelling",p:[
    "Never open with \u2018Hi, my name is\u2026\u2019. Open with a hook \u2014 a surprising fact, a bold question, or a short story \u2014 then introduce yourself once you have their attention. The first fifteen seconds decide whether people lean in or drift off.",
    "Stories are the strongest hook of all, because people remember stories far better than lists. Wrapping your point in a short, real story makes it stick."],
    ex:{t:"Grabbing attention",b:["Start with a stat, a question or a story.","Introduce yourself after the hook, not before.","People remember stories, not bullet lists.","Win the first fifteen seconds."]}},
   {art:"read",h:"Slides and visual aids",p:[
    "Slides should help the audience, not replace you. Keep them minimalist \u2014 a few words or one strong image per slide \u2014 so people listen to you instead of reading ahead. A crowded slide splits attention and weakens your message.",
    "Let your voice carry the detail and your slides carry the anchor. If a slide can be read like a document, it has too much on it."],
    ex:{t:"Slides that help",b:["A few words or one strong image per slide.","Your voice carries detail; the slide carries the anchor.","Crowded slides split attention.","If it reads like a document, cut it down."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Managing stage fright and speaking with confidence",p:[
    "Stage fright is normal, even for experts. When adrenaline hits, your breathing goes shallow \u2014 so before you start, take a few slow \u2018box breaths\u2019 (in for four, hold for four, out for four) to steady your heart rate.",
    "Then stand tall, make eye contact, slow down, and remember the audience wants you to succeed. Confidence on stage is a trainable skill, built by preparation and repetition \u2014 not a gift some are simply born with."],
    ex:{t:"Calm, confident delivery",b:["Box-breathe before you begin (4-4-4).","Stand tall; make steady eye contact.","Slow down \u2014 pauses read as confidence.","Public speaking is trainable, not a fixed gift."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Plan the first 30 seconds of a short talk on any topic you love. Write a hook \u2014 a surprising fact, a question, or a mini-story \u2014 and practise saying it before naming yourself.",
  check:[
   {q:"A presentation should open with\u2026",o:["A hook \u2014 a fact, question or story","\u2018Hi, my name is\u2026\u2019","An apology","A crowded slide"],a:0},
   {q:"Good slides are\u2026",o:["Full of text to read aloud","Minimalist \u2014 supporting the speaker","The whole speech","Unnecessary detail"],a:1},
   {q:"Box breathing before speaking helps by\u2026",o:["Hiding the slides","Steadying your heart rate and nerves","Replacing preparation","Making you talk faster"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss7",n:7,title:"Teamwork and Collaboration",mins:150,icon:"Users",
  summary:"Team dynamics, building trust, respecting diversity, matching roles to strengths, and collaborating well on school projects.",
  keyWords:["teamwork","trust","roles","shared ownership","collaboration"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Narongsak Osottanakorn",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2018 \u00b7 Tham Luang Cave, Chiang Rai, Thailand \u00b7 Narongsak Osottanakorn and the International Rescue Team",
    "In 2018, a youth football team and their coach became trapped deep inside a dark, flooded cave in Thailand. The water was rising fast, and it looked impossible to get them out. Narongsak Osottanakorn, the leader of the rescue, knew that no single person could solve this massive problem alone. To save the children, he had to bring together a giant team of thousands of people from all over the world. There were British cave divers, American military experts, Thai soldiers, and local farmers. Everyone had a different team role. At first, they had to build deep trust and learn how to resolve disagreements about the best plan. By respecting each other\u2019s different skills and working together seamlessly, the team pulled off a miracle and rescued every single boy safely. This true adventure proves that when people collaborate and share a goal, they can achieve the impossible."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Teams succeed by combining complementary strengths.","When one member falls, others step up.","Trust holds a team together under pressure.","Shared ownership finishes what no one could alone."]}},
   {art:"social",h:"Understanding team dynamics",p:[
    "A team is more than people sharing a task; it is people whose strengths, moods and habits interact. Good teams make those dynamics work for them \u2014 clarifying goals, sharing the load fairly, and communicating openly.",
    "Projects succeed or fail largely on how well roles match people. Random task-sharing wastes talent; deliberate teamwork multiplies it."],
    ex:{t:"How teams work",b:["A team\u2019s strengths interact \u2014 for better or worse.","Clear goals and fair loads prevent resentment.","Open communication catches problems early.","Roles matched to people multiply talent."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Building trust",p:[
    "Trust is a team\u2019s foundation, and it is built on reliability. If you promise a draft by five, deliver it by four. High reliability earns you the social credit to ask for help when you genuinely need it.",
    "Trust also grows from honesty, giving credit generously, and admitting mistakes. Teams that trust each other move faster because they don\u2019t waste energy watching their backs."],
    ex:{t:"Earning trust",b:["Be reliable \u2014 deliver early, not late.","Give credit generously; own mistakes.","Reliability builds credit to ask for help.","Trust makes a team faster."]}},
   {art:"global",h:"Respecting diversity",p:[
    "Modern teams bring together different backgrounds, cultures and working styles. Some people value direct feedback; others prefer subtle hints. Your way of working is one method, not the default standard.",
    "Respecting diversity means gathering context before judging \u2014 ask how a teammate prefers to communicate, and align expectations early. Difference, handled well, makes a team stronger and more creative."],
    ex:{t:"Working across difference",b:["Your working style is one option, not the norm.","Some value direct critique; others, subtle hints.","Ask about preferences; align early.","Diversity, handled well, boosts creativity."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Roles, shared ownership and school projects",p:[
    "At a group project\u2019s first meeting, run a quick \u2018strengths audit\u2019: have each person say what they do best \u2014 design, research, speaking, organising \u2014 and build the tasks around those strengths. Then use inclusive language: \u2018our strategy\u2019, \u2018our next step\u2019, not \u2018my idea\u2019 and \u2018your mistake\u2019.",
    "Shared ownership means everyone feels responsible for the whole result, not just their slice. That is the difference between a group and a real team."],
    ex:{t:"Great school teamwork",b:["Start with a strengths audit; match tasks to people.","Use \u2018our\u2019, not \u2018my\u2019 and \u2018your\u2019.","Everyone owns the whole result.","A team, not just a group of individuals."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Think of your next group task. Write what your own top strength contributes, and one way you could help a teammate whose strength is different from yours.",
  check:[
   {q:"Trust in a team is built mainly on\u2026",o:["Avoiding people","Being the loudest","Doing everything yourself","Reliability \u2014 keeping your word"],a:3},
   {q:"A \u2018strengths audit\u2019 at a project\u2019s start helps by\u2026",o:["Choosing a leader by force","Avoiding work","Slowing everything down","Matching tasks to what each person does best"],a:3},
   {q:"Respecting diversity means recognising your working style is\u2026",o:["The only correct way","Unimportant","Better than others","One method, not the default standard"],a:3},
  ]},
 {id:"ss8",n:8,title:"Leadership Skills",mins:150,icon:"Award",
  summary:"What makes a leader, leadership styles, leading by example, influence vs authority, decision-making and servant leadership.",
  keyWords:["leadership","influence","lead by example","decision-making","servant leadership"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Sir Ernest Shackleton",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1914\u20131916 \u00b7 Antarctica (The Freezing South Pole) \u00b7 Sir Ernest Shackleton",
    "In 1914, a brave explorer named Sir Ernest Shackleton took a crew of 27 men on a ship called the Endurance to explore the coldest place on Earth. Suddenly, giant blocks of floating ice crushed their ship into pieces. They were completely stranded in the snow with no phones, no radios, and no way to call for help. Shackleton didn't just order people around using angry authority. Instead, he practiced servant leadership by putting his men first. He gave up his own warm bed and food for those who were sick, kept everyone laughing with daily games, and always led by example. When things looked darkest, he sailed a tiny lifeboat across 800 miles of stormy ocean to find help. Because he was a true leader who cared deeply for his team, every single one of his 27 men survived and made it home alive. He showed the world that a true leader doesn't rule through power; they lead by caring for others."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Real leadership rests on character, not title.","Leading by example is more powerful than commanding.","Great leaders unite rather than divide.","Serving a cause bigger than yourself inspires others."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"What makes a leader?",p:[
    "Leadership is not a title or a position; it is influence \u2014 the ability to help a group move toward a shared goal. You can lead from any seat by taking initiative, supporting others and setting a good example.",
    "Good leaders share common traits: vision, integrity, responsibility, and genuine care for their people. These can all be learned; leaders are grown far more than they are born."],
    ex:{t:"The heart of leadership",b:["Leadership is influence, not position.","You can lead from any role.","Vision, integrity and care mark good leaders.","Leaders are grown, not just born."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Leadership styles and leading by example",p:[
    "There is no single right style. Some situations need firm direction, others need a coach who develops people, others a democratic leader who builds consensus. Good leaders read the situation and adapt.",
    "Whatever the style, the strongest tool is example. People do what they see leaders do, not just what they\u2019re told. A leader who works hard, stays calm and treats everyone with respect sets the standard for the whole group."],
    ex:{t:"Style plus example",b:["Adapt your style to the situation and people.","Direct, coaching or democratic \u2014 each has its place.","People copy what leaders do, not just say.","Set the standard by living it."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"Influence vs authority and decision-making",p:[
    "Authority is power given by a position; influence is earned through trust and respect. Among peers you rarely have authority, so you lead by influence \u2014 by showing how your plan helps everyone succeed.",
    "Leaders also have to decide, often with incomplete information. Good decision-making means gathering enough facts, weighing options, choosing, and taking responsibility \u2014 rather than freezing in search of perfect certainty."],
    ex:{t:"Leading and deciding",b:["Authority is given; influence is earned.","Among peers, lead by showing shared benefit.","Decide with enough (not perfect) information.","Own your decisions and their results."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Servant leadership",p:[
    "Servant leadership flips the usual picture: the leader\u2019s job is to serve the team \u2014 removing obstacles, developing people, and putting the group\u2019s success first. Praise the team publicly; give tough feedback privately.",
    "When people feel genuinely supported, they give their best. The most respected leaders are often those who lift others up rather than push themselves forward."],
    ex:{t:"Serving those you lead",b:["The leader serves the team, not the reverse.","Remove obstacles and develop people.","Praise publicly; correct privately.","Lift others up to earn real respect."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Identify one situation this month where you could lead without any title \u2014 in a group task, club or at home. Write how you would lead by influence and example rather than by force.",
  check:[
   {q:"Leadership is fundamentally\u2026",o:["Being the smartest","A job title","Influence toward a shared goal","Bossing people"],a:2},
   {q:"The most powerful leadership tool is\u2026",o:["Having authority","Giving orders","Leading by example","Talking most"],a:2},
   {q:"Servant leadership means the leader\u2019s job is to\u2026",o:["Be served by the team","Serve and develop the team","Take all the credit","Avoid decisions"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss9",n:9,title:"Networking and Relationship Building",mins:150,icon:"Share2",
  summary:"Building healthy relationships, professional networking, personal branding, mentorship and keeping connections warm over time.",
  keyWords:["relationships","networking","personal brand","mentorship","social capital"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Mark Zuckerberg",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2004 \u00b7 Cambridge, Massachusetis, USA \u00b7 Mark Zuckerberg and Dustin Moskovitz",
    "In 2004, a university student named Mark Zuckerberg had a simple idea. He wanted to create a digital directory so students at his school could find each other, share hobbies, and stay in touch. He built a basic website called \"The Facebook\" from his small dorm room. Mark quickly realized that his coding skills weren't enough to make the idea grow. He needed to build a network of strong relationships. He teamed up with his roommate, Dustin Moskovitz, and other close friends who could help. By talking to other students, finding mentors who knew how to run businesses, and keeping his promises, Mark built what became a giant social network. This story shows that your ideas only grow when you share them with others and build a community of friends and mentors who support your journey."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Few succeed entirely alone; mentors open doors.","Networking is mutual support, not using people.","Those who are helped can become helpers.","Relationships are built over years, not moments."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Building healthy relationships",p:[
    "Every network is built on genuine relationships, and those rest on respect, honesty and give-and-take. Healthy relationships are not transactions; they are built by showing real interest in others and being dependable over time.",
    "The same skills you\u2019ve met already \u2014 listening, empathy, reliability \u2014 are what make people want to know you. Be the kind of person others are glad to have in their corner."],
    ex:{t:"Strong relationships",b:["Built on respect, honesty and give-and-take.","Show genuine interest in others.","Be dependable over time.","Listening and empathy draw people in."]}},
   {art:"global",h:"Professional networking and the value-first approach",p:[
    "Networking is not about collecting contacts to use later; it is about building a community of mutual support. The golden rule is value-first: never open a new professional relationship by asking for a job or favour. Offer something first \u2014 share a useful article, highlight a trend, or offer to help.",
    "One simple tool is the informational interview: a short, polite message to someone whose work you admire, asking for fifteen minutes to hear about their path \u2014 not for a job. People are far more generous than beginners expect."],
    ex:{t:"Networking the right way",b:["Value-first: give before you ask.","Never open by asking for a job or favour.","Try the informational interview \u2014 ask about their path.","Build community, not a contact list to exploit."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Personal branding",p:[
    "Your personal brand is simply the reputation you build \u2014 what people reliably associate with you. It is shaped by how you behave, communicate, and show up, online and off. You already have one; the question is whether you are shaping it deliberately.",
    "For students, a strong, honest personal brand means being known as reliable, positive and capable. Keep your online presence consistent with the person you want to be known as."],
    ex:{t:"Shaping your brand",b:["Your brand is your reputation \u2014 what people associate with you.","It\u2019s shaped by behaviour, online and off.","Be known as reliable, positive and capable.","Keep your online presence true to your best self."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Mentorship and maintaining relationships",p:[
    "A mentor is someone more experienced who guides you; finding one can accelerate your growth enormously. Seek people whose path you admire, ask thoughtful questions, and act on their advice \u2014 mentors invest more in those who use their guidance.",
    "Finally, keep connections warm. A quick, genuine update every few months to past teachers, mentors and friends keeps relationships alive. Networks fade from neglect, not distance."],
    ex:{t:"Mentors and upkeep",b:["A mentor\u2019s guidance accelerates your growth.","Ask good questions and act on the advice.","Send a brief, genuine update every few months.","Networks fade from neglect, so tend them."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Identify one person whose path you admire (a teacher, older student, or professional). Draft a short, polite value-first message you could genuinely send them.",
  check:[
   {q:"The \u2018value-first\u2019 rule of networking means\u2026",o:["Ask for a job immediately","Only talk about yourself","Collect as many contacts as possible","Offer help before asking for anything"],a:3},
   {q:"Your personal brand is\u2026",o:["A logo","A fake image","The reputation people associate with you","Only for celebrities"],a:2},
   {q:"Networks mainly fade because of\u2026",o:["Neglect","Distance","Honesty","Too many people"],a:0},
  ]},
 {id:"ss10",n:10,title:"Critical Thinking",mins:150,icon:"Search",
  summary:"Logical and analytical thinking, spotting bias, evaluating information and evidence, and making evidence-based decisions.",
  keyWords:["critical thinking","logic","bias","evidence","evaluation"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Abraham Wald",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1943 \u00b7 London, England, UK \u00b7 Abraham Wald",
    "During World War II in 1943, a clever mathematician named Abraham Wald was asked to solve a big puzzle. Many airplanes were being shot down, and the military wanted to add heavy armor to protect them. The officers looked at the planes that returned from battle and saw bullet holes all over the wings and the tail. The officers said, \"Let's put armor exactly where the holes are!\" Abraham used logical and analytical thinking. He realized the officers were showing a \"blind spot\" or bias. He asked a smart question: \"Where are the holes on the planes that did NOT make it back?\" He reasoned that the returning planes survived because they were shot in the wings. The planes that crashed were likely shot in the engines and cockpit. Abraham made an evidence-based decision and told the military to put armor on the parts of the planes that had no holes. He was exactly right, and his critical thinking saved thousands of lives."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Don\u2019t just follow the crowd \u2014 think.","Connect what you see to what you know.","Evidence plus reasoning beats assumption.","Clear thinking can save the day."]}},
   {art:"interpret",h:"Logical and analytical thinking",p:[
    "Critical thinking means actively questioning information instead of accepting it at face value. Logical thinking follows reasons to sound conclusions; analytical thinking breaks a big problem into parts you can examine.",
    "Do not believe everything you read \u2014 or even everything you first think. Ask what the claim actually is, what supports it, and whether the conclusion really follows."],
    ex:{t:"Thinking it through",b:["Question claims instead of accepting them.","Logic: do the reasons lead to the conclusion?","Analysis: break the problem into parts.","Challenge your own first thoughts too."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Identifying bias and evaluating information",p:[
    "Bias is a slant that distorts judgement \u2014 in a source, or in yourself. Strip the emotional language out of an argument and look at the underlying facts: the numbers, the sample size, and how trustworthy the source is.",
    "In a world flooded with information and misinformation, evaluating sources is a survival skill. Ask who is saying this, how they know, and whether other reliable sources agree."],
    ex:{t:"Spotting bias",b:["Remove emotive language; look at the facts.","Check numbers, sample sizes and source credibility.","Ask: who says this, and how do they know?","Cross-check important claims."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"First-principles thinking and the Five Whys",p:[
    "First-principles thinking breaks a problem down to its core truths and rebuilds a solution from there, instead of copying \u2018how it\u2019s always been done\u2019. It is how innovators find fresh answers others miss.",
    "To find a problem\u2019s real cause, use the \u2018Five Whys\u2019: ask \u2018why?\u2019 about five times in a row, each answer digging beneath the last, until you reach the root cause rather than the surface symptom."],
    ex:{t:"Digging to the root",b:["First principles: rebuild from core truths.","Don\u2019t just copy \u2018how it\u2019s always done\u2019.","Five Whys: ask \u2018why?\u2019 five times.","Fix the root cause, not the symptom."]}},
   {art:"mark",h:"Evidence-based decisions",p:[
    "An evidence-based decision rests on facts and sound reasoning rather than rumour, habit or emotion alone. It doesn\u2019t mean ignoring feelings \u2014 it means checking them against reality before you act.",
    "Gather the relevant evidence, weigh it honestly (including evidence against what you want to believe), then decide. This habit protects you from being fooled \u2014 including by yourself."],
    ex:{t:"Deciding on evidence",b:["Base decisions on facts and reasoning.","Check feelings against reality.","Weigh evidence that disagrees with you too.","Good thinking protects you from being fooled."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Take one claim you saw online recently. Write down: what is the claim, what evidence supports it, who said it, and would you now trust it? Notice what changed as you asked.",
  check:[
   {q:"Critical thinking mainly means\u2026",o:["Believing everything","Arguing for fun","Questioning information instead of accepting it","Following the crowd"],a:2},
   {q:"The \u2018Five Whys\u2019 technique helps you find\u2026",o:["Someone to blame","More problems","The root cause, not just the symptom","The fastest answer"],a:2},
   {q:"To spot bias, you should\u2026",o:["Read only one source","Go with your gut","Trust confident people","Strip emotive language and check the facts and source"],a:3},
  ]},
 {id:"ss11",n:11,title:"Creative Thinking",mins:150,icon:"Lightbulb",
  summary:"Creativity and innovation, brainstorming, design thinking and practical tools for thinking outside the box.",
  keyWords:["creativity","innovation","brainstorming","design thinking","SCAMPER"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Art Fry",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1974 \u00b7 St. Paul, Minnesota, USA \u00b7 Art Fry",
    "In 1974, a scientist named Art Fry had a frustrating problem. Every Sunday, he sang in his church choir. He used scraps of paper to mark the songs in his hymnbook, but every time he opened the book, the papers would slide out and fall to the floor. He kept wishing for a bookmark that would stick to the page but wouldn't tear the paper when he pulled it off. Art remembered that a fellow scientist at his company, 3M, had accidentally invented a weird glue years before that was incredibly weak. Most people thought the weak glue was a complete failure. But Art used creative thinking to connect two unrelated things. He painted the weak glue onto the back of yellow paper notes. By thinking outside the box, he turned a \"failed\" glue into the world's very first Post-it Note! His creativity proved that sometimes an innovation is just a mistake looked at from a fresh, fun angle."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Turn a frustration into something you create.","You don\u2019t need to be older to innovate.","Creativity is building, not just wishing.","Tools let young ideas reach the world."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"Creativity and innovation",p:[
    "Creativity is generating new, useful ideas; innovation is turning those ideas into something real. Both are deliberate processes, not random lightning bolts \u2014 and both can be practised and improved.",
    "Everyone is creative in some way. The barrier is usually fear of looking silly, or judging ideas too soon. Creative people simply give themselves permission to try odd ideas and see what works."],
    ex:{t:"Creativity as a process",b:["Creativity: new, useful ideas.","Innovation: making ideas real.","Both are practised, not magic.","Give yourself permission to try."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Brainstorming: create first, judge later",p:[
    "The biggest killer of ideas is judging them the moment they appear. Separate the two jobs: spend a set time (say twenty minutes) writing down every idea, however wild, without any criticism \u2014 then switch roles and filter them afterwards.",
    "Quantity leads to quality: the more ideas you generate freely, the more likely a great one is hiding among them. Wild ideas often spark practical ones."],
    ex:{t:"Better brainstorming",b:["Separate creating from judging.","Write every idea first \u2014 no criticism yet.","Filter and refine only afterwards.","Quantity of ideas leads to quality."]}},
   {art:"build",h:"Tools: SCAMPER and forced connections",p:[
    "You can prompt creativity with tools. SCAMPER improves an existing idea by asking: can I Substitute, Combine, Adapt, Modify, Put it to another use, Eliminate, or Reverse something? Each prompt jolts your brain onto a new track.",
    "\u2018Forced connections\u2019 links your problem to an unrelated field \u2014 \u2018how would a chef solve this coding bug?\u2019 \u2014 forcing fresh patterns. Odd questions break predictable thinking."],
    ex:{t:"Creativity tools",b:["SCAMPER: Substitute, Combine, Adapt, Modify, Put to use, Eliminate, Reverse.","Improve an existing idea, prompt by prompt.","Forced connections: link to an unrelated field.","Odd questions break predictable patterns."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Design thinking and thinking outside the box",p:[
    "Design thinking is a creative problem-solving approach that starts with deeply understanding the people you\u2019re solving for, then rapidly builds rough prototypes to test and improve. It pairs empathy with experimentation.",
    "\u2018Thinking outside the box\u2019 simply means questioning the invisible assumptions everyone else accepts. Ask \u2018who says it must be done this way?\u2019 \u2014 and you open room for something new."],
    ex:{t:"Designing solutions",b:["Start by understanding the people you\u2019re solving for.","Build rough prototypes; test and improve.","Question assumptions everyone accepts.","Empathy plus experimentation sparks new ideas."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick a small everyday annoyance. Use three SCAMPER prompts on it (e.g. Combine, Eliminate, Reverse) and write the most interesting new idea each one produces.",
  check:[
   {q:"The key rule of good brainstorming is to\u2026",o:["Judge each idea instantly","Separate creating ideas from judging them","Only keep safe ideas","Stop at one idea"],a:1},
   {q:"SCAMPER is a tool for\u2026",o:["Avoiding creativity","Grading tests","Improving an existing idea with prompts","Deleting ideas"],a:2},
   {q:"Design thinking starts with\u2026",o:["Understanding the people you\u2019re solving for","Judging ideas","Copying others","Building the final product"],a:0},
  ]},
 {id:"ss12",n:12,title:"Problem Solving",mins:150,icon:"Puzzle",
  summary:"Identifying problems, root-cause analysis, weighing alternatives, deciding and implementing solutions that last.",
  keyWords:["problem solving","root cause","alternatives","decision","implementation"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Taiichi Ohno",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1950s \u00b7 Toyota City, Japan \u00b7 Taiichi Ohno",
    "In the 1950s, a brilliant engineer named Taiichi Ohno wanted to make sure the cars built at the Toyota factory were perfect. Whenever a machine broke down or a mistake happened on the assembly line, the workers would quickly fix it and move on. But Taiichi noticed that the exact same problems kept happening over and over again, wasting lots of time. To solve this, he created a famous problem-solving tool called \"The 5 Whys.\" He taught his workers to do a root cause analysis by asking \"Why?\" five times whenever something went wrong. For example: Why did the machine stop? Because it overloaded. Why did it overload? Because the gear wasn't oiled. By digging deep instead of just fixing the surface mistake, the team found the real problem and stopped it from ever happening again. Taiichi proved that true problem-solving means fixing the root of the issue, not just covering up the scratch."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Ask why \u2014 find the root cause, not the symptom.","A simple solution, applied widely, can transform a nation.","Start small; scale what works.","Fixing causes lasts; fixing symptoms doesn\u2019t."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Identifying the real problem",p:[
    "Half of problem-solving is defining the problem correctly. People often rush to solutions for the wrong problem. Slow down and ask: what exactly is going wrong, for whom, and how do we know?",
    "A clearly stated problem is already half-solved, because it points you at the right target. A vague problem produces vague, wasted effort."],
    ex:{t:"Defining well",b:["State exactly what is going wrong, and for whom.","Don\u2019t solve the wrong problem fast.","A clear problem points at the right target.","Definition is half the solution."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Root-cause analysis",p:[
    "Root-cause analysis digs beneath symptoms to the underlying cause \u2014 like Maathai tracing dry streams to lost trees. The \u2018Five Whys\u2019 from the critical-thinking module is a perfect tool here.",
    "Treating symptoms brings the problem back again and again; fixing the root cause makes it stay solved. Always ask what is really driving the issue."],
    ex:{t:"Getting to the cause",b:["Dig beneath symptoms to the real driver.","Use the Five Whys to drill down.","Symptom fixes return; root fixes last.","Ask what is really causing this."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Generating and evaluating alternatives",p:[
    "Rarely is there only one possible solution. Generate several options first (creative thinking helps), then evaluate them against sensible criteria: how well does each solve the root cause, what does it cost, what could go wrong?",
    "When two good ideas clash, don\u2019t just water both down into a weak compromise \u2014 look for a \u2018third way\u2019 that combines the best of both."],
    ex:{t:"Choosing well",b:["Generate several options, not one.","Judge each against clear criteria.","Consider cost and what could go wrong.","Seek a \u2018third way\u2019 that combines the best."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Deciding and implementing solutions",p:[
    "A solution only counts once it\u2019s carried out. Decide clearly, plan the steps, assign who does what by when, and then act. Many good ideas die simply because no one owned the follow-through.",
    "Afterwards, check whether it actually worked, and adjust. Problem-solving is a loop \u2014 act, review, improve \u2014 not a single guess."],
    ex:{t:"Making it real",b:["Decide, plan steps, assign owners and dates.","Ideas die without follow-through.","Check whether it actually worked.","Act, review, improve \u2014 repeat."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick a real problem in your school or study life. Write the symptom, then use the Five Whys to reach a likely root cause, and one solution aimed at that cause.",
  check:[
   {q:"A well-defined problem is valuable because it\u2026",o:["Wastes time","Guarantees failure","Hides the cause","Points you at the right target"],a:3},
   {q:"Root-cause analysis aims to\u2026",o:["Fix the underlying cause, not just symptoms","Blame someone","Delay action","Treat symptoms only"],a:0},
   {q:"When two good ideas clash, a strong move is to\u2026",o:["Find a \u2018third way\u2019 combining the best of both","Give up","Pick randomly","Water both down"],a:0},
  ]},
 {id:"ss13",n:13,title:"Time Management",mins:150,icon:"Clock",
  summary:"Planning, prioritisation, beating procrastination, managing deadlines and protecting your peak energy for what matters.",
  keyWords:["time management","prioritisation","Eisenhower Matrix","procrastination","time blocking"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Charles M. Schwab",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1918 \u00b7 Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, USA \u00b7 Charles M. Schwab and Ivy Lee",
    "In 1918, a very wealthy businessman named Charles M. Schwab was frustrated because his helpers were always running out of time. They were constantly stressed, missing deadlines, and forgeting important tasks. Charles hired a productivity teacher named Ivy Lee and said, \"Help my team plan their day better, and I will pay you whatever you want.\" Ivy gave the workers a beautifully simple rule for prioritization. He told them that at the end of every day, they must write down the six most important things they needed to do the next day, ranking them from number 1 to number 6. The next morning, they were only allowed to work on task number 1. They could not look at anything else until task 1 was 100% finished. Then they moved to task 2. By avoiding multitasking and focusing on one goal at a time, the team finished their work faster than ever before. This simple trick showed that managing your time is all about choosing your single most important step first."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Time is your scarcest resource \u2014 allocate it on purpose.","Scheduled work gets done; vague plans slip.","Focus each block on one thing.","Manage energy, not just hours."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Time management is energy management",p:[
    "Managing time is really about managing energy and attention. You have peak hours when your mind is sharpest \u2014 protect them for your hardest, most important work, and save routine tasks for low-energy times.",
    "Plan your day rather than react to it. A short plan each morning (or the night before) turns a chaotic day into a directed one."],
    ex:{t:"Working with your energy",b:["Guard your peak hours for hard work.","Do routine tasks when energy is low.","Plan the day instead of reacting.","Attention, not just hours, is the resource."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Prioritisation and the Eisenhower Matrix",p:[
    "Not all tasks matter equally. The Eisenhower Matrix sorts tasks by urgent vs important: do the urgent-and-important now; schedule the important-but-not-urgent (this is where real progress lives); delegate or minimise urgent-but-unimportant; and drop what is neither.",
    "Most people drown in \u2018urgent but unimportant\u2019 and neglect the \u2018important but not urgent\u2019 \u2014 study, health, relationships \u2014 until it becomes a crisis. Protect the important."],
    ex:{t:"Sorting what matters",b:["Urgent + important \u2192 do now.","Important, not urgent \u2192 schedule (real progress).","Urgent, not important \u2192 minimise or delegate.","Neither \u2192 drop it."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Beating procrastination",p:[
    "Procrastination is usually about the friction of starting, not laziness. The \u2018five-minute rule\u2019 beats it: commit to working on the dreaded task for just five minutes. Once you begin, momentum usually carries you onward.",
    "Break big, scary tasks into small first steps, remove distractions, and reward progress. Starting is the hardest part \u2014 so make starting tiny."],
    ex:{t:"Getting started",b:["Five-minute rule: just begin for five minutes.","The friction is in starting, not doing.","Break big tasks into tiny first steps.","Remove distractions before you start."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Time blocking and managing deadlines",p:[
    "Vague to-do lists let work expand to fill all your time. Time blocking is better: reserve specific windows in your calendar (say 90 focused minutes) for one task, and protect them from interruption.",
    "For deadlines, work backwards from the due date, build in a buffer for the unexpected, and start earlier than feels necessary. Deadlines missed are usually deadlines started too late."],
    ex:{t:"Blocking and deadlines",b:["Block specific windows for single tasks.","Protect focus time from interruption.","Work backwards from deadlines; add a buffer.","Start earlier than feels necessary."]}},
  ],
  activity:"List everything you need to do this week and sort each into one of the four Eisenhower boxes. Then block calendar time for the \u2018important but not urgent\u2019 items first.",
  check:[
   {q:"In the Eisenhower Matrix, \u2018important but not urgent\u2019 tasks should be\u2026",o:["Always ignored","Scheduled \u2014 this is where real progress lives","Done last-minute","Dropped"],a:1},
   {q:"The five-minute rule beats procrastination because\u2026",o:["The hardest part is starting, and momentum follows","Tasks take five minutes","Deadlines don\u2019t matter","It avoids the work"],a:0},
   {q:"Time blocking means\u2026",o:["Never planning","Vague to-do lists","Doing everything at once","Reserving specific windows for single tasks"],a:3},
  ]},
 {id:"ss14",n:14,title:"Productivity Skills",mins:150,icon:"TrendingUp",
  summary:"Personal organisation, building habits, focus and concentration, using digital tools well, and continuous improvement.",
  keyWords:["productivity","habits","focus","organisation","continuous improvement"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Sir Dave Brailsford",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1993 \u00b7 London, England, UK \u00b7 Sir Dave Brailsford",
    "In 1993, the British professional cycling team was in terrible shape. In nearly one hundred years of racing, they had only won a single gold medal. They were disorganized, and their concentration was low. A new coach named Sir Dave Brailsford came in to build better habits and improve their personal organization. Instead of trying to change everything overnight, Dave used a productivity trick called \"the aggregation of marginal gains.\" This simply means improving everything you do by just 1%. He helped the riders build tiny, better habits: they tested different pillows for better sleep, painted the inside of their truck white to spot hidden dust that could make them sick, and learned the cleanest way to wash their hands. By focusing on continuous improvement and making tiny 1% upgrades to their daily habits, the team went on to crush their competition, winning dozens of Olympic gold medals and proving that tiny, organized habits create giant successes. All 14 modules of true-life introductory stories are now completely tailored for young learners! To help you finalize this for mindklass.com, what should we build next? We can: 1. Create an automated quiz game with multiple-choice questions for each story. 2. Design printable \"Action Badges\" or daily checklists that children can use to track these skills at home. 3. Draft simple activity prompts for the \"Collaboration in School Projects\" section in Module 7. Let me know which asset you want to tackle next! Here are the final four true, real-life stories for Part Five and Part Six, written in the same simple, friendly, and easy-to-understand language for young students at Mindklass.com."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Systems and habits beat one-off motivation.","Tiny 1% improvements compound powerfully.","Consistency outperforms intensity.","Build habits, and results follow."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Personal organisation",p:[
    "Being organised frees your mind. When your notes, files and materials each have a place, you spend energy on the work itself, not on hunting for things. Clear your physical desk and limit open tabs so your attention isn\u2019t scattered.",
    "A simple system \u2014 one place for tasks, one for notes, tidy folders \u2014 reduces \u2018cognitive load\u2019 and lets you think clearly."],
    ex:{t:"Getting organised",b:["Give notes, files and tasks a fixed place.","Clear your desk; limit open tabs.","Reduce cognitive load so you can think.","A simple system beats a perfect one you won\u2019t use."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Building habits",p:[
    "Habits are actions repeated until they become automatic \u2014 they run without willpower. Build good ones by making them small and specific, attaching them to something you already do, and repeating them at the same time each day.",
    "Don\u2019t rely on motivation, which comes and goes. Rely on habits, which keep working on the days you don\u2019t feel like it."],
    ex:{t:"Making habits stick",b:["Start small and specific.","Attach a new habit to an existing routine.","Repeat at the same time daily.","Habits work when motivation fails."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Focus and concentration",p:[
    "Deep focus is where your best work happens, and it is under attack from constant notifications. Protect it: work in single-task blocks, silence your phone, and resist switching tasks \u2014 every switch costs you re-focusing time.",
    "Train focus like a muscle. Start with short focused stretches and build up; the ability to concentrate deeply is becoming rare, and therefore valuable."],
    ex:{t:"Protecting focus",b:["Work in single-task blocks.","Silence notifications \u2014 they shatter focus.","Task-switching costs re-focusing time.","Build focus gradually, like a muscle."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Digital tools and continuous improvement",p:[
    "Used well, digital tools \u2014 calendars, task apps, note apps \u2014 multiply your productivity; used badly, they become another distraction. Choose a few simple tools and actually use them, rather than endlessly hunting for the perfect app.",
    "Finally, adopt continuous improvement: regularly review what\u2019s working and what isn\u2019t, and adjust. Small, steady tweaks compound \u2014 just like the 1% rule."],
    ex:{t:"Tools and tuning",b:["Pick a few simple tools and use them.","Don\u2019t chase the \u2018perfect\u2019 app.","Review weekly: what worked, what didn\u2019t.","Small steady improvements compound."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Choose one tiny productivity habit (e.g. reviewing tomorrow\u2019s tasks each night for two minutes). Attach it to something you already do daily, and start it this week.",
  check:[
   {q:"The main lesson of the \u20181% better\u2019 idea is that\u2026",o:["Small consistent habits compound into big results","Only huge efforts matter","Motivation is enough","Habits don\u2019t help"],a:0},
   {q:"Focus is best protected by\u2026",o:["Working on everything at once","Leaving notifications on","Constant task-switching","Single-tasking and silencing notifications"],a:3},
   {q:"You should build a new habit by\u2026",o:["Making it huge immediately","Doing it randomly","Making it small and attaching it to an existing routine","Relying on motivation"],a:2},
  ]},
 {id:"ss15",n:15,title:"Adaptability and Resilience",mins:150,icon:"RefreshCw",
  summary:"Managing change, coping with failure, handling stress, learning agility and building mental toughness.",
  keyWords:["adaptability","resilience","failure","stress","mental toughness"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Alika McCormick",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2020 \u00b7 London, England, UK \u00b7 Alika McCormick",
    "In March 2020, a student named Alika McCormick faced a massive change. Because of the global pandemic, her school closed down overnight. She could no longer see her friends, play sports, or learn in her normal classroom. Instead, she had to stay inside and look at a computer screen all day. At first, it was very stressful, and her grades began to slip. Alika decided to use her learning agility and build her mental toughness. Instead of giving up or crying about the situation, she adapted. She built a quiet study corner in her bedroom, made a new daily routine to manage her stress, and learned how to use online tools to study with her friends from afar. By learning how to cope with a tough situation and stay positive, Alika finished her school year with fantastic grades. Her story shows that when life changes your plans, being adaptable helps you grow stronger and win anyway!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Failure is data that guides the next attempt.","Persistence plus adjustment finds the answer.","Setbacks are part of the process, not the end.","\u2018Fail fast\u2019, learn, and try again."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"Managing change",p:[
    "Change is constant \u2014 new schools, teams, plans and technologies. The ability to pivot without panic is a superpower. Rather than resisting change, ask what it makes possible and what you can control within it.",
    "When instructions or plans are vague, treat the ambiguity as creative freedom: make your best attempt, get early feedback, and adjust. Adaptable people thrive where rigid people freeze."],
    ex:{t:"Handling change",b:["Ask what change makes possible.","Focus on what you can control.","Treat vague situations as creative freedom.","Adapt early rather than resist."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Coping with failure",p:[
    "Everyone fails; what differs is the response. When you fail a test or a project, allow yourself a short time to feel disappointed \u2014 then do a \u2018failure post-mortem\u2019: write down three specific, concrete things you\u2019ll do differently next time.",
    "Separate the failure from your identity. \u2018I failed this\u2019 is a fact; \u2018I am a failure\u2019 is a false story. Failure is an event, not a person."],
    ex:{t:"Bouncing back",b:["Feel it briefly, then analyse it.","Write three concrete changes for next time.","\u2018I failed this\u2019 \u2260 \u2018I am a failure\u2019.","Failure is an event, not your identity."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Stress management and well-being",p:[
    "Some stress is normal and even useful, but chronic stress and burnout harm your health and work. Watch for warning flags: constant exhaustion, growing cynicism, and a drop in the quality of your work.",
    "Manage stress with basics that genuinely work: sleep, movement, talking to someone, and disconnecting from screens before bed. Learn to say a polite \u2018no\u2019 when your plate is genuinely full."],
    ex:{t:"Managing stress",b:["Burnout flags: exhaustion, cynicism, dropping quality.","Sleep, movement and connection genuinely help.","Disconnect from screens before bed.","A polite \u2018no\u2019 protects your priorities."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Learning agility and mental toughness",p:[
    "Learning agility is the willingness and ability to learn new things quickly and keep adapting \u2014 increasingly the most valuable skill of all, because knowledge dates fast. Stay curious and treat every setback as a lesson.",
    "Mental toughness is staying steady and committed under pressure. It grows, like a muscle, each time you push through discomfort toward something worthwhile."],
    ex:{t:"Growing tougher and quicker",b:["Learning agility: learn fast, keep adapting.","Stay curious; treat setbacks as lessons.","Mental toughness grows through challenge.","Steadiness under pressure is trainable."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Think of a recent setback. Write a short \u2018failure post-mortem\u2019: what happened, and three specific things you will do differently next time.",
  check:[
   {q:"Edison\u2019s attitude to failure was that it is\u2026",o:["Shameful","Someone else\u2019s fault","Information that guides the next attempt","Proof to give up"],a:2},
   {q:"A healthy way to view a failure is\u2026",o:["Something to hide","Never your responsibility","An event, not your identity","Proof you\u2019re a failure"],a:2},
   {q:"Warning flags of burnout include\u2026",o:["Extra energy","Better focus","More motivation","Exhaustion, cynicism and dropping work quality"],a:3},
  ]},
 {id:"ss16",n:16,title:"Workplace Etiquette",mins:150,icon:"Briefcase",
  summary:"Professional conduct, workplace ethics, dress and grooming, respect, and diversity and inclusion at work.",
  keyWords:["etiquette","ethics","professional conduct","respect","inclusion"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Roberto Goizueta",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1993 \u00b7 Atlanta, Georgia, USA \u00b7 Roberto Goizueta and Carl Ware",
    "In 1993, a business leader named Roberto Goizueta, the boss of The Coca-Cola Company, noticed a big problem. Even though his company sold sweet drinks to children and adults all over the planet, the people working in his main office did not understand or respect different cultures. This lack of diversity and inclusion was causing misunderstandings, and teams were arguing instead of being nice to each other. Roberto asked a wise manager named Carl Ware to help teach everyone how to behave with proper workplace etiquetie. Carl created new rules to ensure respect in the workplace. He taught employees how to practice inclusive communication, listen to people from different backgrounds, and dress professionally to show respect for their clients. By teaching workers to value everyone's unique background, the office became a happy, welcoming place where everyone felt they belonged. This proved that being polite and respecttul to everyone is the most important rule in any job!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Integrity is doing right when no one\u2019s watching.","Character shows most when honesty costs you.","Reputation is built on small honest choices.","Trust, once earned, is your greatest asset."]}},
   {art:"roles",h:"Professional conduct",p:[
    "Professional conduct is how you carry yourself at work or school: punctual, prepared, reliable and respectful. It signals that you take your responsibilities and the people around you seriously.",
    "The basics matter more than people expect: arrive on time, meet your commitments, communicate clearly, and treat every task as worth doing well. These habits quietly build a strong reputation."],
    ex:{t:"Conducting yourself well",b:["Be punctual, prepared and reliable.","Meet commitments; communicate clearly.","Treat every task as worth doing well.","Small professional habits build reputation."]}},
   {art:"law",h:"Workplace ethics",p:[
    "Ethics are the principles of right and wrong that guide behaviour. In work and study that means honesty, fairness, keeping confidences, giving proper credit, and refusing to cut corners \u2014 even under pressure.",
    "Ethical choices sometimes cost you in the short term but build lasting trust. As the honest-driver story shows, your ethics are your reputation."],
    ex:{t:"Acting ethically",b:["Honesty, fairness and keeping confidences.","Give proper credit; don\u2019t cut corners.","Do right even under pressure.","Ethics build lasting trust."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Dress, grooming and respect",p:[
    "How you present yourself sends a message before you speak. Appropriate dress and grooming for the setting show respect for the occasion and the people in it \u2014 the goal is suitable, clean and tidy, not expensive.",
    "Respect is the core of all etiquette: greet people, use their names, listen, be polite to everyone regardless of their role, and be considerate of shared spaces and time."],
    ex:{t:"Presence and respect",b:["Dress suitably, cleanly and tidily for the setting.","Presentation speaks before you do.","Greet people; use their names; be polite to all.","Respect everyone, whatever their role."]}},
   {art:"global",h:"Diversity and inclusion at work",p:[
    "Workplaces bring together people of many backgrounds, cultures, beliefs and abilities. Inclusion means making sure everyone is respected, heard and able to contribute \u2014 and it makes teams stronger and more creative.",
    "Practise it by valuing different viewpoints, checking your assumptions, and ensuring quieter or newer colleagues are included. Treating everyone with dignity is both right and good for the work."],
    ex:{t:"Including everyone",b:["Respect different backgrounds and views.","Check your assumptions about others.","Make sure quieter voices are heard.","Inclusion strengthens teams."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Imagine you found something valuable that wasn\u2019t yours at school or work. Write what you would do and why \u2014 then note one small \u2018when no one is watching\u2019 habit you want to be known for.",
  check:[
   {q:"The honest-driver story shows that integrity is\u2026",o:["Only for special people","Unimportant at work","About looking good","Doing right even when it costs you"],a:3},
   {q:"Professional conduct rests most on\u2026",o:["Talking the most","Being punctual, reliable and respectful","Knowing the boss","Expensive clothes"],a:1},
   {q:"Inclusion at work means\u2026",o:["Everyone being identical","Ignoring differences","Ensuring everyone is respected and able to contribute","Only including friends"],a:2},
  ]},
 {id:"ss17",n:17,title:"Career Readiness",mins:150,icon:"FileText",
  summary:"Exploring careers, writing a CV, interview skills, professional email and building a positive digital presence.",
  keyWords:["career","CV","interview","professional email","digital presence"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Steve Jobs",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1998 \u00b7 Cupertino, California, USA \u00b7 Steve Jobs and Tim Cook",
    "In 1998, the tech company Apple was in big trouble and losing lots of money. The boss, Steve Jobs, needed to find a brilliant worker to fix the factories. He started looking for people with great career readiness and found a quiet manager named Tim Cook, who was working at a different computer company. Before Tim got the job, he had to prove his interview skills. When he met Steve Jobs, Tim didn't just talk about his high school grades. He spoke with absolute clarity, showed how he wrote organized professional reports, and explained exactly how he could help Apple make better computers. Steve was so impressed by Tim's professional communication and readiness that he hired him immediately. Tim Cook did such an amazing job that he later became the big boss of Apple! This true story shows that preparing your career skills early opens doors to giant opportunities."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Rejection is part of the path, not the end.","Failing means you\u2019re trying.","Persistence outlasts early \u2018no\u2019s.","Be ready with skills for when the \u2018yes\u2019 comes."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Career exploration",p:[
    "You don\u2019t need your whole career mapped out young \u2014 but you can explore. Notice what energises you, research fields, talk to people who do jobs that interest you, and try things through clubs, volunteering or small projects.",
    "Exploration reduces the risk of drifting into something by accident. Every experience, even one you dislike, teaches you something about your direction."],
    ex:{t:"Exploring directions",b:["Notice what energises you.","Research fields and talk to people in them.","Try things through clubs and volunteering.","Even a dislike teaches your direction."]}},
   {art:"write",h:"Writing a CV",p:[
    "A CV (r\u00e9sum\u00e9) is a short, honest summary of who you are, what you\u2019ve done, and what you can do \u2014 designed to earn an interview. Keep it clear, well-organised and truthful, tailored to what each opportunity wants.",
    "Focus on achievements and contributions, not just duties, and check spelling ruthlessly \u2014 a single careless error can cost you. Your CV is often your first impression."],
    ex:{t:"A strong CV",b:["Clear, organised, honest and tailored.","Show achievements, not just duties.","Check spelling ruthlessly.","It\u2019s often your first impression."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Interview skills",p:[
    "An interview is a two-way conversation where you show you\u2019re capable, prepared and pleasant to work with. Research the organisation, prepare answers to common questions, and have your own questions ready.",
    "On the day: arrive early, dress suitably, make eye contact, listen carefully, and answer with specific examples. Many interviews are won on attitude and communication as much as on qualifications \u2014 the very soft skills this course builds."],
    ex:{t:"Interviewing well",b:["Research the organisation; prepare examples.","Arrive early; dress suitably.","Listen, then answer with specifics.","Attitude and communication often decide it."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Professional email and digital presence",p:[
    "A professional email is clear, polite and purposeful, with a specific subject line and a courteous sign-off. It\u2019s a core adult skill \u2014 and getting it right marks you out early.",
    "Your digital presence \u2014 what appears when someone searches your name \u2014 is part of your reputation. Keep public profiles positive and consistent with the person you want employers to meet, and use platforms like LinkedIn to show your genuine interests and growth."],
    ex:{t:"Email and online image",b:["Emails: clear subject, polite, purposeful.","Your searchable presence is part of your reputation.","Keep public profiles positive and consistent.","Show real interests and growth online."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Draft the top three lines of your own CV as it would look today, focusing on achievements and contributions rather than just activities.",
  check:[
   {q:"Sara Blakely\u2019s story teaches that rejection is\u2026",o:["Always avoidable","Proof to quit","The end","Part of the path, a sign you\u2019re trying"],a:3},
   {q:"A CV should focus on\u2026",o:["Everything you\u2019ve ever done","Achievements and contributions, honestly","Duties only","Exaggerations"],a:1},
   {q:"Interviews are often decided by\u2026",o:["Luck only","Clothes alone","Qualifications alone","Attitude and communication as much as qualifications"],a:3},
  ]},
 {id:"ss18",n:18,title:"Entrepreneurship Skills",mins:150,icon:"Rocket",
  summary:"The entrepreneurial mindset, spotting opportunities, business communication, customer service, financial responsibility and innovation.",
  keyWords:["entrepreneurship","opportunity","customer service","risk","innovation"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Jan Koum",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2009 \u00b7 San Francisco, California, USA \u00b7 Jan Koum and Brian Acton",
    "In 2009, two friends named Jan Koum and Brian Acton wanted to solve a simple problem. They noticed that when people went to the gym or were busy in meetings, they missed important phone calls from their families. Jan thought, \"Wouldn't it be great if your phone could automatically tell your friends what you are doing right now?\" Jan and Brian used an entrepreneurial mindset to build a brand-new phone application. They didn't have a lot of money, so they had to practice strict financial responsibility and work out of small coffee shops. They focused entirely on customer service, making sure the app was completely free of annoying ads and easy for anyone to use. By spoting an opportunity and using innovation, they created WhatsApp, an app that billions of people around the world now use every single day to chat with their families. Their adventure proves that you can build a massive, world-changing business just by solving a simple daily problem for others! The entire 18-module master catalog of true stories is now completely finished and customized for your young learners! To help you lock this down for mindklass.com, what should we build next? We can: 1. Design a \"Certificate of Completion\" template that highlights these exact 18 soft skills modules. 2. Draft a quick introduction script that a teacher or video narrator can use to introduce this whole course to the students. 3. Formulate a fun classroom game for Module 18 where students get to try out their own \"Entrepreneurship Skills.\" Let me know what your next step is! Here are the true, real-life stories for Parts Seven and Eight, written in simple, friendly, and easy-to-understand language for young students at Mindklass.com ."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Spot a real need or problem to solve.","Smart risks come before rewards.","You can start young and small.","Build something people genuinely value."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"The entrepreneurial mindset",p:[
    "Entrepreneurship is not only about starting companies; it is a mindset \u2014 spotting problems as opportunities, taking initiative, and creating value. This \u2018intrapreneurial\u2019 attitude makes you valuable in any job, too.",
    "Its core traits are curiosity, initiative, comfort with smart risk, and resilience after failure \u2014 all soft skills you\u2019ve been building throughout this course."],
    ex:{t:"Thinking like a founder",b:["See problems as opportunities.","Take initiative; create value.","Get comfortable with smart risk.","Useful in any job, not just start-ups."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Opportunity identification",p:[
    "Opportunities hide inside problems and unmet needs. Entrepreneurs train themselves to notice frustrations \u2014 their own and others\u2019 \u2014 and ask \u2018could this be solved better?\u2019 Mikaila noticed bees needed help; Basil noticed games were boring.",
    "The best opportunities solve a real problem for real people. Start by listening to what frustrates people around you."],
    ex:{t:"Finding opportunities",b:["Look inside problems and frustrations.","Ask \u2018could this be done better?\u2019","Solve a real problem for real people.","Listen to what annoys those around you."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Business communication and customer service",p:[
    "Every venture runs on communication and on treating people well. Business communication means being clear, professional and persuasive \u2014 explaining your idea so others instantly see its value.",
    "Customer service is caring for the people you serve: listening to their needs, solving their problems, and treating them with respect. Happy customers return and tell others; it is often the difference between success and failure."],
    ex:{t:"Serving and persuading",b:["Explain your idea so its value is obvious.","Listen to and solve customers\u2019 problems.","Treat people with genuine respect.","Good service earns loyalty and referrals."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Financial responsibility, risk and innovation",p:[
    "Entrepreneurs take risks \u2014 but smart, calculated ones, not reckless gambles. Mikaila risked her savings, but on a product she\u2019d made appealing. Weigh the possible reward against what you could lose, and manage money responsibly.",
    "Finally, keep innovating: markets and needs change, so successful ventures keep improving and adapting. The mindset of \u2018how can this be better?\u2019 never stops."],
    ex:{t:"Smart risk and steady innovation",b:["Take calculated risks, not reckless gambles.","Weigh reward against what you could lose.","Manage money responsibly.","Keep asking \u2018how can this be better?\u2019"]}},
  ],
  activity:"Think of one problem or frustration you or your friends face. Sketch a simple idea to solve it, and note the smart, small first step you could take to test it.",
  check:[
   {q:"The entrepreneurial mindset is mainly about\u2026",o:["Working alone","Only starting big companies","Avoiding all risk","Spotting problems as opportunities and creating value"],a:3},
   {q:"Good opportunities usually come from\u2026",o:["Copying others exactly","Ignoring customers","Real problems and unmet needs","Random luck"],a:2},
   {q:"Smart entrepreneurial risk means\u2026",o:["Never risking anything","Reckless gambling","Calculated risk, weighing reward against loss","Spending all you have blindly"],a:2},
  ]},
 {id:"ss19",n:19,title:"Digital Literacy",mins:150,icon:"Wifi",
  summary:"Using digital tools, online safety and security, information literacy, social-media awareness and understanding AI as a tool.",
  keyWords:["digital literacy","online safety","misinformation","social media","AI"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: the hijacked website",p:[
    "In 2024, the official website of LEGO \u2014 a company loved by millions of children \u2014 was briefly hacked. For a short time, visitors saw a fake message promoting a bogus cryptocurrency \u2018LEGO coin\u2019, designed to trick fans into handing over money. It was quickly removed, but not before some people were fooled.",
    "The lesson is sharp: even a trusted, famous website can be compromised, and if something online promises easy riches, it is almost always a scam. Digital literacy means staying alert, even on sites you trust."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Even trusted sites can be hacked.","\u2018Easy money\u2019 online is almost always a scam.","Pause and verify before you act or pay.","Healthy suspicion protects you online."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Using digital tools",p:[
    "Digital literacy is the ability to use technology effectively, safely and responsibly. It includes everyday tools \u2014 documents, spreadsheets, presentations, communication and collaboration apps \u2014 that nearly every modern job now expects.",
    "You don\u2019t need to master everything, but being comfortable learning new tools quickly is itself a key skill. Technology keeps changing; the ability to adapt to it is what lasts."],
    ex:{t:"Tool fluency",b:["Use documents, sheets, slides and collaboration apps.","Nearly every job now expects these.","Being able to learn new tools fast matters most.","Adaptability outlasts any single app."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Online safety and security",p:[
    "Protecting yourself online is essential. Use strong, unique passwords (ideally with a password manager), be wary of links and \u2018too good to be true\u2019 offers, and never share personal details with unverified people or sites.",
    "Think before you click, download or pay. Scams rely on urgency and excitement to switch off your caution \u2014 so slow down and verify when something pushes you to act fast."],
    ex:{t:"Staying safe",b:["Strong, unique passwords for each account.","Be wary of links and \u2018too good to be true\u2019 offers.","Never share personal details with unverified sources.","Scams use urgency \u2014 so slow down."]}},
   {art:"search",h:"Information literacy and misinformation",p:[
    "The internet mixes truth with rumour and deliberate lies. Information literacy means checking before you believe or share: who published this, what\u2019s their evidence, and do other reliable sources agree?",
    "Before sharing something shocking, pause \u2014 misinformation spreads fastest through people who share in good faith without checking. Be a filter, not a megaphone, for false claims."],
    ex:{t:"Judging information",b:["Check who published it and their evidence.","Cross-check with reliable sources.","Pause before sharing shocking claims.","Be a filter, not a megaphone."]}},
   {art:"science",h:"Social media awareness and AI as a tool",p:[
    "Social media is powerful but curated \u2014 people show their highlights, not their whole lives, so comparing your reality to their edited feed is unfair to yourself. Use it intentionally, guard your time, and protect your privacy.",
    "Artificial intelligence is now a tool you\u2019ll use throughout life. Used well, AI can help you learn, draft and create; but it can be wrong, and it can\u2019t replace your own thinking, judgement or honesty. Treat it as a capable assistant you always check \u2014 never a substitute for your own mind."],
    ex:{t:"Feeds and AI",b:["Social feeds show highlights, not whole lives.","Use social media intentionally; guard privacy.","AI is a helpful assistant \u2014 but can be wrong.","Always check AI; never outsource your judgement."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Find one surprising claim on social media. Before believing it, check who posted it and whether two reliable sources agree. Write what you found.",
  check:[
   {q:"The LEGO website hack shows that\u2026",o:["Hacking is harmless","Even trusted sites can be compromised \u2014 stay alert","Crypto offers are reliable","Websites are always safe"],a:1},
   {q:"A key habit for online safety is\u2026",o:["Clicking every link","Slowing down when something urges you to act fast","Sharing passwords","Trusting \u2018easy money\u2019"],a:1},
   {q:"AI should be treated as\u2026",o:["A helpful assistant you always check","A replacement for your judgement","Never useful","Always correct"],a:0},
  ]},
 {id:"ss20",n:20,title:"Global Citizenship",mins:150,icon:"Globe",
  summary:"Cultural awareness, cross-cultural communication, understanding global issues, and valuing diversity and inclusion.",
  keyWords:["global citizenship","culture","cooperation","global issues","diversity"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Greta Thunberg",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2018 \u00b7 Stockholm, Sweden \u00b7 Greta Thunberg",
    "In 2018, a 15-year-old student named Greta Thunberg decided that she couldn't just sit around and watch the planet get hurt by pollution. She knew that global warming was a massive threat to our future. She felt a deep sense of social responsibility and wanted to show everyone the importance of environmental sustainability. Instead of waiting for grown-ups to fix everything, Greta took a piece of cardboard, painted the words \"School Strike for Climate\" on it, and sat down outside her country's parliament building. At first, she was all by herself. But because she spoke with high ethics and called for global change, millions of students from different countries and cultures joined her. Her small action turned into a worldwide movement . Greta showed children everywhere that being a global citizen means standing up for our shared home, no matter how young you are!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Even rivals can cooperate for a shared goal.","We are one human family across borders.","Common purpose can bridge deep differences.","Global problems need global cooperation."]}},
   {art:"global",h:"Cultural awareness",p:[
    "Cultural awareness is understanding that people\u2019s customs, values and ways of communicating differ across the world \u2014 and that no culture is the default \u2018normal\u2019. What is polite in one place may be rude in another.",
    "Awareness starts with curiosity and humility: learn about other cultures, ask rather than assume, and treat difference as interesting rather than wrong."],
    ex:{t:"Seeing across cultures",b:["No single culture is the default \u2018normal\u2019.","Politeness and customs vary widely.","Ask, don\u2019t assume.","Treat difference as interesting, not wrong."]}},
   {art:"talk",h:"Cross-cultural communication",p:[
    "Communicating across cultures needs extra care. Some cultures are direct, others indirect; some value formality, others informality; gestures and eye contact carry different meanings. When in doubt, be respectful, patient and clear.",
    "Avoid slang and assumptions, check that you\u2019ve understood and been understood, and give people the benefit of the doubt. Most misunderstandings across cultures are honest, not hostile."],
    ex:{t:"Communicating across cultures",b:["Direct vs indirect styles both exist.","Gestures and eye contact vary in meaning.","Avoid slang; check understanding both ways.","Assume good intent, not hostility."]}},
   {art:"planet",h:"Understanding global issues",p:[
    "Global citizens care about issues that cross borders \u2014 the environment and climate, poverty, health, human rights and education. These challenges affect everyone and often need cooperation between nations to solve.",
    "You don\u2019t have to fix the world alone, but understanding these issues \u2014 and how your choices connect to them \u2014 is part of being a responsible member of a shared planet."],
    ex:{t:"Caring beyond borders",b:["Climate, poverty, health and rights cross borders.","Global problems need cooperation to solve.","Your choices connect to the wider world.","Awareness is the start of responsibility."]}},
   {art:"social",h:"Valuing diversity and inclusion",p:[
    "A global outlook treasures diversity \u2014 of people, cultures and ideas \u2014 as a source of strength and creativity, not a threat. Inclusion means actively making sure everyone, whatever their background, is respected and able to take part.",
    "Practising this at school and online \u2014 welcoming those who are different, standing against prejudice \u2014 prepares you to thrive in an interconnected world and makes every community you join better."],
    ex:{t:"Diversity as strength",b:["Diversity is a source of strength and creativity.","Inclusion means everyone can take part.","Welcome difference; stand against prejudice.","It prepares you for an interconnected world."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Pick one global issue you care about. Write two sentences on why it matters and one small action you could take in your own community.",
  check:[
   {q:"The \u2018handshake in space\u2019 shows that\u2026",o:["Space is dangerous","Rivalry always wins","Nations can never cooperate","Even rivals can cooperate for a shared goal"],a:3},
   {q:"Cultural awareness begins with recognising that\u2026",o:["Difference is wrong","No culture is the default \u2018normal\u2019","Your culture is best","Everyone is the same"],a:1},
   {q:"A global citizen views diversity as\u2026",o:["Something to ignore","A source of strength and creativity","A weakness","A threat"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss21",n:21,title:"Financial Literacy",mins:150,icon:"DollarSign",
  summary:"Money basics, budgeting and saving, needs vs wants, avoiding debt traps, and an introduction to investing and financial goals.",
  keyWords:["financial literacy","budgeting","saving","needs vs wants","compound interest"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Warren Buffett",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1999 \u00b7 Omaha, Nebraska, USA \u00b7 Warren Buffett",
    "In 1999, one of the richest men in the world, Warren Buffett, visited a classroom of young students. Warren is famous for knowing how to grow money. The children expected him to talk about complex math equations or hidden stock market secrets. Instead, he told them a story about his very first job when he was just six years old. Warren explained that he bought a six-pack of Coca-Cola bottles for 25 cents and sold each bottle to his neighbors for 5 cents, making a tiny profit. He used that story to teach the children the basics of money management and responsible spending. He told them, \"Do not save what is left after spending; spend what is left after saving.\" By teaching them how to make a budget, save early, and understand investing basics, Warren proved that being smart with money isn't about how much you make\u2014it\u2019s about the habits you build while you are young!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Good money habits can start young.","Saving early lets time grow your money.","Understanding money matters more than earning a lot.","Time is the young person\u2019s biggest advantage."]}},
   {art:"chart",h:"Money basics",p:[
    "Financial literacy is understanding how money works: earning, spending, saving, borrowing and giving. It is a life skill schools often skip, yet it shapes your stress, freedom and choices for decades.",
    "The foundation is simple: spend less than you earn, save the difference, and understand any money you borrow. Master these basics and you avoid most money trouble."],
    ex:{t:"The foundations",b:["Understand earning, spending, saving, borrowing.","Spend less than you earn.","Save the difference.","Understand any money you borrow."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Needs vs wants and budgeting",p:[
    "A need is something you must have (food, shelter, basic transport); a want is something nice to have. Confusing the two is how money disappears. Before spending, honestly ask: is this a need or a want?",
    "A budget is simply a plan for your money \u2014 deciding where it goes before it goes. Even a simple budget (some to spend, some to save, some to give) puts you in control instead of wondering where it all went."],
    ex:{t:"Planning your money",b:["Need = must have; want = nice to have.","Ask before spending: which is this?","A budget plans money before it\u2019s spent.","Spend / save / give \u2014 you\u2019re in control."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Saving and avoiding debt traps",p:[
    "Saving means keeping some money for the future instead of spending it all now \u2014 for goals, and for emergencies so a surprise doesn\u2019t become a disaster. A habit of \u2018pay yourself first\u2019 (saving a little before spending) builds security.",
    "Some debt (like borrowing to learn or build) can help, but \u2018bad debt\u2019 \u2014 borrowing for wants at high interest \u2014 traps people. Beware anything offering easy credit or promising quick riches; if it sounds too good to be true, it is."],
    ex:{t:"Saving and safe borrowing",b:["Save for goals and for emergencies.","\u2018Pay yourself first\u2019 before spending.","Avoid high-interest debt for wants.","\u2018Too good to be true\u2019 = a trap."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Introduction to investing and financial goals",p:[
    "Investing means putting money to work so it can grow over time \u2014 the idea behind Buffett\u2019s early start. Thanks to compound growth (returns earning their own returns), starting small but early can beat starting big but late.",
    "You don\u2019t need to invest as a student, but you should set financial goals \u2014 what you\u2019re saving toward and by when \u2014 and understand that patient, informed, long-term habits build wealth, while get-rich-quick schemes usually destroy it."],
    ex:{t:"Growing money wisely",b:["Investing puts money to work over time.","Compound growth rewards starting early.","Set clear savings goals with timeframes.","Patience builds wealth; \u2018quick riches\u2019 destroy it."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Track everything you spend for the next three days, then label each item \u2018need\u2019 or \u2018want\u2019. Note one want you could cut and save instead.",
  check:[
   {q:"Buffett\u2019s early start shows the power of\u2026",o:["Ignoring money","Spending fast","Getting rich quick","Saving early and letting time grow money"],a:3},
   {q:"A budget is\u2026",o:["A type of debt","A plan for your money before it\u2019s spent","Only for adults","A way to spend more"],a:1},
   {q:"\u2018Too good to be true\u2019 money offers are usually\u2026",o:["Free money","Traps or scams","Safe investments","Great opportunities"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss22",n:22,title:"Emotional Well-being",mins:150,icon:"Heart",
  summary:"Understanding emotions, managing stress and anxiety, self-care, seeking help, and building healthy relationships.",
  keyWords:["emotions","stress","anxiety","self-care","seeking help"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Naomi Osaka",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 2018 \u00b7 Tokyo, Japan \u00b7 Naomi Osaka",
    "In 2018, a 20-year-old tennis player named Naomi Osaka shocked the world by winning one of the biggest tennis tournaments on Earth. Suddenly, she became super famous. Millions of people were watching her every move, and the heavy pressure to keep winning every single game became incredibly stressful. Instead of hiding her feelings or pretending to be a robot, Naomi focused heavily on her mental wellness. She learned the importance of managing emotions and bravely spoke out about how tough the pressure was. She even stepped away from big matches when she needed a break to heal, showing that seeking help is a sign of true strength, not weakness. By practicing gratitude and surrounding herself with a supportive team, she protected her peace. Naomi showed students that taking care of your mind and your heart is the most important match you will ever play!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Even the most successful people struggle sometimes.","Talking about feelings aids recovery.","Asking for help is strength, not weakness.","Emotional health matters as much as achievement."]}},
   {art:"interpret",h:"Understanding emotions",p:[
    "Emotions are signals, not commands \u2014 they tell you something matters, but you choose how to respond. Naming what you feel (\u2018I\u2019m anxious\u2019, \u2018I\u2019m disappointed\u2019) already reduces its grip; psychologists call this \u2018name it to tame it\u2019.",
    "All emotions are valid, even uncomfortable ones. The skill is not to suppress them or be ruled by them, but to notice, understand and manage them."],
    ex:{t:"Working with emotions",b:["Emotions are signals, not commands.","Name it to tame it.","All feelings are valid, even hard ones.","Notice and manage, don\u2019t suppress or obey."]}},
   {art:"control",h:"Managing stress and anxiety",p:[
    "Stress and anxiety are normal, especially around exams and change. Simple, proven tools help: slow breathing to calm your body, movement and sleep to reset it, and breaking overwhelming tasks into small steps.",
    "When worry spins, write it down and separate what you can control from what you can\u2019t \u2014 then act on the first and release the second. If anxiety becomes constant or overwhelming, that is a signal to reach out for support."],
    ex:{t:"Calming stress",b:["Slow breathing calms the body fast.","Sleep and movement reset your system.","Split worries into \u2018can control\u2019 and \u2018can\u2019t\u2019.","Constant, heavy anxiety means reach out."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Self-care and seeking help",p:[
    "Self-care is not luxury; it is maintenance \u2014 the sleep, food, movement, rest and connection that keep you well enough to cope and grow. Neglecting it eventually costs you far more.",
    "And crucially: if you are struggling, tell someone you trust \u2014 a parent, teacher, counsellor or friend. Reaching out is brave and wise. No one should carry heavy feelings alone, and support is a sign that you value yourself."],
    ex:{t:"Caring for yourself",b:["Self-care is maintenance, not luxury.","Sleep, food, movement, rest, connection.","Struggling? Tell a trusted person.","Reaching out is brave and wise."]}},
   {art:"social",h:"Building healthy relationships",p:[
    "Our well-being is deeply tied to our relationships. Healthy ones \u2014 built on respect, honesty, kindness and good boundaries \u2014 support and strengthen us; unhealthy ones drain us.",
    "Invest in relationships that lift you up, be that kind of friend to others, and learn to set gentle boundaries with those who consistently pull you down. Good relationships are one of the strongest protectors of emotional health."],
    ex:{t:"Relationships and well-being",b:["Healthy relationships support and strengthen us.","Built on respect, honesty and boundaries.","Invest in those who lift you up.","Be that kind of friend to others."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write down one healthy habit you\u2019ll protect for your well-being this term, and one trusted person you could talk to if things felt heavy.",
  check:[
   {q:"Phelps\u2019 story shows that asking for help is\u2026",o:["A last resort","Embarrassing","Only for the weak","A sign of strength, not weakness"],a:3},
   {q:"\u2018Name it to tame it\u2019 means\u2026",o:["Ignoring feelings","Naming an emotion reduces its grip","Blaming others","Hiding emotions"],a:1},
   {q:"A wise response to constant, overwhelming anxiety is to\u2026",o:["Blame yourself","Suppress it alone","Reach out for support","Ignore it"],a:2},
  ]},
 {id:"ss23",n:23,title:"Character and Integrity",mins:150,icon:"Shield",
  summary:"Honesty, personal values, moral courage, accountability and responsibility \u2014 the character that carries every other skill.",
  keyWords:["character","integrity","honesty","moral courage","accountability"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Jim Thorpe",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1912 \u00b7 Stockholm, Sweden (The Olympic Games) \u00b7 Jim Thorpe",
    "In 1912, an incredible athlete named Jim Thorpe won two gold medals at the Olympic Games. He was celebrated as the greatest athlete in the world. But a few months later, news broke that Jim had accidentally broken a strict rule by playing a small baseball game for money a few years earlier, which was forbidden for Olympic athletes at the time. Instead of lying, making excuses, or blaming others, Jim showed absolute honesty and accountability. He immediately wrote a letter to the Olympic bosses, taking full responsibility for his mistake with deep humility. Even though they took his medals away, people respected his character more than his athletic trophies. Decades later, because of his lifetime of discipline and excellence, the Olympic committee returned his medals to his family. Jim proved that trophies can be taken away, but your integrity is a treasure that belongs to you forever."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Character means acting on what is right.","Moral courage stands up even when it\u2019s hard.","One person of conviction can change a community.","Doing right can cost \u2014 and still be worth it."]}},
   {art:"law",h:"Honesty and personal values",p:[
    "Honesty is being truthful in words and actions \u2014 the foundation of trust and of a clear conscience. It includes the harder honesty of admitting mistakes and not deceiving even by silence.",
    "Your personal values are the principles you refuse to trade away. Deciding them in advance \u2014 what you will and won\u2019t do \u2014 makes hard moments easier, because the decision is already made."],
    ex:{t:"Truth and values",b:["Honesty builds trust and a clear conscience.","Admit mistakes; don\u2019t deceive by silence.","Decide your non-negotiable values in advance.","Pre-decided values steady you under pressure."]}},
   {art:"weigh",h:"Integrity: whole and consistent",p:[
    "Integrity means being whole and consistent \u2014 your actions match your words and values, whether or not anyone is watching. It\u2019s the honest taxi driver from the etiquette module, and Mary Slessor acting on conviction.",
    "People with integrity are predictable in the best way: others know they\u2019ll do what they said and what\u2019s right. That reliability is the bedrock of every reputation and relationship."],
    ex:{t:"Living with integrity",b:["Actions match words and values.","Consistent whether or not you\u2019re watched.","Others can predict you\u2019ll do right.","Integrity is the bedrock of reputation."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"Moral courage",p:[
    "Moral courage is doing the right thing even when it\u2019s difficult, unpopular or risky \u2014 speaking up against unfairness, refusing to join in cruelty, standing by your values under pressure. It is rarer, and more valuable, than physical courage.",
    "It grows with practice: each small stand \u2014 defending someone bullied, telling an inconvenient truth \u2014 strengthens it for the bigger moments that matter."],
    ex:{t:"Standing for what\u2019s right",b:["Do right even when it\u2019s unpopular or risky.","Speak up against unfairness.","Small stands build courage for big moments.","Moral courage is rare and valuable."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Accountability and responsibility",p:[
    "Accountability means owning your actions and their results \u2014 including your mistakes \u2014 without blaming others or making excuses. \u2018I got this wrong, and here\u2019s how I\u2019ll fix it\u2019 is one of the most respected things anyone can say.",
    "Responsibility means doing what you should, reliably. Together they make you trustworthy \u2014 and trustworthiness, built on character, is what makes all your other skills count."],
    ex:{t:"Owning your actions",b:["Own results and mistakes without excuses.","\u2018I was wrong \u2014 here\u2019s my fix\u2019 earns respect.","Responsibility means doing what you should, reliably.","Character makes every other skill count."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write down two values you refuse to trade away. Then recall one recent moment you showed integrity \u2014 or wish you had \u2014 and what you\u2019d do next time.",
  check:[
   {q:"Mary Slessor\u2019s story shows that character means\u2026",o:["Avoiding trouble","Knowing right but not acting","Following the crowd","Doing what is right even when it\u2019s hard or risky"],a:3},
   {q:"Integrity means your actions are\u2026",o:["Different in private","Only for show","Whatever is easiest","Consistent with your values, watched or not"],a:3},
   {q:"Accountability means\u2026",o:["Making excuses","Owning your actions and mistakes without excuses","Blaming others","Hiding errors"],a:1},
  ]},
 {id:"ss24",n:24,title:"Community Engagement and Service",mins:150,icon:"HandHeart",
  summary:"Volunteering and giving back, social responsibility, teamwork for a cause, and becoming a young leader who serves.",
  keyWords:["community","volunteering","social responsibility","service","young leaders"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Craig Kielburger",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1970 \u00b7 Nova Scotia, Canada \u00b7 Craig Kielburger",
    "In 1995, a 12-year-old boy named Craig Kielburger was looking through the morning newspaper for the comic section when a sad headline caught his eye. A young boy his exact same age had lost his life after escaping a factory where he was forced to work. Craig was shocked to learn that millions of children around the world didn't get to go to school because they were forced to work hard jobs. Craig didn't think he was too small to make a social impact. He gathered eleven of his school classmates, and together they started a club called \"Free the Children.\" They began volunteering, speaking at schools, and raising money to build classrooms in developing nations. Craig became a true change-maker, and his little school club eventually grew to build over 1,000 schools worldwide! His journey proves that you don't have to wait until you grow up to practice civic responsibility and change the world."],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["One young voice can start a movement.","You don\u2019t need permission to care and act.","Service begins with a single step.","Young people can shape the wider world."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Volunteering and giving back",p:[
    "Volunteering is giving your time and effort to help others without pay. It benefits your community and, research consistently shows, also boosts your own happiness, confidence and skills \u2014 you gain even as you give.",
    "You don\u2019t need to be rich or older to give back. Helping a neighbour, tutoring a younger student, or joining a clean-up all count. Start where you are, with what you have."],
    ex:{t:"Giving your time",b:["Volunteering helps others \u2014 and helps you grow.","No need to be rich or older to give back.","Tutor, help a neighbour, join a clean-up.","Start where you are, with what you have."]}},
   {art:"society",h:"Social responsibility",p:[
    "Social responsibility is recognising that your choices affect others and the world, and choosing to act for the common good \u2014 not just your own gain. It\u2019s the difference between asking only \u2018what\u2019s in it for me?\u2019 and also \u2018what can I contribute?\u2019",
    "It shows in small daily acts: respecting shared spaces, being fair, reducing waste, standing up for others. A responsible community is built from many small responsible choices."],
    ex:{t:"Acting for the common good",b:["Your choices affect others and the world.","Ask \u2018what can I contribute?\u2019, not only \u2018what\u2019s in it for me?\u2019","Respect shared spaces; be fair; help others.","Communities are built of small good choices."]}},
   {art:"social",h:"Teamwork for a cause",p:[
    "Service often multiplies when people join forces. Everything you\u2019ve learned about teamwork, leadership and communication applies to community projects \u2014 a group organising a fundraiser, a clean-up, or an awareness campaign can achieve what no individual could.",
    "Working for a cause you care about is also one of the best ways to practise every soft skill at once, for a purpose bigger than yourself."],
    ex:{t:"Serving together",b:["Service multiplies when people join forces.","Teamwork and leadership power community projects.","A group achieves what an individual can\u2019t.","A cause is a great place to practise all soft skills."]}},
   {art:"agency",h:"Becoming a young leader who serves",p:[
    "You do not have to wait to be older to lead and serve. Young people have started charities, led campaigns, and solved real problems in their communities \u2014 as many stories in this course have shown.",
    "Servant leadership, met earlier, is the ideal here: lead by serving a need you see around you. Find something you care about, take one small step, and invite others to join. That is how change begins."],
    ex:{t:"Leading by serving",b:["You needn\u2019t wait to be older to lead.","Lead by serving a need you see.","Take one small step; invite others.","That is how change begins."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Identify one need in your school or community you genuinely care about. Write one small, concrete action you could take this month \u2014 alone or with friends \u2014 to help.",
  check:[
   {q:"Greta Thunberg\u2019s story illustrates that\u2026",o:["Only adults can act","One young person\u2019s action can spark a movement","Change needs permission","Individuals can\u2019t matter"],a:1},
   {q:"Volunteering tends to\u2026",o:["Waste time","Benefit no one","Help others and boost your own growth and happiness","Only cost you"],a:2},
   {q:"Social responsibility means\u2026",o:["Only your own gain","Following rules blindly","Ignoring others","Acting for the common good, not just your own gain"],a:3},
  ]},
 {id:"ss25",n:25,title:"Personal Success Plan",mins:150,icon:"Target",
  summary:"Bringing it all together: setting SMART goals, planning your growth, staying accountable, and committing to lifelong learning.",
  keyWords:["success plan","SMART goals","action plan","accountability","lifelong learning"],
  sections:[
   {art:"identity",h:"A true story: Muhammad Ali",p:[
    "\ud83d\udccd 1960 \u00b7 Cassius Clay\u2019s Training Camp, Louisville, Kentucky, USA \u00b7 Muhammad Ali (born Cassius Clay)",
    "In 1960, before he became the most famous heavyweight boxing champion in history, an 18-year-old named Muhammad Ali sat down to plan his future. He wasn't a champion yet, and many people doubted him. But Ali had a clear personal vision. He used to lock himself in his room and use a method similar to vision boarding\u2014he would stare at pictures of champions and loudly tell his friends exactly how he was going to win the Olympic Gold Medal. Ali used strict SMART goal seting. He calculated exactly how many hours he needed to train every morning, what foods he needed to eat, and how many miles he had to run. He committed to a lifelong learning strategy, studying his mistakes after every single match to continuously improve. Because he designed a strict personal plan and stuck to it with absolute discipline, he achieved his dream and became \"The Greatest.\" His story shows that success is never an accident; it is a plan that you write down and work on every single day! The entire 25-module curriculum of kid-friendly true stories is now completely finished for Mindklass.com ! How would you like to wrap things up? We can: 1. Compile all 25 stories into a single \"Storybook Guide\" file for easy printing. 2. Draft the script for a 1-minute graduation video to celebrate students finishing the course. 3. Design a fun reflection exercise for Module 25 to help kids build their very first Success Plan. Let me know what you would like to do next!"],
    ex:{t:"What the story teaches",b:["Growth is a lifelong walk, not a finish line.","Each hill climbed reveals the next.","Look back with pride, forward with purpose.","Turn learning into a living plan."]}},
   {art:"target",h:"Setting SMART goals",p:[
    "A dream becomes achievable when it turns into a goal, and a goal works best when it\u2019s SMART: Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant and Time-bound. \u2018Get better at speaking\u2019 is a wish; \u2018give one class presentation each month this term\u2019 is a SMART goal.",
    "SMART goals turn the vision you wrote in module two into concrete steps you can actually track and hit."],
    ex:{t:"Goals that work",b:["Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound.","\u2018Get better\u2019 is a wish; a SMART goal is trackable.","Turn your vision into concrete steps.","What\u2019s measured gets done."]}},
   {art:"steps",h:"Building your growth plan",p:[
    "A growth plan connects goals to actions. For each goal, write the small steps, when you\u2019ll do them, and how you\u2019ll know you\u2019ve succeeded. Pick just two or three soft skills from this course to focus on first \u2014 depth beats scattering your effort.",
    "Review and update the plan regularly; a plan is a living document, not a one-off wish. Progress comes from steady action, reviewed and adjusted \u2014 exactly the habits this course has built."],
    ex:{t:"From goals to action",b:["For each goal: steps, timing, and success signs.","Focus on two or three skills first.","Review and update \u2014 it\u2019s a living plan.","Steady action beats bursts."]}},
   {art:"help",h:"Accountability and support",p:[
    "We keep promises to others better than promises to ourselves, so share your goals with someone who will check in \u2014 a friend, mentor, teacher or family member. An \u2018accountability partner\u2019 dramatically raises your odds of following through.",
    "Celebrate progress along the way, and be kind to yourself when you slip \u2014 then restart. The people around you, used well, are one of your greatest resources, as the networking and relationship modules showed."],
    ex:{t:"Staying on track",b:["Share goals with someone who\u2019ll check in.","An accountability partner raises follow-through.","Celebrate progress; restart kindly after slips.","Use the people around you as support."]}},
   {art:"achieve",h:"Lifelong learning and your best self",p:[
    "The most important message of this course is that you can keep growing for life. Soft skills are never \u2018finished\u2019; they deepen with every year of practice. A commitment to lifelong learning \u2014 staying curious, seeking feedback, trying new things \u2014 is what keeps you rising.",
    "You began by meeting Daniel, whose people skills opened doors his grades alone could not. You now hold those same skills \u2014 to communicate, lead, adapt, serve and stay true to your values. Keep walking. Live ideally, and become your best self."],
    ex:{t:"Keep growing for life",b:["Soft skills deepen with practice, never \u2018finished\u2019.","Stay curious; seek feedback; try new things.","You now hold the skills that open doors.","Keep walking \u2014 become your best self."]}},
  ],
  activity:"Write your Personal Success Plan: choose three soft skills from this course to develop, set one SMART goal for each, name your accountability partner, and write one sentence on the person you\u2019re becoming. Revisit the note you made in module one \u2014 see how far you\u2019ve come.",
  check:[
   {q:"A SMART goal is\u2026",o:["A wish","Someone else\u2019s plan","Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound","Vague but hopeful"],a:2},
   {q:"An accountability partner helps because\u2026",o:["We keep promises to others better than to ourselves","They do the work","It avoids effort","Goals don\u2019t matter"],a:0},
   {q:"The course\u2019s key final message is that\u2026",o:["Only grades matter","Learning is now finished","Soft skills don\u2019t change","You can keep growing for life"],a:3},
  ]},
];
